<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Obit-Clarke     03-18 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Clarke,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Army Europe Chief, 4-Star General Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bruce G. Clarke, a retired four-star general
who was the Army commander-in-chief in Europe when Berlin was the
focal point of the Cold War between the United States and the
Soviet Union, has died. He was 86.
   Clarke, who died Thursday at Walter Reed Army Hospital, had
suffered a stroke.
   The McLean, Va. resident was born in Adams, N.Y. He was
graduated from the U.S. Military Academy at West Point, N.Y. in
1925, and he later received a master's degree in civil engineering
from Cornell University and a law degree from La Salle Extension
University.
   During World War II, he commanded the Combat Command A in the
4th Armored Division and later commanded the division. During the
Korean War, he commanded the U.S. I Corps and later the X Corps of
the Far East Command.
   Later, he commanded the U.S. Army in the Pacific, the U.S. 7th
Army in Europe and the Continental Army Command at Fort Monroe, Va.
   He was commander-in-chief of the Army in Europe from 1960 to
1962 and was credited with keeping his troops in a high state of
training and morale while supervising patrols of air and ground
routes to Berlin.
   Clarke devoted himself to Army affairs after retiring in 1962,
writing frequently on matters such as training and command and
making an inspection of Vietnam in 1968.
   His wife, the former Bessie Mitchell, died in 1956.
   He is survived by three sons _ Bruce C. Clarke Jr. of St. Anton
a.d. Jessnitz, Austria; Dr. David A. Clarke of Colorado Springs,
Colo.; and Army Col. Gordon M. Clarke of San Antonio, Texas _ a
daughter, Mrs. Elisabeth Clark of Leesburg, Va.; two sisters, Mary
Griffin of Adams and Frances Saternow of Oswego, N.Y.; 18
grandchildren and five great-grandchildren.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
