<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Dioxin-BirthDefects     03-18 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dioxin-Birth Defects,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Cites Lack of Relationship Between Dioxin and Birth Defects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A six-year study of the largest population ever
contaminated by the toxic chemical dioxin found no apparent
increase in birth defects.
   The study, published in Friday's Journal of the American Medical
Association, focused on babies born in and around Seveso, Italy,
from 1977 through 1982.
   A 1976 chemical accident ata factory in the area released a
cloud of dioxin that contaminated more than 37,200 residents in
Seveso and the neighboring towns of Meda, Cesano Maderno and Desio.
   The study said that if there is any increased risk related to
dioxin, ``the overall risk is unlikely to be large or might be
limited to very rare and specific birth defects.''
   ``Still more important,'' the study concluded, ``is the fact
that no infant with a major malformation was identified in the most
highly contaminated zone.''
   Dioxin, a byproduct of pesticide manufacture, causes cancer in
laboratory animals. It has not been directly linked to cancers in
humans.
   In the Italian study, doctors considered as defects only those
congenital malformations obvious at birth. Congenital problems that
manifest themselves later in life, such as mental retardation, were
not considered.
   The Seveso Congenital Malformations Registry, established
shortly after the accident, found that in 15,291 births, 742
infants were born with deformities, a rate of 48.5 per 1,000.
   The prevalence of deformities over the same period in a nearby
uncontaminated area used as a control was 48.8 per 1,000 births,
the study found.
   The quantity of dioxin released into the environment ``seemed to
be enormous'' but was never precisely determined, according to the
study.
   Levels of dioxin concentration found on the ground in the area
surrounding the factory were nearly 1,000 times higher than the
levels termed safe by state and federal officials after a cleanup
at Times Beach, Mo.
   Times Beach is now deserted and hundreds of families have filed
lawsuits against companies and individuals over their exposure to
dioxin contained in waste oil sprayed on their streets to control
dust in the 1970s.
   Questions about the effects of exposure to dioxin have lingered
since the Vietnam War. Dioxin is in Agent Orange, a defoliant used
during the war.
   Some veterans have sought government compensation, contending
their exposure resulted in cancers, rashes, headaches and other
side effects, as well as birth defects in their children.
   The Veterans Administration has contended numerous studies have
found no link between exposure and reported symptoms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
