<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Church-Libel     03-18 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Church-Libel,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$1.26 Million Overturned; New Protections for Churches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Churches were given increased protection
from libel suits in matters of religious doctrine Thursday when
California's Supreme Court refused to reinstate a $1.26 million
verdict.
   The high court, in a 5-2 vote, refused to hear an appeal by a
woman who sued the Worldwide Church of God after a minister
proclaimed her ``one of the enemies of God's church.''
   The court's action returns the case to Los Angeles Superior
Court for a retrial based on a new legal standard: whether the
minister knew his statements were false, or spoke in reckless
disregard of whether they were false.
   That standard already applied to libel suits filed by public
figures and government officials against newspapers and other news
media.
   In a precedent-setting decision that now has statewide effect, a
lower appeals court said the freedom of religion requires the same
constitutional protections to churches and their officials when
discussing religious doctrine.
   The suit was filed by Leona McNair of Pasadena, former wife of
Raymond McNair, deputy chancellor of the church-run Ambassador
College.
   She was a prominent church member who later became associated
with a dissident faction and was divorced by McNair in 1976 after
20 years of marriage.
   The court said their divorce and McNair's remarriage the next
year prompted criticism within the church, which recognizes divorce
in only a few instances.
   In a 1979 speech to about 1,000 people at the church's annual
meeting in Tucson, Ariz., Roderick Meredith, the church's director
of pastoral administration, sought to explain why the McNair
divorce was justified by ``desertion by an unconverted mate,'' one
of(the grounds recognized by the church.
   Mrs. McNair, he said, ``had left the church and was virtually
cursing (McNair) ... spitting literally in people's faces and as
hateful as a human being can be.''
   ``She departed so far that she is one of the major enemies of
God's church in Southern California,''he said.
   Meredith returned to the subject several months later in a
written report, repeating some of his previous accusations and
saying Mrs. McNair had ``refused to be a wife to (McNair) for over
two years'' before the divorce.
   In the suit against the church, Meredith, McNair and others, a
jury found that the statements were false, and that the pastor's
report had caused Mrs. McNair extreme emotional distress.
   The appeals court overturned the verdict because jury was not
asked to find that the statements were intentionally or recklessly
false.
   ``The right to free exercise of religion is a constitutional
guarantee of equal significance'' to freedom of the press, the
appeals court said, adding that Meredith's remarks, however
personal, ``were made while he was explaining church doctrine'' on
divorce.
</TEXT>
