<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ACLU-Stalker     03-18 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ACLU-Stalker,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Reins In Police Search For Sexual-Assault Suspect</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city agreed Thursday to restrict police
in their search for a sexual-assault suspect after the Police
Department was accused in an ACLU suit of detaining hundreds of
black men without cause.
   The agreement, signed by city attorneys and the American Civil
Liberties Union, prohibits officers from detaining anyone merely
because he matches the race or age of the man suspected of
attacking eight women in the past five weeks.
   However, the agreement allows police to stop anyone to seek
their voluntary cooperation in the investigation.
   A similar dispute involving a Police Department dragnet in an
Hispanic neighborhood ended with the city paying a $45,000
settlement to about 80 people in 1985.
   Barry Steinhardt, executive director of the ACLU in
Pennsylvania, applauded the agreement, saying Police Commissioner
Kevin Tucker recognized that the investigation ``should not become
the occasion for the random mass questioning of black
Philadelphians.''
   In the suit filed earlier Thursday, the ACLU sought a federal
court injunction to prevent police ``from stopping, frisking,
questioning and detaining'' black men in the search for the
so-called Center City Stalker.
   The suit, filed on behalf of two men, charges that several
hundred men were questioned without probable cause.
   Attorneys for the ACLU and Deputy City Soliciter Ralph Teti met
Thursday with U.S. District Judge James McGirr Kelly, who approved
the agreement.
   ACLU Legal Director Stefan Presser said: ``We do believe that a
large number of people were illegally detained and we will now
pursue the question of damages.''
   Teti could not be reached for comment Thursday night.
   Earlier in the day, the police commissioner defended the conduct
of the police.
   ``Obviously, our feeling is we have a composite (sketch) and we
feel we're following proper guidelines,'' Tucker said. ``If the
courts think we're doing things differently, then we will abide by
their ruling.''
   The Center City Stalker has generally approached victims leaving
an elevator an empty hall. With a gun, he has directed victims into
an empty room, robbed them, tied their hands hands and ankles and
sexually assaulted them.
   The attacks have created fear among women in downtown office
buildings, leading to an increase in the sale of chemical Mace.
   In 1985, police questioned 125 Hispanics after a police officer
was shot to death in his patrol car in an Hispanic neighborhood.
   A federal judge ordered the department to stop the ``disgraceful
activities'' and ``unlawful conduct'' in rounding up Hispanics
indiscriminately, and the city later agreed to a monetary
settlement.
</TEXT>
