<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 0225EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-82ndHistory     03-18 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-82nd History,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>82nd Airborne Designed to Cool Global Hot Spots</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FORT BRAGG, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army's 15,000-soldier 82nd Airborne
Division is a troubleshooting unit for handling hot spots around
the world.
   ``The division is used as kind of a fire department _ a unit
that can move quickly into an emergency, bring with it the tools
and techniques to put out fires and restore order,'' military
writer Hans Halberstabt said in his 1988 book, ``Airborne: Assault
from the Sky.''
   Here's a brief history of the 82nd Airborne Division:
   _ 1917: The 82nd is activated at Camp Gordon, Ga., but
discontinued in 1919.
   _ 1942: The 82nd is reactivated under Gen. Omar Bradley at Camp
Claiborne, La. The first airborne unit is trained here in
preparation for combat. All five combat airborne divisions, the
82nd, 101st, 11th, 13th and 17th, are trained in the Fort
Bragg-Camp McCall area.
   _ 1943: The division is deployed to North Africa.
   _ July 9, 1943: Paratroopers from the 82nd Airborne Division
make their first jump in Sicily.
   _ June 6, 1944: Paratroopers from the division, along with the
101st Division, lead the charge in the invasion at Normandy.
   _ 1944: The 82nd paratroopers participate in the Battle of the
Bulge.
   _ 1945: Division ordered to Berlin for occupation duty.
   _ 1946: 82nd returns to the United States and is assigned to
Fort Bragg, N.C.
   _ 1965: Division deployed to Santa Domingo in the Dominican
Republic to evacuate Americans.
   _ 1968-1970: Division's 3rd Brigade sent to Vietnam.
   _ 1983: Two brigades of 82nd Airborne Division sent to Grenada
to rescue American medical students.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
