<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Witnesses 2ndLd-Writethru a042licansAgreeToDropLawsuitsToOustL</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Witnesses, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0420,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Journalists Watch as Jets from Honduras Bomb Border Area</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs `The bombs ... banana trees.' with 2 grafs
to CLARIFY where bombs fell. PICKS up 6th graf pvs, `The
journalists ....' DELETES first reference to Carrion in 12th graf
pvs `Lt. Col Javier...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANDRES DE BOCAY, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan officials
apparently wanted to show reporters how quiet this jungle-covered
border region was when they flew them here Thursday, following a
major offensive against Contra rebels.
   But as officials were briefing about 25 journalists at a
military base, two unidentified jet planes from Honduras roared
into Nicaraguan territory and dropped bombs along the border.
   The reporters dived into the dirt for cover. No one was hurt.
   Some military officials in Nicaragua described the planes as
French-made Mysteres, while others said they were U.S.-made F-5s.
The Honduran air force has both.
   The bombs landed along the Coco River, which marks the border
between the two countries. Puffs of black smoke curled over the
banana trees.
   Lt. Col. Javier Carrion, the deputy chief of the Sandinista
army's general staff, said two bombs landed in Nicaraguan territory
and one in Honduras.
   The journalists' briefing came after Reagan administration
officials had claimed that Nicaraguan troops had penetrated
Honduran territory in pursuit of the U.S.-backed rebels. Nicaragua
and Honduras share a long, ill defined border.
   As the jets roared in Thursday, drowning out the lapping of the
slow-moving river and the chirping of crickets, journalists and
soldiers threw themselves against the earth.
   Some of the bombs exploded about 70 yards away from where they
lay.
   Maj. Rosa Pasos, the Defense Ministry spokeswoman, lost her
eyeglasses in the weeds but quickly found them. She wore an
American-made uniform that had apparently been taken from a Contra
rebel.
   The Sandinistas opened fire at the planes with anti-aircraft
guns. They apparently didn't hit either of them.
   None of the five Soviet-made helicopters used in this area 175
miles from Managua was hit. In Washington, sources who spoke on
condition of anonymity claimed that one Soviet-made helicopter on
the ground had been damaged. The Soviet Union supplies the
Sandinistas with military hardware and training.
   Carrion, who had been conducting the offensive against the
Contras, said that jets had buzzed the Coco River earlier in the
day.
   Asked whether Sandinista troops had crossed the border in their
offensive, Carrion replied, ``Well, no.''
   ``There are sectors in the mountains here where you can get
lost. It's easy to confuse the topography.''
   However, Carrion displayed a map showing where Sandinista troops
had destroyed Contra camps along a six-mile route on both sides of
the Coco River.
   Thursday's attack came hours after 3,200 American troops arrived
in Honduras in a show of force.
   Nicaraguan officers said the air attack appeared to be aimed at
harassing the Sandinistas.
</TEXT>
