<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Trade     03-18 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Potatoes and Plywood: Home State Concerns Dominate Trade Session</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators are pressing the Reagan
administration with a host of worries about how plywood, potatoes
and other home-state products would fare under the U.S. and
Canadian agreement to phase out tariffs.
   The outpouring of concern came Thursday at a Senate Finance
Committee session with Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III and
U.S. Trade Representative Clayton K. Yeutter.
   Dropping potato tariffs under the plan will magnify the
importance of Canadian potato subsidies and a Canadian ban on Maine
potatoes, declared Sen. George J. Mitchell, D-Maine.
   ``Will you gentlemen explain to me and Maine potato farmers why
this agreement is good for them?'' Mitchell said.
   ``Before I fully support a free-trade agreement, I must make
sure that it will not hurt coal,'' said Sen. Jay Rockefeller,
D-W.Va.
   ``We're being moved out of their markets'' even without the
agreement, said Sen. David Durenberger, R-Minn. ``And it is wheat,
and it is potatoes and it is corn.''
   Sen. Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich., said that of the nation's
$13 billion trade deficit with Canada last year ``nearly half of
that is in auto and truck activity.''
   ``I must say to you that I have very serious reservations about
that section of the treaty,'' Riegle said.
   Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, told the
administration officials that they must not merely dismiss the
questions as narrow concerns that skirt the big picture.
   Baker declared that the agreement ``is in the national economic
interest or we wouldn't have sent it up here for approval.''
   ``It is unlikely that we'll ever negotiate a utopian
agreement,'' Yeutter said.
   Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., called for approval of the
U.S.-Canada treaty, but he expressed concern that Canada already
has violated the agreement by failing to retest U.S. plywood that
Canada says cracks in extreme cold.
   ``They're used in Nome, they're used on the North Slope (in
Alaska),'' he said. ``They don't crack where they're used.''
   And Bentsen expressed impatience when Yeutter said energy
provisions of the agreement will be valuable to the United States
``in the long run.''
   The oil-state senator, who has been concerned about sagging
petroleum prices, replied that ``in the long run we'll all be
dead.''
   ``I'm concerned about what's happening while we're all still
around here,'' Bentsen said. ``I have a state that's in a
depression.''
</TEXT>
