<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Candidates-Money     03-18 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Candidates-Money,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidates Face New Round Of Fund-Raising</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With some of the most expensive campaign
states coming up, the presidential candidates are pressing
fund-raising appeals anew and only George Bush is out of the
financial woods.
   After costly excursions into the 20 Super Tuesday states on
March 8, the candidates now face money-draining states like New
York, Pennsylvania, California and Ohio.
   Bush has almost finished raising as much money as he can legally
spend, and still has more than $4 million available to spend at
this time, a spokeswoman said. GOP rival Pat Robertson has spent
nearly to the $27 million limit and has to dramatically scale back
his campaign.
   Among Democrats, Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois and Rep. Richard
Gephardt of Missouri both are looking for enough cash to keep their
campaigns afloat beyond caucuses on March 26 in Michigan and
primaries March 29 in Connecticut and April 5 in Wisconsin.
   The Democratic money leader, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis,
has an active April fund-raising schedule, and remains in good
financial shape, his campaign said.
   Democrat Jesse Jackson, whose fund-raising has trailed that of
opponents, has been picking up money through an aggressive mail
program, and will appeal for money in California this weekend.
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr.'s campaign is ``in the black'' and has ``a
sufficient amount of money to do what we need to do,'' said
spokesman Arlie Schardt.
   ``We're in good solid shape,'' Schardt said, but declined to
give any specifics. Gore borrowed heavily for pre-Super Tuesday TV
ads.
   Bush plans to shut down his fund-raising operation by the end of
April, after a handful of high-ticket dinners and one final mailing
to his faithful contributors, said campaign treasurer Fred Bush,
who is no relation to the candidate.
   At that point Bush will have raised the $27 million, plus
another $2 million or so for legal and accounting costs, which are
exempt from the limit. However, he has not spent the limit, so he
can continue campaigning.
   As Bush continues the road to all-but-certain nomination this
summer, people are flocking to give him money and two dozen had to
be refused tickets to a $1,000-a-person dinner at a private home
this week, the treasurer said.
   Robertson is in a different situation, having spent nearly the
limit. He says he will rely heavily on volunteer efforts to see him
through the rest of the campaign.
   Sen. Bob Dole's spokeswoman, Dale Tate, said the Kansas
Republican's poor showing on Super Tuesday and in Illinois did not
result in a dramatic decrease of contributions, although, ``We're
not bathing in dollars.''
   Conversely, contributors have been calling to urge Dole to stay
in the race, she said.
   On Friday, callers pledged $140,000, on Monday $95,000 and on
Tuesday $60,000, she said, adding, ``These are Republicans saying
we think there should be a race.''
   Dukakis spokesman Mark Gearan said the campaign raised $100,000
Wednesday night in New York, and is getting financial mileage out
of the candidate's strong Super Tuesday showing.
   Dukakis has about $1.5 million in the bank, not counting the
more than $600,000 he got this week in federal matching funds, said
spokesman Leslie Dach.
   Simon and Gephardt, who face uphill struggles in fund-raising
after their poor Super Tuesday showings, both said they are out of
debt at this point.
   Both also said they had record fund-raising months in February _
Gephardt collecting $1.2 million and Simon more than $900,000.
   And Gephardt spokesman Mark Johnson said, ``It's a day-to-day
thing.'' He said the campaign was aggressively seeking money, and
Gephardt was putting in personal calls to contributors.
   Gephardt is targeting Michigan for a heavy advertising campaign,
but Johnson said he has no idea whether any loans will be taken out.
   Simon spokesman David Carle said the campaign, which has scaled
back its payroll and operations, had around $300,000 in cash on
hand.
   Simon collected about $60,000 at a Chicago event Monday night,
and expected to bring in another $25,000 Thursday night in New
York, he said.
   A mailing to Simon's 50,000 contributors will go out next week,
and unsolicited donations came in following Simon's victory in his
home state of Illinois, Carle said. He declined to give specific
figures.
   Simon will strongly contest Wisconsin with a large television
campaign, but will not buy ads in Michigan, he said.
</TEXT>
