<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Colombia-Plane Bjt   03-18 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Colombia-Plane, Bjt,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>137 Killed, Jetliner Crashes Into Mountain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CUCUTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Avianca jetliner smashed into a
mountain minutes after takeoff, triggered a landslide and burst
into flames, killing all 137 people aboard, officials and witnesses
said.
   Among the 131 passengers were a Roman Catholic auxiliary bishop
and more than 30 soccer players, officials said. There were no
Americans aboard, they said.
   The Boeing 727 clipped trees before hitting the snow-covered
mountain 50 miles away near Zulia, witnesses said.
   The craft took off in heavy fog at 1:16 p.m. Thursday from
Cucuta, 250 miles northeast of Bogota, on a domestic flight to the
Caribbean port of Barranquilla.
   Rescue workers who reached the wreckage Thursday night said
there were no survivors, Col. Miguel Benedetti, civil defense
director for the state of North Santander, said in a interview by
radio-telephone from Zulia.
   ``The impact of the plane against the mountain was so violent
that it caused a landslide which buried part of the aircraft,''
said Benedetti.
   Work crews, some using helicopters, were to return to the crash
site today, said Col. Edgar Lozano, spokesman for the Civil
Aeronautics Agency. Rain, snow and rough terrain hampered rescue
efforts Thursday.
   Airport officials lost radio contact with the plane four minutes
after it took off, although no problems had been reported up to
that point, said Lozano.
   Lozano said the plane apparently was unable to get enough
altitude to fly over the 8,000-foot mountain.
   Zulia police said three witnesses reported that the plane
clipped some trees, then slammed into the mountain and burst into
flames.
   ``We heard a tremendous noise ... and ran toward the mountain
where we saw the ruins of the plane,'' said Victor Pineda
Villamizar, a schoolteacher, in an interview with the radio network
RCN.
   He said local rescuers could not reach the crash site because of
the rough terrain.
   Avianca and the government air agency reported the plane was
carrying 131 passengers and six crew members. They both had had
given different numbers earlier.
   The agency said the passenger list included Monsignor Horacio
Olave Velandia, 44, who was named auxiliary bishop of Tibu in
February, and at least 31 soccer players from two teams who were
flying to a tournament in Cartagena.
   The soccer teams were affiliated with the state petroleum
company Ecopetrol.
   Colombia's last major air crash occurred July 27, 1985, when an
air force transport plane went down in the Amazon jungle, killing
74 people. The military plane was carrying civilian passengers
because of an airline strike.
</TEXT>
