<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Contra-Talks     03-18 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra-Talks,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contra Leader: Peace Talks Off Unless Sandinistas Leave Honduras</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peace talks scheduled to begin Monday between the
Contra rebels and the Nicaraguan government are off unless
Sandinista troops withdraw from Honduras, a Contra leader says.
   ``If this situation does not take a radical turn, we will not
attend,'' Aristides Sanchez, a member of the five-person
directorate of the Nicaraguan Resistance, said Thursday. The group
has its headquarters in Miami.
   Sanchez said the Contras would attend the meeting only if the
Sandinistas withdraw at once from Honduras. ``There could be
changes in the next four days, but I doubt they will be positive,''
he said.
   Nicaraguan government officials maintain their troops didn't
advance into Honduras, but the Reagan administration claims they
did and dispatched 3,200 American soldiers to Honduras because of
their presence.
   The Sandinista government of Daniel Ortega and Contra
representatives are scheduled to begin three days of talks Monday
in Sapoa, a town in southern Nicaragua near the border with Costa
Rica.
   If Monday's meeting is held, it will be the first on Nicaraguan
soil between the two sides.
   A Contra spokeswoman in Miami said intense fighting continued
Thursday with 2,000 Sandinista troops still in Honduras.
   ``The intention of the Sandinistas was to weaken our position at
the negotiating table,'' Marta Sacasa said. ``It's also timed to
coincide with the end of United States aid.''
   Preliminary reports indicated 10 Contra rebels were killed and
56 wounded in the Sandinista offensive, she said.
   ``They have been able to overrun certain of our positions and we
have had to disperse,'' Ms. Sacasa said. ``We're trying to avoid a
frontal engagement and rely on guerrilla tactics.''
   Contra leaders had no comment on the American troops airlifted
to Honduras in a show of support for the Central American nation,
Ms. Sacasa said.
   ``The United States troops did not go to Honduras to involve
themselves with the fighting in any way, so we have no comment,''
she said.
</TEXT>
