<HEAD>Dollar Up Sharply, Stocks Higher In Early Tokyo Trading.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grfs to UPDATE with closing figuers. PICKS up
2nd graf pvs bgng, ``The opening jump...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose sharply and stock prices
continued to rally Friday as traders in Tokyo reacted to favorable
economic reports.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues finished the day's trading at 25,966.26 points, up
93.97 points, or 0.36 percent, from Thusday's closing figure.
   The dollar closed at 128.35 yen, up 0.92 yen from Thursday's
close, but down from its 128.65-yen opening.
   ``The opening jump was in reaction to sharp rises in the dollar
recorded on the New York and London markets due to the U.S. trade
figures,'' said a foreign exchange dealer, who requested anonymity,
with a major bank.
   Another dealer, who also asked not to be named, said the dollar
later receded because of selling pressure from exporters and
insurance companies.
   Figures released Thursday in Washington by the U.S. Commerce
Department indicated the U.S. trade deficit for January rose to
$12.44 billion from $12.2 billion the previous month. But although
the gap widened by 1.9 percent, imports to the United States
declined by 6 percent during the month.
   Improvements in the U.S. trade deficit reduce the pressure for a
weaker dollar, which has been a key weapon in the Reagan
administration's attempts to narrow the imbalance.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average index of
225 selected issues closed the morning session at 25,911.10 points,
up 38.81 from Thursday's close. Volume in the first section was
estimated at 750 million shares.
   The early gains on the Nikkei average followed three consecutive
closing rallies that brought the index to a level higher than that
just prior to the October crash.
