<2ND_LINE>PM-Shamir Visit,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Urges American Jews to Stand behind Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir urged
American Jews to close ranks behind Israel as it tries to quell
riots by Palestinians in the occupied territories of the West Bank
and the Gaza Strip.
   ``When unity breaks down, then our enemies exploit every
critical statement to their own end,'' Shamir said to enthusiastic
applause from 1,600 American Jews at a fund-raising banquet on
Thursday.
   He apparently referred to criticism by some Jews of the Israeli
Army's use of beatings and live ammunition to quell riots in the
occupied territories. At least 100 Palestinians have been killed in
more than three months of violence.
   Shamir also warned Israel's supporters not to compare the
Palestinian protests to a civil rights struggle.
   ``These are not passive civil rights marches. These are another
expression of the Arab refusal to accept Israel, to coexist with
us, and to recognize that Israel is a permanent feature in the
region,'' Shamir said.
   ``If there were some excesses, they were isolated cases that
were blown way out of proportion by the media,'' he added.
   Those attending the $60-a-plate benefit at the Century Plaza
Hotel agreed to pledge at least $1,000 to either the United Jewish
Fund or Israel Bonds during the coming year.
   Earlier Thursday, at a ceremony dedicating a cornerstone for a
museum commemorating the Holocaust, Shamir told about 1,500 people
that Americans and Europeans may wrongly interpret the Arab
rebellion.
   ``They cry, `Palestine is Arab,' and openly declare that all of
Palestine is theirs,'' he said.
   Shamir also was scheduled to address a luncheon meeting today of
the Los Angeles World Affairs Council. He is scheduled to leave Los
Angeles on Saturday evening.
   The prime minister, fresh from his meeting with President
Reagan, Secretary of State George P. Shultz, and congressional
leaders in Washington, reiterated his opposition to an American
plan for peace in the Middle East that calls for an international
conference.
</TEXT>
