<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-StPatrick's     03-18 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-St Patrick's,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan, Wright Exchange St. Patrick's Day Toasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan toasted ``Seamus Wright''
among other adversaries during a Capitol Hill luncheon after paying
a surprise visit to a tavern in a celebration of St. Patrick's Day.
   Standing Thursday at a table covered with a green cloth and
decorated with green carnations, the president wished House Speaker
Jim Wright ``warm words on a cold evening and a full moon on a dark
night.''
   Wright, who wore a green jacket and green tie, declared that
``we've buried all differences that might exist between political
parties and branches of government on this day of St. Patrick.'' He
toasted Reagan, 77, for his youthfulness.
   Wright's great-grandmother, Grace Hannington, emigrated from
County Dungannon, Ireland, in 1837. The Irish for James is Seamus.
   Reagan traces his Irish roots to his great-great-grandfather,
Michael O'Regan, who left County Tipperary during the potato famine
of the 1840s.
   Before he arrived at the Capitol, Reagan paid a surprise visit
to Ireland's Own, a noisy pub in suburban Alexandria, Va., where he
sipped beer and sampled corned beef and cabbage with columnist
James J. Kilpatrick.
   The president, a moderate drinker, left most of the beer in his
glass, but joined the tavern crowd in singing ``When Irish Eyes Are
Smiling,'' and clapping to guitar and fiddle music.
   Reagan, who like most presidents is seldom seen handling money,
reached in his pocket for some currency and paid his own check when
he left.
   On a more serious note, Reagan issued a statement urging
concerned Americans to refuse financial or moral support to Irish
terrorists.
   ``Northern Ireland continues to suffer from senseless violence,
which tragically we have seen repeated in recent days, and high
unemployment,'' he said.
   ``We can best address these problems by supporting those who
seek peaceful settlements to disputes, and rejecting those who seek
solutions through terror.''
   Meantime, members of Congress commemorating St. Patrick's Day
said Britain's refusal to prosecute certain cases of criminal
conduct by its forces in Northern Ireland is ``intolerable'' and
tarnishes Britain's international reputation.
   ``We call on the British government to prosecute any member of
the security forces who has engaged in criminal conduct in Northern
Ireland,'' said a statement issued by Friends of Ireland in
Congress, a 160-member bipartisan group.
   ``It is intolerable not to pursue and bring to justice
individuals known to have perverted justice.''
   The statement did not mention a recent string of violent
incidents that started March 6 when British troops in Gibraltar
killed three unarmed Irish Republican Army guerrillas who allegedly
were on a bombing mission.
   Another congressional group, the Ad Hoc Congressional Committee
for Irish Affairs, which includes 41 House and Senate members from
both parties, called for a new investigation of the Royal Ulster
Constabulary, the British police force in Northern Ireland.
   Both groups urged Britain to enact laws to help stop
discrimination against the Roman Catholic minority in Northern
Ireland that has resulted in jobless rates of more than 50 percent
among Catholic men in some areas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
