<1ST_LINE>r p PM-KansasDemocrats     03-18 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kansas Democrats,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic Caucuses Set Saturday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Democratic presidential hopefuls _ who
also are the leaders in the national delegate race _ were
campaigning in Kansas, which holds county caucuses on Saturday.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson were
campaigning today in the state, a day after a foray by Tennessee
Sen. Albert Gore Jr.
   At Saturday's caucuses, local delegates will be elected to
district conventions April 23 and the state convention May 2. At
the district and state conventions, 39 of Kansas' 43 national
delegates to the Democratic convention in Atlanta in July will be
elected.
   The candidates who win the most local delegates Saturday will
claim the national delegates at the later conventions. Four state
party leaders automatically are national delegates.
   Gore, the first of the Democratic contenders to come to Kansas
ahead of the caucuses, scored something of a coup Thursday when he
was invited to address the state House of Representatives and
gained a qualified endorsement from state Democratic Party Chairman
Jim Parrish.
   Dukakis was speaking at a rally in the Capitol rotunda today,
then holding a Statehouse news conference. Jackson scheduled a
speech at Washburn University and another at Wichita State
University.
   Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt has the support of Kansas' two
Democratic U.S. House members, Dan Glickman and Jim Slattery, but
has not campaigned here in advance of the caucuses. Illinois Sen.
Paul Simon, who is strapped for cash and concentrating on races in
Michigan and Wisconsin, made little effort here.
</TEXT>
