<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Commonwealth-Extortion     03-18 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Commonwealth-Extortion,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Commonwealth Officials Indicted on Extortion Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAIPAN, Northern Mariana Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Republican Party
chairman of this U.S. commonwealth and five other people connected
to the government were charged by a federal grand jury with
extorting money from businessmen.
   Among those named in two indictments returned Thursday were the
party chairman, Jesus Mafnas, a government personnel officer;
commonwealth Rep. Mariano Bermudes; former commonwealth Senate
president Ponciano Rasa and his brother, Oscar Rasa, publisher of
the now-defunct Commonwealth Examiner newspaper.
   Also indicted were former Senate legal counsel James Doerty and
former Senate employee Leo Pangelinan.
   One indictment accused Mafnas of soliciting and receiving a
$22,760 bribe in 1986 from Adrian Johnston, owner of the Surf Hotel.
   In exchange for the money, Mafnas guaranteed that the Marianas
Public Land Corp. would grant the hotel a lease for a piece of
public beachfront land located next to the hotel, the indictment
said.
   In the second indictment, the Rasa brothers, Pangelinan,
Bermudes and Doerty were accused of demanding payments of $222,000
in 1983 from Sumitomo Corp. and subsequently receiving $113,000 in
bribes from the Japanese construction company.
   According to the indictment, the five conspired to force
Sumitomo to pay a 1 percent commission on all Northern Marianas
business awarded the company.
   Mafnas and Bermudes were each charged with one count of
extortion. The Rasa brothers were each charged with two counts of
extortion, while Doerty and Pangelinan each faced three counts of
extortion. Mafnas also was charged with one count of conspiracy to
commit extortion.
   At the request of assistant U.S. Attorney George Proctor, U.S.
District Judge Alfred Laureta set bail for Mafnas, Ponciano Rasa,
Pangelinan and Bermudes at $25,000 each. Laureta also issued arrest
warrants for Oscar Rasa and Doerty, who now live in California.
   Arraignment was set for March 25.
   Bermudes had no comment on the indictment, Pangelinan and
Mafanas have unlisted numbers and could not be reached for comment
and Ponciano Rasa did return a telephone call to his home, the
Pacific Daily News reported.
</TEXT>
