<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CoastGuard-Drugs     03-18 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Coast Guard-Drugs,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Pushes For $60 Million Transfer For Coast Guard Patrols</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe cutbacks are devastating the Coast
Guard's drug interdiction and search and rescue operations, the
agency's chief said in asking Congress for an immediate transfer of
$60 million from other accounts.
   ``We have Coast Guard cutters sitting at docks and planes on the
runways,'' said Adm. Paul A. Yost, commandant of the Coast Guard.
``Congressional approval of the reprogramming request would let us
put those ships and planes back to work patrolling the high seas.''
   President Reagan on Thursday asked Congress to transfer money
from highway, mass transit and Amtrak funds to restore the patrols,
which were ordered cut back by the administration last month to
help make up for a $103 million budget shortfall.
   The Coast Guard eliminated routine search and rescue patrols,
cut drug patrols by 55 percent, eliminated 1,100 jobs, closed down
nearly 30 Coast Guard installations and severely reduced other
stations.
   None of the jobs or installations would be restored with the $60
million. That money would be devoted exclusively to restoring
patrol levels to their pre-cutback levels, Yost said.
   Before the cutbacks, Yost said, 90 percent of the agency's drug
seizures came from routine patrols. Last year, $3 billion in
cocaine alone was seized by the Coast Guard, he said.
   The commandant said it was too early to quantify the cutback's
impact on drug seizures or rescue missions, but he predicted it was
heavy.
   Yost said he and Transportation Secretary James Burnley
conferred with lawmakers before making the recommendations.
   ``I will do everything I can to work with Congress to get it
passed,'' Yost said.
   The request would not increase overall spending since the money
is already appropriated.
   Under the administration's plan, $25.3 million would come from
Federal Highway Administration funds that are not earmarked for
specific projects; $17.3 million from mass transit grants; $12.4
million from a 2 percent reduction in Amtrak's budget; and $5
million from last year's Coast Guard research and development funds.
   Yost said even if Congress approves the administration's budget
proposal for fiscal year 1989 in full _ a $200 million increase
from this year _ there are no plans to reopen the closed
installations or rehire employees.
</TEXT>
