<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 0555EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CleanAir     03-18 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Clean Air,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Of Nine Hopes To Break Committee Deadlock Over Clean Air</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine members of the House Energy and Commerce
Committee have staged a quiet revolution against their chairmen in
an effort to break a six-year logjam that has stalled committee
action on air quality legislation.
   The low-key uprising led by Rep. Al Swift, D-Wash., came to a
seemingly harmonious head Thursday when the self-proclaimed ``Group
of Nine'' unveiled a compromise plan to escalate the battle against
urban pollution.
   Their effort drew applause from the targets of their end-run
around the committee system: Chairman John Dingell, D-Mich., and
Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., chairman of the health and the
environment subcommittee. The details of their plan didn't.
   Swift and his allies effectively took over the committee's air
quality deliberations last December after months of fruitless
wrangling between Dingell and Waxman, the sponsor of an air quality
bill endorsed by environmentalists but deadlocked in his
subcommittee with a 10-10 split.
   ``It's a legislative product,'' Swift told a news conference.
``None of us is happy with every last detail. ... This is a good
piece of environmental policy, and it's cost effective.''
   Their plan in many ways is similar to Waxman's bill and one
produced last year by the Senate Environment Committee but still
awaiting a call to the floor by a major foe, Majority Leader Robert
Byrd, D-W.Va.
   Each proposal calls for stricter emissions controls on industry
and automobiles in an effort to reduce the carbon monoxide and
smog-producing ozone that the Environmental Protection Agency says
have reached unhealthy levels for some 100 million people living in
60 or so metropolitan areas.
   The group's plan, however, would give states and localities more
time to come up with plans to cut pollution, from three to 16
years, depending on the severity of their problems.
   The plan would leave most remedies up to EPA and the states, but
at minimum a city falling short of clean air standards would have
to institute a vehicle inspection and maintenance program.
   Swift and Rep. Dennis Eckart, D-Ohio, said group members would
begin working next week on an acid rain plan, which has also been
divisive.
   Dingell, from an automaking district, has been firm against
calls for cleaner vehicle exhausts, saying the retirement of older
vehicles lacking emissions controls will cause vehicular pollution
to continue to decrease.
   In a prepared statement, Dingell said the Group of Nine plan is
``a vast improvement'' over Waxman's bill and has a ``real
opportunity to gain my full support.''
   Waxman called the proposal a ``very constructive step.''
   Earl Mallich, chairman of industry's Clean Air Working Group,
said the proposed tailpipe standards may not be technologically
achievable. R.G. Ensz, spokesman for the American Petroleum
Institute, said that a proposal to make fuel less evaporative was
not cost effective.
   The Motor Vehicle Manufacturers Association of the United States
said the plan for cleaner exhausts would have imperceptible
benefits to the nation's air.
   Spokesmen for the Sierra Club and Environmental Action said they
were pleased the plan called for tighter controls on industries and
vehicles, but said the pace of controls was too slow.
   Other members of the Swift group are Mike Synar, D-Okla.; Phil
Sharp, D-Ind.; Jim Cooper, D-Tenn.; Jim Slattery, D-Kan.; Bill
Tauzin, D-La.; and Rick Boucher, D-Va.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880318-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 0556EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Israel     03-18 0811</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Israel,810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz`s Deadline Passes With US Plan For Mideast Talks In Doubt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The deadline set by Secretary of State George
P. Shultz for Arab and Israeli replies to his Mideast peace plan is
passing with the outlook for eventual acceptance bleak.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir wound up four days of
talks Thursday critical of Shultz's call for an international
conference.
   He didn't say yes and he didn't say no to the plan, which also
anticipates Israel yielding at least part of the West Bank and Gaza
in exchange for Arab recongition.
   But most of what Shamir had to say during his visit was critical
of the proposal _ especially its call for an international
conference hosted by the United States, the Soviet Union and the
three other permament members of the U.N. Security Council: China,
Britain and France.
   The other major player in the Shultz scenario, King Hussein of
Jordan, has not replied to the U.S. plan. A Jordanian official,
speaking this week in Amman on condition of anonymity, said he
doubted there would be a definitive reponse for 10 days.
   An indication of Arab reservations came Thursday from Clovis
Maksoud, the Arab League's representative here. He criticized the
exclusion of the Palestine Liberation Organization and urged the
United States to demand a total Israeli withdrawal from the West
Bank and Gaza.
   At least 100 Palestinian Arabs have died in a little more than
three months in clashes with Israeli forces. Shultz's proposal
would lead to self-rule for three years, with negotiations on an
overall settlement to begin by December.
   Israel took control of the territories from Jordan and Egypt in
the 1967 Six-Day war. Shamir and other Likud bloc leaders have
vowed not to surrender any of the land.
   Shultz submitted his plan for negotiations two weeks ago to
Israel, Jordan and also Syria, which would be participate in the
talks on an overall settlement. He asked for a reply by mid-March.
   ``As you know, I, in general, think that deadlines are good
things in trying to get people to make up their minds,'' Shultz
told reporters on his Mideast shuttle. ``So we have pointed out the
fact that the situation carries inherent in it a certain sense of
deadlines.''
   And yet, Shultz noted philosophically, ``you can't push people
if they don't want to be pushed.''
   Shamir headed for Los Angeles from Washington. He and the other
senior members of the Israeli Cabinet will take up the U.S.
proposal next Wednesday. A vote by the full Cabinet would be likely
on Sunday, March 27.
   If Israel and Jordan both say ``yes'' by then, the Shultz plan
could take off. But there would be little room, if any, to make
changes.
   President Reagan and Shultz both have ruled out revisions.
Reagan said he would neither ``slice'' the plan apart nor abandon
it. Shultz told the Senate Budget Committee on Thursday, ``The
United States will not permit any aspect of its proposal to be
eroded or compromised.''
   But Shamir clearly is hoping for at least one major change. He
wants to replace the international conference with a ``ceremony''
held by the United States and the Soviet Union. Afterward, Israel
and the Arabs would negotiate directly.
   Shultz is trying to win Shamir over with reassurances.
   He told the Senate committee after a final meeting with the
prime minister that the United States would not attend _ or remain
_ at a conference designed to replace direct Arab-Israeli
negotiations.
   ``The conference will be specifically enjoined from imposing
solutions or vetoing what had been agreed bilaterally,'' Shultz
said.
   Maksoud of the Arab League called, meanwhile, for a U.S.
commitment at the outset of negotiations backing Arab demands that
Israel yield all the territory captured in the 1967 war.
   In a speech, Maksoud also reasserted the Arab position that the
PLO is the sole legitimate representative of Palestinian Arabs.
Some 1.5 million live on the West Bank and Gaza, which were
controlled until 1967 by Jordan and Egypt.
   Shultz's plan does not insist that Israel relinquish all of the
territory. Also, it excludes the PLO from the negotiations.
Palestinians approved by the PLO would be in a delegation with
Jordan.
   Maksoud said an international conference must have the power to
settle disputes between Israel and the Arabs. ``It cannot be a
ceremonial opening, or an event, or some sort of an international
framework,'' he said _ taking direct aim at Shamir's proposal.
   Maksoud also criticized Reagan's appeal to both sides to accept
the U.S. initiative without modification.
   In light of what he called ``bitter Arab experience,'' he said,
``We find ourselves unwilling to be rushed into a timetable
presented on a take-it-or-leave-it basis.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Schweid has reported on Middle East
diplomacy for 15 years.
</TEXT>
