<1ST_LINE>r w PM-LakeThurmond     03-18 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lake Thurmond,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thurmond Won't Help Citizens Restore Original Name To Thurmond
Lake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of people living on the Georgia-South
Carolina line says there's nothing wrong with Strom Thurmond unless
it's the name of a lake shared by the two states.
   The group met privately with the veteran South Carolina
Republican for 35 minutes Thursday to present petitions signed by
42,000 people who want the senator's help in restoring the lake's
original name, Lake Clarks Hill.
   Of the signatures, 30,000 came from the Georgia side, and a
legislative proposal to repeal the new name is sponsored by eight
Democratic congressmen from that state.
   Thurmond said he would stay out of the dispute, which began in
December when Congress renamed the 42-year-old Army Corps of
Engineers lake quickly and with no public hearings.
   ``He told them he feels the matter is settled and since he did
not instigate it or push for it, he feels it would be inappropriate
for him to get involved now,'' press secretary Christopher Simpson
said.
   The meeting also was attended by a group of South Carolina
legislators who want to keep the Thurmond name. ``We're disturbed
that this is going to be an embarrassment to Sen. Thurmond,'' said
state Sen. John Drummond of Greenwood.
   Drummond said the South Carolina lawmakers told the citizens
group that it would be an embarrassment for Thurmond to ``ask the
whole Congress and the president to reverse what they've done.''
   Thurmond himself had nothing to say, referring all questions to
Simpson.
   Roy Giles, a Lincolnton, Ga., restaurant owner and one of the
leaders of ``Keep Our Lake Clarks Hill,'' said the petitions
presented Thursday propose a compromise that would restore the name
of the lake to Clarks Hill but would retain the new Strom Thurmond
name for the dam and road.
   ``Sen. Thurmond will have his monument and the people will have
their lake back,'' Giles said of the compromise, which has been
incorporated into a bill that Rep. Doug Barnard, an Augusta, Ga.,
Democrat, has introduced in the House with the backing of the other
seven Democrats in the Georgia House delegation.
   Giles said he was surprised when the South Carolina lawmakers
showed up at the meeting because Thurmond originally had agreed to
meet privately with representatives of the citizens group opposed
to the name change.
   Giles said the name change will cause financial hardships for
businesses around the lake that have built their reputations using
the Clarks Hill name. And he vowed that the group will continue its
fight, even without Thurmond's help.
   ``We're going to continue to get signatures,'' he said. ``We're
not going to let up. This was just an opportunity to present our
case to Sen. Thurmond and ask for his help.''
</TEXT>
