<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FBI-Rochon     03-18 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FBI-Rochon,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Chief Criticized in Racial Discrimination Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI Director William Sessions is coming under
increasing fire on Capitol Hill in connection with the racial
harassment case of black FBI agent Donald Rochon.
   On Thursday, Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., accused Sessions of
``sidestepping'' and engaging in ``a classic stall'' by promising
to give a full report to Congress at a later date on Rochon and
equal employment matters.
   ``I am frankly deeply disappointed in your lack of candor and
outrage about the terrorism that is going on,'' Conyers said in
referring to the Rochon case and other allegations of
discrimination within the bureau.
   Rochon is suing the FBI and the Justice Department, alleging
racial discrimination, harassment and death threats from fellow
agents and supervisors when he worked at FBI offices in Omaha,
Neb., and Chicago. The federal Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission has upheld Rochon's racial discrimination allegations in
connection with his stay in Omaha in 1983 and 1984.
   ``There has been no sidestepping at all, none,'' responded
Sessions, who has been FBI director for four months.
   He said he was in ``almost total agreement'' with Conyers'
concerns and said he is committed to seeing that the bureau ``is
precisely what it strives to be, an organization which has no
racism.''
   However, Sessions said that with lawsuits pending he cannot
conduct a detailed discussion during this ``awkward period of
time.''
   In addition to the Rochon case, Hispanic agents have filed a
class-action suit in El Paso, Texas, accusing the FBI of racial
discrimination.
   Blacks and Hispanics each make up slightly more than 4 percent
of the bureau's more than 9,000 agents.
   In prepared testimony before the House subcommittee on civil and
constitutional rights, of which Conyers is a member, Sessions said
he has designated executive assistant FBI director John D. Glover,
who is black, to oversee a complete review of equal employment
opportunity matters within the FBI.
   Sessions said Glover ``will report directly to me'' concerning
the Rochon matter and other aspects of the FBI's equal employment
opportunity program including training, handling of complaints,
hiring and promotion policy.
   ``In both cases, I can assure this subcommittee that once these
processes have been completed, I will make a full reporting to
Congress,'' Sessions said.
</TEXT>
