<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Trade-Frenzel     03-18 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade-Frenzel,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Always Glad to Help, Japanese Break Trade Bill Bottleneck</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A frustrated congressman had to turn to the
Japanese Embassy this week to find out exactly what the Senate was
proposing to do on trade legislation.
   ``That is just not the way to do business,'' Rep. Tom Downey,
D-N.Y., said Thursday following a closed-door caucus at which
grievances over the incident got a full-scale airing.
   At the caucus, Rep. William Frenzel, R-Minn., expressed outrage
that he had to rely on the Japanese Embassy to get a copy of the
Senate proposal on how best to crack down on Japanese barriers to
American exports.
   Pat Eveland, Frenzel's administrative assistant, confirmed that
the congressman was disturbed about the delay in transmitting the
Senate report to the House and raised the issue at the closed-door
session.
   ``We think it would be nice if the Senate would decide to give
us the trade offer first before the private sector and the press,''
she said. Frenzel himself was not available to discuss the matter,
she added.
   The document was a compromise offer from Senate members of a
House-Senate conference committee that is trying to merge rival
versions of a 1,000-page trade bill passed by the two houses last
year.
   Among other things, the Senate's offer proposed to erase from
the bill the controversial trade plan sponsored by Democratic
presidential hopeful Richard Gephardt, D-Mo. His plan, calling for
10 percent yearly rollbacks in Japanese trade surpluses, is
contained only in the House version.
   The Senate's alternative proposal would require the U.S. trade
representative to draw up a list of Japanese barriers to American
products and then either negotiate an end to them or retaliate.
   Eveland said she was on the telephone with a Japanese Embassy
official early Wednesday morning, discussing the Senate's offer,
when to her surprise ``it became evident that they had a copy of
it.''
   She said she asked the Japanese for a copy and they immediately
duplicated theirs and sent it by messenger to Frenzel's office on
Capitol Hill. She said a version was not available from the Senate
Finance Committee until 12:30 p.m. Wednesday.
   It remained unclear just how the Japanese managed to obtain
their copy of the offer.
   When Eveland was told that several copies were distributed to
reporters who worked late in the Senate Press Gallery on Tuesday
night, she said, ``Well, now we'll know where to go.''
</TEXT>
