<1ST_LINE>u a PM-LaRoucheTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0492 03-18 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LaRouche Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0492,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Says Kissinger May Testify To Rebut LaRouche Harassment
Claim</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-4, `Kissinger may ..., with 2 grafs to restore
dropped matter; picks up 5th graf: `LaRouche, six ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Henry Kissinger may be called to testify at Lyndon
LaRouche's trial to rebut charges by LaRouche's lawyers that the
government launched a vendetta against the political extremist, a
prosecutor says.
   LaRouche's attorneys, who contend the federal charges against
LaRouche were fabricated, showed the jury letters Thursday in which
Kissinger, as secretary of state, requested an FBI investigation of
LaRouche groups.
   Kissinger may be called to testify that he was a target of
protests and harassment by LaRouche followers and was justified in
seeking the probe, Assistant U.S. Attorney John Markham said.
   LaRouche lawyers said they would welcome an opportunity to
cross-examine Kissinger, whom the fringe politician has labeled a
Soviet spy.
   LaRouche, six aides and five LaRouche organizations are charged
with conspiring to obstruct a grand jury investigation of alleged
credit card and loan fraud by LaRouche's 1984 presidential
campaign. Four of the organizations are charged with fraud.
   Also Thursday, Richard Welsh, an accountant and treasurer with
several LaRouche groups, testified that LaRouche's two campaign
organizations budgeted up to $125,000 a month to pay back credit
card charges that card-holders claimed were unauthorized.
   Prosecutors allege the campaign relied on fraudulent charges to
stay afloat when legitimate fund-raising stalled, knowing it would
take several weeks before unauthorized charges would be deducted
from the campaign's bank account.
   The campaign allegedly misused the charge-card numbers given by
contributors for donations or by people who bought books and other
literature from the LaRouche groups.
   The defendants contend evidence of widespread fraud and
obstruction was fabricated by FBI and CIA infiltrators as part of a
Reagan administration effort to ruin LaRouche and cripple his
highly successful fund-raising.
   Admitted as evidence to the jury Thursday was a series of
letters between Kissinger, then-FBI Director William H. Webster and
Oliver Revell, the FBI's executive assistant director, discussing
LaRouche organizations.
   In an August 1982 letter to Webster, Kissinger complained that
LaRouche supporters had become ``increasingly obnoxious'' in their
criticism of him and asked whether the FBI could investigate
LaRouche groups.
   Revell responded with two letters saying the agency would
investigate Kissinger's complaint and that there appeared to be
some evidence of illegal telephone use by LaRouche supporters to
harass Kissinger.
   No LaRouche followers ever were charged with harassing or
threatening Kissinger.
   The defense contends Revell later directed FBI infiltration of
LaRouche groups at the request of Lt. Col. Oliver North, the former
White House national security aide indicted Wednesday for his role
in the Iran-Contra affair.
   LaRouche contends he has been the target of a 20-year government
vendetta that climaxed in 1984 because of his outspoken criticism
of Reagan's Contra-aid programs.
   Last week, the defense was given two declassified documents, one
a memo to North from another pivotal figure in the Iran-Contra
affair discussing apparent efforts to collect information against
LaRouche.
   The discovery of those documents 60 days into the trial prompted
Keeton to order an extensive search of government records,
including those of the White House and Vice President George Bush,
for any evidence of infiltration or harassment of LaRouche groups.
The searches are expected to be completed by next week.
</TEXT>
