<HEAD>Dole A Winner With Student Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bob Dole, who has taken a beating at the
hands of George Bush in nearly all the Republican presidential
primaries, won hands down among a select group of young voters.
   One hundred and two high school student leaders were asked in
January to name their favorite candidates in both the Republican
and Democratic parties. The students are winners of the Century III
Leaders scholarship program sponsored by the National Association
of Secondary School Principals and Shell Oil Co.
   On the GOP side, the student leaders chose Dole over Bush by 70
percent to 15 percent, with 10 percent naming Pete du Pont, who is
now out of the race, according to survey results released Thursday.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis was the favorite on the
Democratic side, getting 37 percent of the students' votes to 17
percent for Sens. Albert Gore Jr. and Paul Simon, 10 percent for
Bruce Babbitt (now a dropout), 9 percent for Rep. Richard Gephardt
and just 4 percent for Jesse Jackson.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Arab League Envoy Gives Robertson ``Kiss of Death'' Endorsement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Arab League's envoy to the United States
gave what he called ``the kiss of death'' to Pat Robertson's
presidential bid _ an endorsement.
   After a speech Thursday in which he denounced Israel, lauded the
Palestine Liberation Organization and blasted Congress and the
Reagan administration, ambassador Clovis Maksoud was invited to
state his preference in the presidential sweepstakes.
   ``Well, I don't want to say who's the preferred presidential
candidate, because that almost would be the kiss of death, so I
would suggest _ I would suggest Pat Robertson,'' Maksoud said,
provoking laughter from the audience.
   Robertson is an outspoken supporter of Israel.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>N.J. Leader Drops Plan To Send Uncommitted Slate To Democratic
Convention</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AM) _ New Jersey Senate Democratic Leader John
Lynch says he will abandon a proposal to send a slate of
uncommitted delegates to the Democratic National Convention.
   Lynch said Thursday he will drop a movement he headed and bow to
the request of Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J.
   Bradley met with Democratic leaders Wednesday and asked them to
drop their efforts toward an uncommitted slate, saying the drive
could be interpreted outside the state as a movement to back him as
a presidential candidate.
   ``Senator Bradley feels the uncommitted movement would be
perceived as a `stalking horse' for a candidacy at a brokered
convention,'' Lynch said.
   Lynch has said an uncommitted slate could enable New Jersey to
play a decisive role at the convention if no Democratic candidate
wins a majority of delegates in the primaries.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dole Fan Urges Senator To Drop Out Of Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Dole's staunchest New Jersey
supporter, Assembly GOP Leader Chuck Haytaian, says the Kansas
senator should drop out of the race for the Republican presidential
nomination.
   Haytaian, who is chairman of Dole's New Jersey campaign, said
Thursday that Vice President George Bush has the nomination all but
locked up, and Dole ought to face reality.
   ``He knows how to count numbers,'' said Haytaian. ``If he looks
at the delegate numbers for Bush, the numbers should tell him what
to do.''
   Haytaian added he would continue to support Dole as long as he
remains a candidate.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jackson Campaign May Seek Postponement Of S.C. County Conventions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The coordinator of Jesse Jackson's
presidential campaign in South Carolina says he may ask a judge to
postpone Monday's county conventions.
   Kevin Gray said Thursday he is frustrated by the inefficiency of
the Democratic caucus and the absence of delegate lists.
   ``The caucus process is rearing its ugly head,'' said Gray, one
of a growing number of Democrats who believe the party should be
holding a primary.
   Eighteen counties' conventions are meeting Monday and the other
28 counties are meeting March 28. Jackson was the overwhelming
winner at Saturday's 1,788 precinct caucus meetings.
   Gray said it's important to all of the campaigns to have access
to the delegate lists so they can make sure their delegates know
where and when to go to the county conventions and so they can seek
the support of uncommitted delegates.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaRouche Ruled Off Indiana Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political extremist Lyndon LaRouche has been
ruled off Indiana's Democratic presidential primary ballot because
of inadequate petition signatures.
   The State Election Board concluded on Thursday that LaRouche's
supporters had failed to meet the requirements for signatures to
qualify him for the May 3 ballot.
   Indiana law requires 500 signatures from each of the state's 10
congressional districts. The LaRouche petitions met that
requirement in nine districts and had more than 5,000 signatures
overall, but the petitions had only 325 signatures in the 10th
District, according to election board Chairman John R. Whitaker.
</TEXT>
