<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Wedtech     03-18 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness: Meese Friend Got him to Intercede for Wedtech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A close friend of Attorney General Edwin Meese
III said Meese interceded on Wedtech Corp.'s behalf to gain federal
approval for financing, a witness testified at the racketeering
trial of Rep. Mario Biaggi.
   The witness, former Wedtech Vice Chairman Mario Moreno, said
Meese's lawyer and friend, E. Robert Wallach, told him at a 1983
meeting across the street from the White House that Meese had asked
then-Commerce Secretary Malcolm Baldrige to sign the necessary
documents.
   Moreno said Thursday he was told that Baldrige balked at signing
because the matter was ``too hot politically,'' but two or three
days later ``the matter was resolved.''
   Moreno recounted the meeting with Wallach in his third day of
testimony at federal court in Manhattan, where Biaggi and six
others are on trial on charges of turning Wedtech into a
racketeering enterprise through an alleged series of bribery and
extortion schemes.
   Wedtech, a now-bankrupt defense contractor, at the time was
delinquent on two loans of more than $2 million each, one from the
Commerce Department's Economic Development Administration, the
other guaranteed by EDA.
   The company in 1983 wanted EDA approval to refinance the loans
with a new bank.
   But the EDA chief, Assistant Commerce Secretary Carlos Campbell,
resisted pressure from former White House political director Lyn
Nofziger and his lobbying partner, Mark Bragg, to approve the plan.
   Moreno, one of four ex-Wedtech officials who have pleaded guilty
to bribing public officials and other crimes, testified Wallach
``said he was going to a national security meeting at 6 a.m. and
told me to wait in Lafayette Park'' across from the White House.
   Moreno said he saw Wallach enter the White House and when he
emerged two hours later, Wallach ``said he talked to his friend
over there.''
   Moreno said he understood that Wallach's friend was Meese, who
was then presidential counselor.
   Wallach said they would try to get another assistant Commerce
secretary besides Campbell to approve the financing and Moreno said
he was told to call Bragg.
   Moreno said he was told that no assistant secretary could sign
the papers legally but there was a vacancy in the department and
perhaps a new assistant secretary could sign. Two or three days
later the problem was resolved, he said.
   Nofziger was convicted last month of illegal lobbying for
Wedtech and other companies. The conviction is under appeal.
   Last December, a special prosecutor said there was insufficient
evidence to charge Meese in the Wedtech case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
