<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PlaneCrash-School     03-18 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plane Crash-School,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Leave Schoolyard Just Before Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAKERSFIELD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small airplane crashed into a
schoolyard moments after pupils were shepherded to their classrooms
at the end of noon recess. The children escaped injury, but the
pilot was critically hurt.
   ``It was the classic case of fate intervening,'' said Kern
County Fire Capt. Tom Pulcher. ``Where his impact point was, eight
minutes prior to that there was a schoolyard full of children.''
   One class barely made it off the playground at North Beardsley
School in time Thursday, fire officials said. The teacher had just
lined her class up and was herding them inside when she heard the
plane coming in.
   ``A small group were still outside,'' said Assistant City Fire
Chief Henry Pacheco. ``She told the kids to run, and they all ran
out of the way.''
   Observers said the fuselage of the single-engine Dornier came to
rest against a breezeway at the grade school one mile south of
Meadows Field, the main airport in this city 100 miles north of Los
Angeles.
   The pilot, Kenneth Dale Howard, 42, of Anchorage, Alaska, was
taken to Kern Medical Center where he was listed in critical
condition in the intensive care unit.
   Howard was making his final approach and preparing to land at
Meadows when his engine lost power, said Wilbur Friend, air traffic
manager for the Federal Aviation administration tower at the
airport.
   A National Transportation Safety Board investigator requested a
blood-alcohol test on Howard after some containers of alcohol were
found at the crash site, Pulcher said. He added there was no
immediate evidence that Howard had been drinking.
</TEXT>
