<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seized Clothes To Be Distributed To Needy People Abroad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says $20 million worth of
clothing seized by the Customs Bureau will be given to homeless
people and orphans in Mozambique, Malawi and Zimbabwe.
   The clothing had been exported by China and was seized by
inspectors after Chinese officials notified the Customs Bureau that
counterfeit visas were being used to send textiles into the United
States.
   The Customs Bureau said Thursday the first increment of the
clothing _ cotton jeans, shirts, dresses, infants' shirts, denim
jackets and pants and suspenders sets _ would be distributed by the
World Vision Relief Organization and the Adventists Development and
Relief Agency International.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mississippi Federal Judge ``Upset'' With Impeachment Resolution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted federal Judge Walter L. Nixon Jr. of
Mississippi would say only that he was ``very upset'' after the
chairman of the House Judiciary Committee introduced a resolution
of impeachment against him.
   The action Thursday by Judiciary Chairman Peter W. Rodino Jr.,
D-N.J., came just two days after he received a recommendation from
the Judicial Conference, the governing body for federal judges.
   The conference certified to the House that Nixon had engaged in
conduct which might constitute grounds for impeachment. Judges are
appointed for life, and can only be removed by Congress in an
impeachment proceeding.
   Nixon was convicted in February 1986 of two counts of perjury
before a federal grand jury.
   Nixon, reached by phone at his home in Ocean Springs, Miss.,
said: ``My family and I are very upset at this time. Beyond that, I
have no further comment. Any other comments I may have must come
through my attorney.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Activist Urges Rule Against Advertising In Children's TV Shows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An advocate for quality children's television
programs is urging Congress to reinstate limits on advertising
during children's shows, but the National Association of
Broadcasters says such rules aren't needed.
   Peggy Charren, president of the Cambridge, Mass.-based Action
for Children's Television, told a House subcommittee Thursday that
the TV industry cannot be expected to protect the interests of
children.
   Since the Federal Communications Commission abandoned its
advertising limits, dozens of cartoons starring toymakers' products
have appeared, she said.
   The National Association of Broadcasters, however, said
regulation is unnecessary because commercial broadcasters ``have
not and will not desert children.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Countries Warned To Protect Dolphins During Fishing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commerce Department says foreign countries
that export tuna to the United States must reduce the numbers of
dolphin deaths that occur during fishing or lose the right to
export tuna to America.
   The department's National Marine Fisheries Service on Thursday
ordered foreign nations that export tuna to reduce the number of
dolphins killed in fishing.
   The order covers foreign fleets that catch yellowfin tuna in
purse seine nets, and requires them to establish dolphin protection
rules similar to those that already cover U.S. fishermen.
   The regulation will take effect in mid-April, and requires that
the rate of dolphins killed by the foreign fleets be reduced to the
U.S. fishing fleet level by 1991, the Fisheries Service said.
</TEXT>
