<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     03-18 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0654</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HYDE PARK, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angela Patricia Schembeck's birth
made it a hat trick for the Schembeck family. She became the
third-generation St. Patrick's Day baby of the clan that traces its
roots to Ireland.
   Thursday was her father's 23rd birthday and his father's 47th
birthday.
   ``It's a miracle. It's absolutely incredible,'' said the baby's
father, Kevin Schembeck. ``This is the best birthday present we
could have ever received.''
   Angela arrived three days late at Long Island Jewish Medical
Center.
   The Schembecks, all of College Park, were celebrating in the
nursery with a birthday cake baked by the baby's grandmother.
   ``My mom baked the cake yesterday so it only has my dad's name
and mine on it,'' said Schembeck. ``We'll have to add Angela's name
to it from now on.
   ``What makes this so overwhelming is that it was all natural;
nothing was used to stimulate the labor,'' he said.
   The baby's mother, Doreen, 22, said that when the birth went
past the due date she had a feeling that the baby would be born on
the 17th.
   Schembeck said the mutual birthday has been good for him and his
father, Paul.
   ``It's always been the best day of the year for us,'' said
Schembeck. ``We've always had lots of laughs, lots of parties and
lots of good times.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BALFOUR, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 60 years in office, Gordon Olson
would gladly give up his post as Cottonwood Lake Township
treasurer-clerk, but instead he has won re-election to yet another
term.
   Not that the job entails all that much responsibility _ the
township only has nine households.
   ``We're about running out of people for these township jobs,''
said Olson, 85. ``We have a few younger people here but they are
young and single; we don't know how long they will be around.
   ``It's just a job, but somebody has do do it.''
   Township Board Chairman Leon Driessen of Butte has been in
office for 44 or 45 years, Olson said.
   ``Mike Nechiporenko, a board supervisor, has quite a few years
in, too,'' Olson said.
   When Olson was first elected township clerk in 1928, his father,
Magnus, was treasurer and Driessen's father, Henry, was acting
chairman. The clerk and treasurer jobs were combined later.
   Twenty-six families farmed in Cottonwood Lake Township then.
Today there are nine families in the township, several of whom no
longer farm.
   People don't turn out for township elections. Usually, the only
voters are the officers themselves, though they say they follow the
correct election procedures anyway.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT YUKON, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miss America may have been a hit in
Atlantic City. But unless she's a native of the North, she wouldn't
stand a chance in the Fort Yukon Spring Carnival Queen contest.
   Entrants in the annual competition, which beings March 25, must
demonstrate skills that could come in handy in this northeast
Alaska town _ but might not go over too well on national TV.
   First, the tea-making contest. Each of the young women must
build a fire on the snow, melt enough snow to make one cup, boil
the water and brew the tea.
   Then there's the snowshoe race. There's not much call for
three-inch heels in this secluded Yukon River community of less
than 700 people.
   Finally, queen candidates must show their prowess at skinning a
snowshoe hare, known in some parts of Alaska as a ``lowbush
moose.'' Not surprisingly, the event is not a favorite of most
entrants.
   But in other respects, the contest is similar to the Miss
America pageant. All contestants must display some special talent,
answer impromptu questions and appear in an evening gown.
   The winner will preside over the carnival, which runs through
April 2.
</TEXT>
