<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Presser     03-18 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presser,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Department Says Jury Should Determine Presser's Claims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government lawyers say that deception by a
former FBI agent led to claims by Teamsters President Jackie
Presser that the FBI authorized him to start a union
payroll-padding scheme.
   The Justice Department lawyers said Thursday they believe a
trial jury should determine whether the FBI gave Presser and two
other union officials authorization to allegedly embezzle money
from his own union local's treasury, as Presser's lawyers contend.
   The government ``has taken the position that FBI agents never
authorized any embezzlement,'' the Justice Department's Organized
Crime Strike Force said in documents filed Thursday in U.S.
District Court. It also said the so-called authorization defense
raises ``factual issues which only a trial jury may resolve.''
   Presser, 60, is the leader of the 1.6 million-member union and
also is secretary-treasurer of Teamsters Local 507 in Cleveland. He
was indicted on May 16, 1986, on two charges of labor racketeering,
one count of embezzlement, and two counts of filing false reports
with the Labor Department.
   Harold Friedman, Teamsters vice president and Local 507
president, and Anthony Hughes, the local's recording secretary, are
scheduled to stand trial with Presser on July 12.
   The indictment alleged that Presser, in his capacity as a Local
507 officer, masterminded a $700,000 scheme to pay four people who
received union money without doing any work for the union.
   Presser's lawyers say the FBI told Presser, who was an FBI
informant, to pay certain people who had connections to organized
crime so the agency could obtain information from them through
Presser.
   In documents filed with the court March 7, Presser's lawyers
said the government has supplied statements written in 1985 by
former Cleveland-based FBI agents Patrick J. Foran and Martin P.
McCann Jr. that say the agency authorized Presser to make the
payments.
   But prosecutors William S. Lynch, Stephen H. Jigger and Bernard
A. Smith referred to a finding last week by a federal appeals court
in Washington that the authorization defense is a ``tangled web of
deception'' and is ``the product of a calculated lie.''
   The appeals court's finding came in the federal prosecution of
Robert S. Friedrick, a former Cleveland-based FBI agent who was
fired after an indictment alleged he concocted a scheme to avert
the indictment of Presser.
   Most of the evidence against Friedrick was ruled invalid when a
judge found that Justice Department lawyers misled him by making
him believe he was immune from prosecution.
</TEXT>
