<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Midwest, South Dusted With Light Snow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm dusted the Midwest and parts of the South today with
snow after snapping power lines and closing schools in Arkansas.
   ``There were people who planned to lay out in bikinis, and
they're packing up their snow suits,'' said Donna Dickey, a
University of Arkansas student whose spring break began today.
   The storm knocked out power to about 3,000 homes and businesses
Thursday, Arkansas Power & Light Co. spokesman Charles Kelly said.
   Harrison, Ark., reported 22 inches of snow on the ground, while
most northern parts of the state had 4 to 8 inches.
   Forecasters posted winter storm warnings for nothern Arkansas
and western Kentucky. Snow advisories also were posted for southern
Illinois, western Tennessee, southern Indiana, Ohio, northern West
Virginia and southwest Pennsylvania.
   Early today, snow fell across lower Michigan, southwest Ohio,
Indiana, Illinois, southern and eastern Missouri and northwest
Kentucky. Rain and snow fell across southeast Missouri and
southwest Kentucky. Rain fell in western Tennessee, Arkansas,
Mississippi, Louisiana and eastern Texas.
   Snowfall during the six hours ending at 1 a.m. EST included an
inch at Columbia, St. Louis and Springfield, Mo. During the same
period, Galveston, Texas, had nearly 2 inches, Lake Charles, La.,
had slightly more than an inch and Palacios, Texas, had about
three-quarters of an inch.
   The temperature in Midland, Texas, dropped to 23 degrees, tying
the record low for the date set in 1934.
   In Florida, a cold snap that sent temperatures to record lows
showed signs of easing today. The cold did little damage to crops,
officials said.
   Today's forecast called for snow from southeast Missouri and
eastern Arkansas across much of Tennessee and the Ohio Valley into
the central Appalachians and New York state; snow scattered over
Michigan; rain and thunderstorms from the central Gulf Coast states
across east Tennessee, Georgia and northern and central Florida;
rain spreading east across the Carolinas; and scattered rain along
the middle Atlantic Coast.
   Highs were expected to be in the 40s or 50s in much of the
nation; the 30s from North Dakota across the upper Mississippi
Valley, the Ohio Valley and the Great Lakes into northern New
England; the 60s and 70s over the West Coast and western portions
of the Plateau, Florida and southern Georgia; the 60s along the
central Gulf Coast and along the coast of the Carolinas; and the
80s over much of the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 1
degree below zero at Laramie, Wyo., to 70 at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 46 cloudy; Boston 35 fair; Buffalo 27 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 38 foggy; Cincinnati 32 snow; Cleveland 33 cloudy;
Detroit 34 cloudy; Miami 66 fair; New York 35 fair; Philadelphia 33
partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 29 cloudy; Portland, Maine 26 fair;
Washington 34 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 25 fair; Chicago 31 snow; Dallas-Fort Worth
37 windy; Denver 17 fair; Des Moines 23 fair; Indianapolis 32 snow;
Kansas City 24 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 27 fair; Nashville 40
cloudy; New Orleans 55 rain; St. Louis 32 snow.
   _West: Albuquerque 26 fair; Anchorage 31 cloudy; Las Vegas 46
fair; Los Angeles 57 fair; Phoenix 58 fair; Salt Lake City 29 fair;
San Diego 55 fair; San Francisco 48 fair; Seattle 46 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 27 fair; Toronto 27 foggy.
</TEXT>
