<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PoliticalBed     03-18 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Bed,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alderman Can Remain On Council If He Annexes Rest Of His Yard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TROY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alderman Joe Lanahan may no longer have to
worry about which side of the bed he sleeps on.
   Lanahan's right to retain his City Council seat has sparked
heated debate in this St. Louis suburb of 3,800 people since just
after Christmas, when he told the council he had his land surveyed
and found that about half his house was in the city and half in
Madison County.
   Lanahan said he sleeps in the city, however, because the line
falls across one corner at the foot of his bed. He also pays city
taxes.
   The Troy City Council on Thursday unanimously approved an
ordinance requiring city officials to live entirely within city
limits. But all members agreed that if Lanahan annexed the rest of
his property to the city, he could remain an alderman.
   Lanahan said he was pleased with the decision and will seek to
have the section annexed. A crowd of about 50 supporters applauded
when the agreement was finally reached.
   ``This has been a real hassle for us,'' he said. ``I'm glad to
see the support of the people. You really don't know how many
friends you have till something like this happens.''
   Three petitions supporting Lanahan containing 380 signatures
were presented to the council before the vote.
</TEXT>
