<1ST_LINE>r a PM-St.Patrick'sRdp     03-18 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-St. Patrick's Rdp,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northern Irish Violence Lends Somber Tone to Parades</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Terrorist violence in Northern Ireland briefly cast a pall over
St. Patrick's Day celebrations in New York, Boston and other
cities, but for most of the more than 1.5 million parade-goers the
usual high spirits flowed freely.
   New York's traditional parade up Fifth Avenue began in midtown
Thursday with somber words from political and religious leaders,
but soon the bands, sunshine and some surreptitious sipping
produced the usual festive atmosphere among the more than 1 million
marchers and watchers.
   More than 200,000 people crowded the sidewalk in downtown
Chicago to watch the 40,000 marchers, 50 floats and 45 bands that
made up the annual parade. Portions of the Chicago River were dyed
green for the day of revelry.
   In Kansas City, Mo., 70,000 Irish and would-be Irish
parade-goers braved a wet snowfall, while 321,000 people thronged
the streets of Savannah, Ga., in the 164th edition of that city's
St. Patrick's Day procession, the second-largest behind New York's.
   New York's Cardinal John J. O'Conner, in his homily at a Mass
preceding the parade, reflected on a terrorist's
grenade-and-gunfire attack on an Irish Republican Army funeral in
Belfast, Northern Ireland, that left three dead and 68 wounded the
day before.
   ``I hope everyone marching will remember those killed, Catholic
or Protestant,'' said O'Connor, who reviewed the parade from the
steps of St. Patrick's Cathedral. ``The violence is insane.''
   O'Connor said New York's parade was not canceled because
``that's not the Irish way.''
   In Boston, where the parade is scheduled for Sunday, Mayor
Raymond L. Flynn said the root of the violence in Northern Ireland
was ``the utter despair that British rule has perpetrated.''
   The crowds, in various shades of green and varying stages of
sobriety, were generally well-behaved and few arrests were
reported. In New York, 15 summonses were issued for drinking in
public, and only one person was arrested for disorderly conduct.
   In Washington, President Reagan proved his Irish wasn't up over
past disputes with Congress when he toasted ``Seamus Wright'' _
otherwise known as House Speaker Jim Wright _ during a Capitol Hill
luncheon.
   Standing Thursday at a table covered with a green cloth and
decorated with green carnations, the president wished Wright ``warm
words on a cold evening and a full moon on a dark night.''
   Wright, who wore a green jacket and green tie, declared that
``we've buried all differences that might exist between political
parties and branches of government on this day of St. Patrick.'' He
toasted Reagan, 77, for his youthfulness.
   Both men have roots in 19th century Ireland. The Irish for James
is Seamus.
</TEXT>
