<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Koop-AIDS 1stLd-Writethru a0541 03-18 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koop-AIDS, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0541,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Young At Risk For AIDS Because They Often Ignore Warnings, Koop
Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts lead; SUBS last 3 grafs with 2 grafs to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The AIDS virus could spread among American
high school and college students because the young tend not to
believe health warnings are meant for them, according to Surgeon
General C. Everett Koop.
   ``My greatest concern is with the group aged 15 to 24,'' Koop
told a convention of hospital administrators Thursday.
   Officials may have a better idea of the extent of the AIDS virus
among college students by the end of the year as more colleges go
along with a U.S. Centers for Disease Control request to conduct
blind blood testing, Koop said.
   Under such procedures, already used by hospitals in about 40
cities, blood drawn for other purposes is tested for AIDS without
the sample being identified by patient.
   He noted that sexually transmitted diseases in general are
rising at the steepest rate in 16 years ``in spite of the
tremendous educational campaign in 1987, where for the first time
in history we were discussing in the print media and on television
very blunt statements about AIDS and sexually transmitted disease.''
   ``If there is HIV (the AIDS virus) out there, and we know there
is, then there can't help but be some infection going on that we're
not going to see until we get down the road about five years,'' he
told the Federation of American Health Systems.
   It can take five years or more for AIDS to develop after a
person contracts the virus.
   ``So with teen-agers, who think that they're immortal, who
always think the health message is meant for the person next to
them, who have sort of a sense that risk-taking is sort of fun, we
have our most difficult target group, especially with regard to
heterosexual transmission.''
   Earlier, the federal official who oversees the Medicare and
Medicaid health programs for the elderly and poor told the hospital
executives they have been given ``an almost impossible task:
controlling physician decision-making.''
   ``There is deep-seated ambivalence in America about intruding on
physician decision-making,'' said Dr. William L. Roper, head of the
Health Care Financing Administration. ``But we cannot have both
physician autonomy and cost constraint.''
</TEXT>
