<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DalkonShield     03-18 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dalkon Shield,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Professor Pleads Innocent To Charges Of Lying About IUD Safety</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A professor pleaded innocent to charges he
lied about the Dalkon Shield's safety when he testified for A.H.
Robins Co. in its attempt to disprove a woman's claim that the
contraceptive device made her sterile.
   Dr. Louis G. Keith remained free on a $10,000 appearance bond
after entering his plea here Thursday. He said he voluntarily took
a leave of absence from Northwestern University in Chicago, where
he teaches obstetrics and gynecology, until the case is resolved.
   Keith testified as an expert witness for A.H. Robins, the
Richmond, Va.-based manufacturer of the device, during trial of the
lawsuit brought against the company by Linda Harre of Tampa five
years ago.
   The 53-year-old professor told the jury he had conducted
experiments that verified the safety of the intrauterine device.
   But a federal indictment announced March 3 contends that Keith
``did not design, direct, conduct or do the scientific experiments
about which he testified.''
   Keith is charged with obstruction of justice and lying eight
times on the witness stand. If convicted on all counts, he faces 45
years in prison and $85,000 in fines.
   The case is being prosecuted by attorneys from the U.S. Justice
Department in Washington.
   Mrs. Harre, 39, alleged the shield made her sterile, but she
lost her $12.5 million lawsuit. She won a new trial in March 1985
when the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta issued an opinion
that attacked the veracity of Keith's testimony.
   Five months later, Robins filed for protection from its
creditors in federal bankruptcy court in Richmond due to the more
than 14,300 lawsuits filed against the company by women who claim
to have suffered pelvic infections, sterility or spontaneous
abortions from using the Dalkon Shield.
   The bankruptcy filing barred future action on the pending
lawsuits.
   Ann C. Tighe, of the Chicago law firm representing Keith, said:
``My client has proclaimed his innocence. We will expect him to be
vindicated.''
   After the brief hearing Thursday, U.S. Magistrate Thomas Wolfson
set the trial for May before Judge William Castagna.
</TEXT>
