<HEAD>Star of Silent Films and Flash Gordon Series Dead at 87</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `As a romantic...' to CORRECT spelling Dolores
del Rio.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roland Drew, a movie actor who quit
Hollywood in the 1940s for a second career in dressmaking, died at
home of natural causes, his son said. He was 87.
   Drew's roles included that of Prince Baron of Vulcan in the
Flash Gordon serials of the late 1930s which featured Buster Crabbe
as the adventurous Earthman.
   Drew, who died Thursday, received a letter requesting his
autograph as recently as three months ago, said his son, Damon Drew.
   Some of Roland Drew's films, such as ``Hitler, Beast of
Berlin,'' have been shown on local television in recent years.
   The appeal of stardom faded for Drew during the 1940s, and he
quit acting to enter the garment industry as a representative and
maker, his son said. He manufactured women's dresses under the
label Damon Originals.
   As a romantic leading man, Drew co-starred with Dolores del Rio
in the silent film ``Ramona.'' The two later were engaged to be
married, but the romance fizzled, Damon Drew said.
   Roland Drew married Dorothy Dearing, a former Busby Berkeley
girl, in 1946. She died in 1965.
   In addition to his son, Drew is survived by two grandsons.
</TEXT>
