<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Abalone     03-18 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abalone,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Marine Mollusk Bid Denied</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banana slug backers defeated abalone
admirers in an California Assembly battle to name the official
state mollusk.
   Assemblyman Trice Harvey tried in vain Thursday to add the
abalone to a bill that would give the mollusk title to the banana
slug. His amendment failed 36-37.
   ``I feel there should be a sharing of this,'' Harvey said. ``The
banana slug could be the inland mollusk. The abalone can be the
marine mollusk.''
   He said the abalone was deserving because it is ``working hard
to try to save the endangered sea otter.''
   ``The banana slug is yucky. Abalone is delicious,'' he added.
   Assemblyman Byron Sher, author of the banana slug bill, opposed
the amendment, but said, ``I respect Mr. Harvey and enjoy abalone,
or is it the other way around?''
   He said the amendment would be a disservice to the Dynamite
Bluebird troop of Redwood City, which did the research and
convinced him to carry the slug bill.
   Also, he said, ``the abalone is not an accessible mollusk.'' Not
only does it live underwater, but it costs $38 a pound.
</TEXT>
