<HEAD>Cobb Arts Commission Restores Nude Models In Arts Class</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   County officials have removed an obstacle
that kept art students from drawing nude models: bathing suits.
   The Cobb County Arts Commission voted unanimously Thursday to
overturn a ban on nude models imposed several weeks ago by
Community Services Department chief Bob Ash. Ash had been concerned
about how the community would perceive nude modeling, even though
it was limited to advanced, adults-only classes.
   Judge Mary Staley, chairwoman of the Arts Commission, said
members realized the value of the nude as art. ``It's a classical
approach to developing your skills as an artist. As long as
precautions are taken to avoid exposing people who do not wish to
be exposed.''
   The commission said nudes could only be used in advanced, adult
arts classes and that warning signs must be posted on classroom
doors. In addition, the panel also voted to require students
between ages 15 and 18 to obtain written parental consent before
they can attend classes with nude models.
   Ash has said he would abide by the arts commission's decision.
