<DOCNO> AP880318-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 0837EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Dioxin-AgentOrange     03-18 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dioxin-Agent Orange,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italian Study Cites Lack of Relationship Between Dioxin and Birth
Defects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cloud of dioxin spread over an area of Italy by
an industrial accident in 1976 apparently caused no significant
increase in birth defects, according to a six-year study.
   The study reported in today's edition of the Journal of the
American Medical Association focused on babies born in and around
Seveso, Italy, from 1977 through 1982. Another study in today's
Journal reported that a blood test developed in Sweden might
simplify the job of determining how many Vietnam veterans have been
exposed to the defoliant Agent Orange.
   The blood test is less expensive and less invasive than the
standard test of fat tissue, which requires surgery, said Wayne P.
Wilson, executive director of the New Jersey State Commission on
Agent Orange.
   A team led by Dr. Peter C. Kahn of Rutgers University compared
both tests in a study involving 27 men and found little difference
in the results.
   Although the tests now can be performed only in Sweden and at
the U.S. Centers for Disease Control, Wilson on Thursday, urged
their increased use.
   Dioxin, a byproduct of pesticide manufacture, causes cancer in
laboratory animals, but has not been directly linked to cancers in
humans.
   The July 1976 accident at a chemical factory exposed more than
37,200 residents of Seveso and three neighboring towns in northern
Italy to dioxin _ the largest population ever contaminated by the
chemical.
   The six physicians who performed the six-year study wrote that
it confirms previous analyses which concluded that if there is any
increased risk related to dioxin, ``the overall risk is unlikely to
be large or might be limited to very rare and specific birth
defects.''
   The Italian doctors considered as defects only congenital
malformations that were present and obvious at birth. Congenital
problems that manifest themselves later, such as mental
retardation, were not considered.
   The Seveso Congenital Malformations Registry, established
shortly after the accident, found that in 15,291 births, 742
infants were born with malformations, a rate of 48.5 per 1,000.
   The prevalence of malformations over the same period in a
nearby, uncontaminated area used as a control was 48.8 per 1,000
births, the study found.
   The quantity of dioxin released into the environment ``seemed to
be enormous'' but was never precisely determined, according to the
study.
   ``Still more important,'' the study concluded, ``is the fact
that no infant with a major malformation was identified in the most
highly contaminated zone.''
   Levels of dioxin concentration found on the ground in the area
surrounding the factory were nearly 1,000 times higher than the
levels termed safe by state and federal officials after a cleanup
at Times Beach, Mo.
   Times Beach is now deserted, and hundreds of families have filed
lawsuits against companies and individuals over exposure to dioxin
contained in waste oil sprayed on their streets as a dust-control
measure in the 1970s.
   Agent Orange, used in Vietnam to eliminate ground cover for Viet
Cong and North Vietnamese troops, contained the most toxic form of
dioxin, 2,3,7,8-TCDD.
   Questions about the effects of Agent Orange exposure have
lingered since the war. Some veterans have sought government
compensation, contending their exposure resulted in cancers,
rashes, headaches, infertility and other side effects, as well as
birth defects in their children.
   The Veterans Administration has rejected the claims, saying
numerous studies have found no link between exposure and reported
symptoms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880318-0077 </DOCNO>
