<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FBI-Socialists     03-18 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FBI-Socialists,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Department Drops Appeal in Socialist Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Socialist Workers Party, the subject of 16
years of illegal FBI surveillance, claimed victory after the
Justice Department decided to withdraw an appeal and pay a damage
award to the party.
   U.S. District Judge Thomas Griesa had awarded the party $264,000
in damages Aug. 26, 1986, ruling that an FBI campaign of
wiretapping, bugging, burglaries, anonymous letters and harassment
was illegal and ``patently unconstitutional.''
   ``The rulings by Judge Griesa are now final,'' Jack Barnes,
national secretary of the party, said Thursday. ``This places a
valuable weapon securely in the hands of every fighter for
democratic rights and political liberties.''
   Amy Brown, spokeswoman for the Justice Department's civil
division in Washington, confirmed that the department notified the
U.S. District Court in New York on Wednesday that it was
withdrawing its appeal.
   She referred a request for comment to Assistant U.S. Attorney
Peter Salerno in Manhattan, who had none.
   ``The Socialist Workers Party, the First Amendment and the rule
of law have won,'' said attorney Leonard B. Boudin of the Political
Rights Defense Fund, which represented the party.
   The case, filed in 1973, challenged an extensive
counterintelligence operation by the federal government to
infiltrate and neutralize organizations suspected of ``subversive
activities.''
   According to the court, the FBI planted 1,300 informers in the
party and its offshoot, the Young Socialist Alliance, between 1960
and 1976, paying them a total of $1.7 million. The FBI committed
193 burglaries and photographed or removed 9,864 party documents,
the judge said.
   The Socialist Workers Party, a Trotskyite offshoot of the
Communist League, claims about 2,000 members nationwide.
</TEXT>
