<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Killings     03-18 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Killings,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four More Wounded in Street Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen wounded a senior police
officer, his chauffeur and two other soldiers in separate attacks
today. The military said arrested a provincial deputy commander of
the communist New People's Army.
   On Thursday, communist rebels killed three people in Manila's
so-called ``war of the streets.''
   Police said gunmen in a speeding car opened fire today on a
vehicle carrying Maj. Pepito Campos and his driver in suburban
Quezon City. Police said the two were wounded, but out of danger at
a local hospital.
   Campos is chief of the special investigations division for the
capital's Northern Police District. Police said a Philippine
Constabulary captain was arrested later as a suspect.
   In a separate incident, gunmen believed to be communist rebels
fired on a car carrying three Philippine Constabulary soldiers in
Manila's Taguig suburb. Two of the soldiers were wounded, police
said.
   On Thursday, two suspected rebels shot and killed Jaime
Javellana, a neighborhood ward leader, as he was walking along a
street in Manila's Santa Mesa district.
   An hour later, four men armed with .45-caliber pistols opened
fire on a jeep near the University of Santo Tomas. Two soldiers,
Sgt. Herman Pascua and Constable Perfecto Terte, were mortally
wounded. A third soldier suffered wounds in the chest and arms but
survived.
   In San Fernando, 40 miles north of here, the Philippine
Constabulary announced the arerest of Elizardo Lapuz, 42, which it
identified as the deputy commander of the New People's Army in
Pampanga province.
   A military statement said Lapuz was arrested late Thursday as he
left his home in the San Fernando area. He offered no resistance.
Pampanga province, which borders Manila to the north, has been a
longtime rebel stronghold.
   In Manila, police said a leaflet left near the scene of the
first shooting said Javellana had been slain by the rebel Alex
Boncayao Brigade because of ``crimes against the people.''
   The brigade is the Manila wing of the communist New People's
Army, which has been waging a 19-year insurgency to establish a
Marxist state. It has claimed responsibility for killing scores of
police, soldiers and government officials in the capital since
President Corazon Aquino took office in 1986.
</TEXT>
