<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NBC-Schedule     03-18 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NBC-Schedule,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tartikoff Announces NBC's Fall Plans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Laugh-In'' creator George Schlatter
will produce a one-hour comedy series for NBC this summer called
``Funny People,'' NBC Entertainment President Brandon Tartikoff
told advertising executives.
   Schlatter will bring together a cast of comedians for the weekly
show that will premiere Wednesday, July 27. Schlatter previously
produced the landmark comedy hit ``Rowan and Martin's Laugh In''
and ``Real People'' for NBC.
   Tartikoff told 250 advertising executives Thursday at the NBC
studios that the network also would have original episodes of
``Sonny Spoon'' this summer.
   If the Writers Guild of America strike is settled in time, NBC
also plans a new situation comedy during the rerun season, he said.
   Tartikoff, describing his No.1-rated network's coming fall
season during his annual spring preview, said NBC had six series
commitments _ four comedies and two dramas _ with at least 10 other
comedy and 14 drama pilots in the wings.
   The comedy commitments include ``Empty Nest,'' a show about a
Miami doctor with two grown daughters starring Richard Mulligan,
Kristy McNichol, Dinah Manhoff and David Leisure. Mulligan lives
next door to the four women of the ``Golden Girls'' and will have
an occasional romance with Rue McClanahan.
   Other comedy shows include:
   _``Dear John,'' starring Judd Hirsch as a man whose wife walks
out on him and must start life over.
   _``Baby Boom,'' based on the movie starring Diane Keaton. The
show about a career woman who suddenly finds herself with a baby
has not been cast.
   _``Channel 99,'' in which Marilu Henner stars as a woman who
takes over a failing UHF station in New York state.
   ``|attingers'' is a fa|l drama in which Stephen Collins stars as
a restaurateur and man about town in`a Manhattan-based drama that
also stars Blythe Danner and Jerry Stiller.
   ``The Disney Hour,'' which is moving from ABC, will feature a
rotating schedule of series specials, including the return of Fess
Parker as ``Davy Crockett,'' Harry Anderson as the ``Absent-Minded
Professor,'' plus other movies and specials and a third regular
series to be created later.
   Robert Loggia and Lance Guest will star as two FBI agents in the
mini-series ``Favorite Son,'' which was described by Tartikoff as a
back-door pilot, meaning it could be developed into a series
featuring the two G-men.
   Aaron Spelling, whose long-term exclusive commitment to ABC
expired last year, is developing a new show for NBC called
``Nightingales,'' about six young women who are in a student
nursing program.
   Turning to movies planned next year, Tartikoff said Raymond Burr
was returning for three more ``Perry Mason'' films, but he thought
one of them probably would be ``Perry Mason's last case.''
   Tartikoff said NBC was considering at least 20 shows to
counterprogram ABC's 30-hour miniseries, ``War and Remembrance.''
   Among the pilots being considered are ``Flip Side,'' about a
rock legend who comes home to face his three alienated children.
Ex-Beatle Ringo Starr had been cast for the lead role.
   Tartikoff jokingly told the audience Starr had been replaced by
Pete Best _ the original drummer for the Beatles, who was replaced
by Starr.
   Another pilot is being prepared for singer Morris Day, who
starred in ``Purple Rain'' and ``Moving'' and will play a
flamboyant record producer in a new comedy in development.
   Kate Capshaw of ``Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom'' stars
in the comedy pilot ``When In Rome,'' about a hotshot New York
newspaper woman who takes over a local newspaper in Rome, N.D.
   Tartikoff said NBC would begin in September with the Summer
Olympics from Seoul, South Korea, then open its regular season with
a special featuring all of its stars at Disneyland, to be followed
by a new ``Davy Crockett'' epsiode.
   NBC also has this year's baseball World Series and football
Super Bowl.
</TEXT>
