<2ND_LINE>PM-Prince Charles,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Charles Flies To Switzerland To Visit Friend Hurt In Ski Tragedy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Charles returned to
Switzerland today to visit a friend who broke both legs in an
avalanche that killed another of the prince's skiing companions and
nearly engulfed him.
   The Queen's Flight plane, flown by Charles, arrived at Zurich
airport at 12:40 p.m., airport officials said.
   Buckingham Palace said the heir to Britain's throne was paying a
private visit to Patricia Palmer-Tomkinson at the hospital in Davos
where she is recovering. She underwent further surgery Thursday.
   Mrs. Palmer-Tomkinson and her husband were in the royal party on
the slopes of the Alpine resort of Klosters when the avalanche
struck March 10. The palace said Charles traveled without any other
members of the royal family.
   Meanwhile, the palace refused to comment on a report in the Sun,
a London tabloid, saying a Swiss investigator told it the royal
skiing party was responsible for the snowslide.
   The Sun claimed the finding emerged from what it said was a
scientific investigation by the local chief of ski police,
Christian Kasper.
   Kasper, however, told a reporter: ``I would not say anything
before the investigation was finished.''
   A spokesman for the prosecutor's office, Albert Largiader, said:
``Kasper is a private person. He has nothing at all to do with the
investigation.''
   Charles and five companions were skiing off Kloster's regular
ski runs when the avalanche occurred.
   British Army officer Maj. Hugh Lindsay, 34, was killed, and Mrs.
Palmer-Tomkinson was buried with him in the snow. Charles and the
rest of the party managed to ski clear and were uninjured.
</TEXT>
