<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 0908EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AmocoSuspenders     03-18 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amoco Suspenders,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marble Deteriorating on Amoco Headquarters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They're fitting ``Big Stan'' with suspenders to
keep his outerwear on when the hard wind blows. After all, you
can't have someone 1,136 feet tall shedding 275-pound marble slabs.
   ``Big Stan'' is the nickname of the downtown Amoco Corp.
headquarters, formerly the Standard Oil Building. It's the world's
fourth-tallest building, and is in danger of losing some of its
sheathing, officials say.
   As a result, Amoco will install steel ``suspenders'' to keep the
white marble in place, engineering manager Shelby Pierce said
Thursday.
   The sheathing slabs are starting to curl or ``bow'' after 15
years in place, said Pierce. The slabs are 1\-inch thick and
measure 4 feet 2 inches by 3 feet 9 inches. Beginning next week,
workers will begin installing bolted-in stainless steel straps,
one-sixteenth of an inch thick and 2 inches wide, at the southeast
corner of the building at a minimum cost of $1 million.
   ``We're looking at an area where the most severe bows occur,''
he said. ``The southeast corner gets most exposure to sun and
thermal cycles and heavy wind.''
   Pierce said company officials first noticed the problem in 1979.
By last November, the condition of the marble began to worsen, and
officials decided to reinforce the marble.
   While workers spend six weeks reinforcing the southeast corner,
engineers will be checking the rest of the building to see if more
drastic measures need to be taken. If the strapping doesn't work,
Amoco may have to strip the building of its gleaming white facade,
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
