<HEAD>South Korean Opposition Remains Split</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates of South Korea's two main
opposition parties ran into trouble today as they tried to forge a
united front against the government.
   They were seeking a merger after Kim Dae-jung quit as president
of the Party for Peace and Democracy Thursday. Kim Young-sam had
resigned as leader of the larger Reunification Democratic Party in
February.
   Both men ran in December's presidential election, dividing
opposition votes and allowing victory for government candidate Roh
Tae-woo. The two Kims had been under pressure since then to step
down and clear the way for a united opposition.
   But the Reunification Democratic Party insisted today it should
have the right to name the main opposition leader and to pick the
lion's share of candidates for National Assembly elections,
expected on April 26. The smaller party, however, insisted on a
strong voice in picking candidates and leadership.
   Announcing its own candidates today for the upcoming election,
the ruling Democratic Justice Party dropped several hard-line
legislators. Party leaders said they were cut in efforts to end
authoritarian rule and advance democracy.
   Roh, a former general, helped former President Chun Doo-hwan
take power in 1980 with military backing. Roh has vowed to
introduce full democracy.
   Meanwhile, the government today stepped up its rhetoric against
communist North Korea. It warned that another provocation like the
December bombing of a South Korean civilian airliner, for which it
blames North Korea, would be viewed as ``a declaration of war.''
   ``We will consider a similar incident like this a declaration of
war against us and mete out strong punishment,'' Defense Minister
Oh Ja-bok told local reporters.
   Oh's statement was one of the strongest warnings against North
Korea since the bombing of a Korean Air jetliner near Burma on Dec.
29. All 115 people on board the flight were killed.
   Oh said 650,000 troops under his command were fully prepared to
crush any North Korean provocation or attack across the border
</TEXT>
