<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Homeless-Builders     03-18 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Homeless-Builders,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Industry Effort Would Renovate Apartments For Homeless</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition of landlords and developers hopes to
enlist activists for the homeless in a a five-year program to buy
and renovate 5,000 vacant apartments as low-income housing, the
coalition's president said.
   Associated Builders and Owners of New York has created a
not-for-profit corporation called Affordable Alternative Housing
for the Homeless, which would buy buildings, renovate them at an
estimated cost of $85,000 each and turn over management to
organizations for the homeless, Jerome Belson said Thursday.
   In some cases, apartments in occupied buildings would be
designated for the homeless. Buildings could be converted later to
low-income cooperatives.
   Major funding is expected to come from the city and state, the
Daily News reported today. The corporation also has the support of
the Real Estate Board of New York and the Rent Stabilization
Association.
   Deputy Mayor Robert Esnard called the idea ``very interesting,''
and Robert Hayes, founder of the Coalition for the Homeless,
expressed cautious support.
</TEXT>
