<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritersStrike     03-18 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Plans to Defy Writers Strike with ``Smothers Brothers'' Shows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Producers of a new CBS television comedy show
plan to defy a writers' strike and continue making the show even
after they run out of union-written scripts.
   CBS made the announcement about ``The Smothers Brothers Comedy
Hour'' Thursday, just two days after the Writers Guild of America
rejected pleas from TV producers for special permission to continue
work during the strike.
   The 9,000-member union went on strike against the Alliance of
Motion Picture and Television Producers on March 7 over residuals
from foreign distribution, creative control and a management
proposal to restructure residuals for one-hour TV shows sold into
syndication.
   A session with a federal mediator last weekend failed to end the
dispute, and no new talks are scheduled.
   A CBS spokesman, who talked on condition he not be identified,
said six ``Smothers Brothers'' shows were planned and three scripts
were in hand. When asked what would happen if the strike were still
in progress when it came time for the fourth show, the spokesman
said: ``I can only stand by the statement.''
   ``Production will continue,'' he said, but ``the nature of the
show may change.''
   Under terms of the guild contract, not even cue cards can be
drawn up. Previously, the show's producers said production plans
were postponed because of the strike.
   The WGA, hundreds of whose members picketed the CBS-MTM studios
here Thursday, reacted to the announcement with a warning.
   ``If any writing is done by guild members, they'll be subject to
charges,'' said union president George Kirgo. ``If any writing is
done by non-guild members, well, that's scab writing.''
   The strike has had its biggest impact on talk and variety shows
and has forced some shows into premature reruns.
</TEXT>
