<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0551,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Reportedly Attacks Three Ships, Captures Two Iraqi Towns</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with more missiles, planes downed
and Iraqi attack in gulf. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said its forces fired 30 missiles
into Iraqi cities today, shot down five Iraqi jets and captured two
Iraqi towns. Persian Gulf shipping sources said the Iranians
attacked three ships and Iraq struck one.
   Iraq said it shot seven long-range missiles into Tehran. Iran's
official media, monitored in Nicosia, reported at least one child
killed and an undisclosed number of civilians wounded.
   The gulf sources said a Japanese seaman was killed aboard the
Panamanian liquified gas carrier Maria 2. The rest of the 20-man
crew abandoned ship when it was set on fire. Three were wounded,
and all were rescued.
   The Iranians, who used speedboats and a frigate, later attacked
the 284,494-ton Norwegian tanker Berge Lord, starting a small fire,
and the 87,768-ton Singapore-flag tanker Neptune Saburu. No
casualties were reported.
   Iraqi warplanes hit at least one tanker off the Iranian coast in
a pre-dawn attack, setting it on fire.
   The official Iraqi News Agency quoted military communiques as
saying another ship was hit in a separate air raid. But there was
no immediate confirmation. The report was monitored in Nicosia.
   Today's Iraqi missile attacks raised to 30 the number of
long-range Al Hussein projectiles Baghdad says it has lobbed into
the Iranian capital since the ``war of the cities'' exploded again
Sunday after a two-day lull.
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency said Iranian interceptors
shot down three Iraqi Mirage F-1 fighter-bombers over the northern
gulf today in two separate dogfights. IRNA also was monitored in
Nicosia.
   The agency said all three planes, apparently hit by air-to-air
missiles, crashed into the water, killing the pilots. Iraq usually
uses the French-built Mirages for shipping attacks.
   IRNA said two other Iraqi planes, one a Soviet-built Sukhoi
Su-22 ground-attack jet, were downed by anti-aircraft fire on
strafing missions Thursday and today against Iranian forces
thrusting into northeast Iraq.
   Iran has claimed to have downed nine Iraqi jets in the region
since Sunday. Iraq has not admitted losing any aircraft.
   IRNA said Revolutionary Guards pushing into the mountains of
northeast Iraq recaptured the Iranian border town of Nowsud, held
by the Iraqis since the early days of the 7{-year-old war.
   It said they later overran the ``military towns'' of Tawla,
three miles north of Nowsud, and Byara a few miles further north,
killing or wounding 700 Iraqis and capturing 200.
   The Iranians, driving into the region in a two-pronged offensive
codenamed Val-Fajr-10, claim to have killed or wounded 9,200 Iraqis
and captured 4,000 in heavy fighting since Sunday and seized 328
square miles of territory.
   IRNA reported that a broadside of 24 medium-range missiles was
fired late Thursday and early today into the southern industrial
town of Zubair near Basra and the nearby towns of Haretha and
Shubair.
   The Iranian offensive was seen as retaliation for Iraqi missile
and air attacks on Iranian cities since Feb.29.
   Both sides have reported hundreds of civilians killed in the
attacks.
   Iraq said it has lobbed 101 missiles into Tehran, the holy city
of Qom and the central city of Isfahan in that period.
   Iran said it has fired 36 into Baghdad and the northern city of
Mosul, with dozens of short-range missiles into Basra and other
border towns.
   Both sides have ignored an appeal by United Nations
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar for a cease-fire in the
``war of the cities.''
</TEXT>
