<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SpaceShuttleCrews     03-18 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Space Shuttle Crews,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Astronaut Crews Named For Three Space Shuttle Missions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA has selected 15 astronauts, 11
of them veteran space shuttle fliers, for three 1989 shuttle
missions which will deploy a large space telescope, a
communications satellite and a probe to Venus.
   With Thursday's announcement, six crews have been selected for
shuttle missions, which are to resume Aug. 4. The shuttle fleet has
been grounded since the Challenger explosion that killed seven
astronauts in January 1986.
   Shuttle mission STS-29, scheduled for launch Jan. 19, 1989, will
be commanded by Navy Capt. Michael L. Coats. The others are Air
Force Col. John E. Blaha, Marine Cols. Robert C. Springer and James
F. Buchli and James P. Bagian. They will release the third in a
series of Tracking and Data Relay Satellites for communications.
   STS stands for space transportation system.
   Navy Capt. David M. Walker will command STS-30, set for launch
April 27, 1989. With him will be Air Force Col. Ronald J. Grabe,
Air Force Maj. Mark C. Lee, Norman E. Thagard and Mary L. Cleave.
Their mission will start planetary probe Magellan on its way to map
the entire surface of Venus with radar.
   The STS-31 mission will feature deployment of the Hubble Space
Telescope and is set for June 1, 1989. Air Force Col. Loren J.
Shriver will command the flight. The others are Marine Col. Charles
F. Bolden, Kathryn D. Sullivan, Steven A. Hawley and Navy Capt.
Bruce McCandless.
   Blaha, Springer, Bagian and Lee will be making their first
shuttle flights.
</TEXT>
