<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TieTermination     03-18 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tie Termination,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Employee Fired For Refusing To Wear Coat And Tie</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal employee fired for refusing to wear a
coat and tie for an identification photograph says he'll appeal,
arguing that the dress requirement is discriminatory.
   Roger Arnold, whose dismissal from his $36,000-a-year job was
effective today, said the controversy was solely over the
photograph, not his attire on the job. He said he has not worn a
coat and tie at work since the late 1970s and last wore a tie at
his son's wedding in 1983.
   ``Ties just don't serve any purpose in my life,'' said Arnold,
50, of Duxbury, an employee of the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms who checked wineries, distilleries and firearm
manufacturers for federal license compliance.
   Arnold, a 17-year ATF employee, said his objection to the dress
requirement was based on his dislike for business attire, and the
fact that no clothing requirement was placed on female ATF
employees posing for identification photographs.
   ``Personally, it was a matter of principles,'' said Arnold.
``But when I looked at the regulations, it was apparent they were
discriminatory. It placed all the clothing burden on men.''
   Arnold said he will appeal the dismissal to the Merit Systems
Protection Board and the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission.
   Dot Koester, an ATF spokeswoman in Washington, D.C., said Arnold
is the first ATF employee to be fired over a clothing issue.
   Koester said the government requires coats and ties for
identification photographs but does not have a specific dress code
for the ATF.
   ``We just expect our employees to look and dress like the
professionals they are,'' said Koester.
   She said the issue of Arnold's dress was raised only last year
because a change in ATF identifications required new photographs be
taken.
   Arnold was reprimanded in writing and suspended without pay
twice before his dismissal after he was first asked to wear a coat
and tie in January 1987, said Koester.
   ``This is not something that just came up,'' she said. ``Mr.
Arnold has been fighting us for quite a while.''
   ``It's good to stand up for your principles,'' said Arnold.
``But with no job, things are going to be tight.''
</TEXT>
