<2ND_LINE>PM-Campbell Announces,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rep. Campbell Announces Re-Election Plans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PUEBLO, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, D-Colo.,
announced today he would seek a second term in Congress from
Colorado's 3rd District.
   ``You know how hard I worked to get it, and I'll work twice as
hard to keep it,'' Campbell said at a a breakfast meeting of
Democrats.
   Campbell, 54, was elected to Congress two years ago by upsetting
Republican freshman Mike Strang of Carbondale.
   In 1986, he began his campaign by shocking some Democratic
activists when he told the 3rd District nominating assembly to
``put up or shut up'' and donate money to his campaign if he was to
have a fighting chance.
   The necessary money was raised, and Campbell defeated the
better-financed Strang by 6,845 votes out of more than 183,000 cast.
   Campbell is half Northern Cheyenne Indian and sits on the
Council of 44 Chiefs of the Montana tribe. A jeweler who runs a
horse training and raising operation with his wife, Linda, Campbell
has two children, Colin, a freshman at Fort Lewis College, and
Shannan, a high school senior.
   Campbell participated in the 1964 Olympics as a member of the
U.S. judo team, and carried the country's flag in closing
ceremonies.
</TEXT>
