<1ST_LINE>r a PM-IllegalIrish     03-18 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Illegal Irish,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nursing Home Owner Pleads Guilty To Inducing Illegal Aliens To
Enter U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nursing home owner has pleaded guilty to
inducing 11 Irish nationals to quit their jobs and illegally enter
the United States to work for him as nurses' aides and orderlies.
   As part of a plea agreement announced Thursday, Peter H. Starr
will be allowed to withdraw his guilty plea if U.S. District Judge
John J. McNaught rejects a government recommendation that Starr
receive a suspended prison sentence and be placed on probation for
three years.
   The deal also calls for Starr to be fined $40,000 and to perform
1,000 hours of community service. McNaught scheduled sentencing for
May 10.
   Starr, 34, owner of the Queen Anne nursing home, was indicted
March 2 and charged with inducing the workers to come to the United
States. He recruited the workers after being warned it was highly
unlikely that they would be issued working permits, the indictment
said.
   Despite the warning, Starr, who had recruited the workers with
an advertisement in a Dublin newspaper, assured them their work
visas were being processed and that the only problem was a delay
caused by passage of the new federal immigration law.
   Because of that purported delay, Starr convinced the 11 workers
to enter the United States on vacation visas. To obtain those, the
workers had to lie and say they never had requested permission to
work in the United States.
   The indictment stemmed from a Labor Department investigation
that began last year after one of the Irish aliens was involved in
a local police investigation.
   The 11 workers cooperated with the investigation and were given
permission to stay in the United States through August. They can
apply for residency status during that period.
</TEXT>
