<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Taiwan-LiuKilling     03-18 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-Liu Killing,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwan Government Urged to Reinvestigate U.S. Killing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition lawmakers asked the government
today to investigate whether high-ranking officials were involved
in the 1984 assassination of a Chinese-American journalist in the
United States.
   A former gang member in Taiwan, Tung Kuei-sen, testified
Wednesday in San Mateo County Superior Court in California that he
shot Henry Liu on orders of Chiang Hsiao-wu, son of then-President
Chiang Ching-kuo. Chiang Hsiao-wu was head of Taiwan's secret
police at the time.
   Liu, then 52, was gunned down in Daly City south of San
Francisco just after he finished writing a biography critical of
President Chiang, who died in January of heart failure.
   The attorney for a man convicted of the murder by a court in
Taiwan said today he had evidence that his client, Chen Chi-li, was
acting on orders of ranking Nationalist government officials.
Attorney Chen Shui-pien said he would request the High Court to
reopen its murder trial to allow presentation of new evidence.
   Chen Chi-li, reputed head of the United Bamboo gang, and his
lieutenant, Wu Tun, were convicted by the High Court in 1985 of
murdering the journalist. They testified that they received orders
from Taiwan's chief of military intelligence at the time, Vice Adm.
Wong Hsi-ling, who also was imprisoned in the case. The three are
serving life terms in Taiwan.
   The government has denied involvement in the killing and refused
U.S. attempts to have Chen and Wu extradited for trial in the
United States.
   The four opposition lawmakers today told the Legislative Yuan,
Taiwan's highest law-making body, that the government should not
make any attempt to cover up the killing.
   The lawmakers requested that Chiang Hsiao-wu, the government's
deputy trade representative in Singapore, return to testify at the
Legislative Yuan.
   But Legislative Yuan President Nieh Wen-ya said it would be
inappropriate for the body to hold a hearing on a judicial case
being tried in the United States.
</TEXT>
