<1ST_LINE>r w PM-North-Hostage 1stLd-Writethru a0479 03-18 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-North-Hostage, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0479,670</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after 6th, Perot had, to update with Perot
comment.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former White House aide Oliver L. North gave
an employee of Texas billionaire H. Ross Perot a letter granting
him presidential authority to take $100,000 into Canada as part of
a failed plan to free a U.S. hostage, a published report says.
   The money, provided by Perot, wound up being squandered on high
living by a Canadian who was supposed to help win the release of
Peter C. Kilburn, the librarian at the American University in
Beirut who was kidnapped Dec. 3, 1984, The Washington Post reported
today.
   Kilburn was killed by a Libyan terrorist group in April 1986 in
apparent retaliation for the U.S. bombing of Libya.
   North sent Perot employee Jay Coburn to Canada in January 1986
with a letter on National Security Council stationery that said
Coburn ``is acting on official U.S. Government business on behalf
of the President of the United States,'' according to a copy of the
letter obtained by the Post.
   ``In support of this mission he has the authority to transport
and disburse as necessary, U.S. $100,000,'' the letter said. ``In
the event of emergency or clarification, please contact: Oliver L.
North.''
   Perot had provided the money at North's request, and Coburn
needed the North letter in case U.S. Customs Service agents stopped
him at the border, the Post said.
   Perot said Thursday night that he never questioned his employee
concerning details of the cash delivery and didn't learn until much
later the name of the hostage for whom authorities were negotiating.
   He told the Dallas Times Herald the request for the money came
from the NSC, but that he didn't seek to know details.
   ``This is a small event in a very active life,'' he said. ``They
asked me for it. I delivered it to them and I didn't ask for any
details. They've been calling me on things like this since 1969. It
doesn't matter to me who's president. I did it for a simple reason
_ there was an American over there who needed help.''
   Travelers must file a disclosure statement if they take more
than $10,000 out of the country. Failure to file is punishable by
up to $250,000 in fines and five years in prison.
   Coburn got into Canada without difficulty and in Montreal, he
gave the money to a Canadian citizen who had provided proof of
contact with Kilburn's captors.
   The Canadian said the $100,000 was a down payment and that with
it, he could arrange Kilburn's release for $1 million more, said
the Post, which did not identify the man.
   The Canadian contact took the money, but never came through with
his end of the deal and was later observed by the CIA in Damascus,
spending the money on high living, the Post said, citing
unidentified sources for the information.
   The Post said that a senior FBI official has told Congress that
then-FBI Director William H. Webster _ who is now CIA director _
approved the FBI's participation in the plan. The newspaper said
the plan also was discussed with Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   North has said repeatedly that he had express authority from his
superiors for his actions. But the White House has said Reagan had
no knowledge of any efforts to ransom U.S. hostages in Lebanon.
   North, who was fired from his job as an NSC aide in late 1986
following revelations of the secret sales of arms to Iran and the
diversion of profits from those sales to the Nicaraguan Contra
rebels, was indicted Wednesday.
   He was charged with conspiracy to defraud the government and
commit criminal offenses against it, theft of government property
and wire fraud arising from the diversion of arms-sales proceeds.
   He was named in nine counts charging him with obstruction of
Congress, making false statements, obstructing Meese's Nov. 21-23,
1986, inquiry by making false statements and concealing, falsifying
and destroying classified government documents in NSC files.
   Also indicted Wednesday were former national security adviser
John M. Poindexter and arms dealers Richard V. Secord and Albert
Hakim.
</TEXT>
