<1ST_LINE>r w PM-China-Missiles 1stLd-Writethru a0477 03-18 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Missiles, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0477,350</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said today that Saudi
Arabia's acquisition of Chinese missiles that can carry nuclear
warheads is a ``disturbing'' development that could harm the
security of all states in the Middle East, including Israel.
   ``The missile system would have a range which would include all
areas of the Middle East,'' spokesman Rudolph Boone said. ``It is
another part of a disturbing regional trend in surface-to-surface
missile proliferation.''
   ``The sum total of the proliferation is a degradation of the
security of all states in the region,'' he said.
   Boone said Saudi Arabia has confirmed it is acquiring the
missile system, which another official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said were Chinese CSS2-class rockets with a range of
2,200 miles and the ability to carry nuclear warheads.
   Several of the missiles are being installed, but it will be some
time before they are operational, the Washington Post reported.
   State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said the Saudi
government ``has assured us categorically at the very highest level
that Saudi Arabia does not have, nor does it intend to acquire, any
nuclear capability.''
   Redman told The Washington Post that ``the government of China
has stated categorically that it will not export nuclear weapons to
any government. We accept these assurances in both cases.''
   According to sources quoted by the Post, the Saudis began
negotiating to purchase the missiles from Beijing in 1985 after it
became apparent that the United States, the kingdom's principal
weapons supplier, would be prevented by congressional opposition
from selling Saudi Arabia up to 48 F-15 jet fighters.
   Congress agreed late last year to permit the sale of 24 F-15s on
a replacement basis to keep Saudi air strength at its current
levels.
   The CSS2 is believed to be an offshoot of the rocket used by
China to launch its first satellite in 1970. The Chinese have been
developing various military versions since 1979. Its different
models have ranges running from about 1,000 miles to 2,200 miles,
and the sources said the Saudis are believed to have acquired the
most advanced type.
</TEXT>
