<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Korea-PeaceCorps     03-18 0145</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Korea-Peace Corps,0149</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korea Beginning Own Version of Peace Corps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea will send its own version
of the U.S. Peace Corps to third world countries beginning this
year, government officials said Friday.
   The program, to be funded by both the government and the U.N.
Development Program, is aimed at transferring South Korea's
economic and farming expertise to developing nations in Asia and
Africa.
   The U.S. Peace Corp was created in 1961 by President John F.
Kennedy to send skilled American volunteers to developing countries.
   Under South Korea's program, the first group of 50 ``Youths
Overseas Technical Service Corps'' volunteers will be sent to
Indonesia, Thailand, the Philippines and other developing
countries. The program will cost $410,000 this year.
   South Korea plans to increase the number of volunteers to 300 by
1992. Each will serve two years abroad.
</TEXT>
