<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Smith-Belushi     03-18 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Smith-Belushi,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canadian Woman Who Injected Belushi With Drugs Returned Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The woman who admitted injecting
comedian John Belushi with the ``speedball'' of heroin and cocaine
that killed him returned to Canada after waiving a deportation
hearing, an official said today.
   Cathy Evelyn Smith, 40, was put on a flight to Vancouver by
Immigration and Naturalization Service officers, spokesman Ron
Rogers said. ``She was a voluntary deportee. We returned her to her
home country last night, where she is now free.''
   The onetime rock singer was paroled Wednesday from the
California Institution for Women in Frontera, 35 miles east of Los
Angeles, after serving 15 months.
   Facility superintendent Hal Tanner said Ms. Smith had been a
``model prisoner.''
   Ms. Smith was sentenced to prison after pleading guilty to
involuntary manslaughter and three drug charges in the Belushi case.
   Belushi, 33, was found dead March 5, 1982, in a bungalow at the
Chateau Marmont hotel on the Sunset Strip.
   Belushi, the portly comic who gained fame on the ``Saturday
Night Live'' television show and moved on to starring roles in such
movies as ``Animal House'' and ``The Blues Brothers,'' died after a
lengthy drug binge with Ms. Smith and others.
   Ms. Smith later admitted she and the comic injected
``speedballs,'' a mix of cocaine and heroin, but she denied any
responsibility for his death.
   She fled to Canada, but returned in June, 1986 and entered the
guilty pleas to reduced charges.
   Originally, she was charged with second-degree murder and 13
counts of furnishing and injecting Belushi with drugs.
</TEXT>
