<HEAD>Leprechaun Costume Means Aheadin' Home For Postal Worker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was St. Patrick's Day, but the wearin'
of a leprechaun costume meant ``go home'' for a postal worker.
   A supervisor at the Lansing Post Office sent Diane Horanburg
home after she showed up for work Thursday in costume.
   It was the third time she has been sent home for wearing holiday
clothes. She wore a Santa Claus hat for Christmas 1986 and a
pilgrim dress last Thanksgiving. She said she filed union
grievances both times.
   Horanburg said she wore the leprechaun outfit partly to make the
point that she can wear what she wants at work.
   ``You have to do something once in a while to break the boredom.
I'm not a robot,'' said Horanburg, 31, who helps operate a
letter-sorting machine.
   Don Harants, the post office's director of city operations, said
there is a policy against costumes or loose-fitting clothing that
can become caught in machines.
