<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     03-18 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Recess For Weekend, Seen Under New Pressure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMAD AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators trying to work out a settlement in the
Afghanistan war were reportedly under new pressure to reach an
agreement Friday after a statement released by the Soviet Foreign
Ministry.
   The talks recessed for the weekend, and U.N. officials said they
would resume Monday.
   An Afghan rebel leader said the Soviet Union was secretly trying
to contact the resistance to negotiate an agreement.
   In Moscow, Foreign Ministry spokesman Vadim P. Perfiliev said if
a settlement proved impossible in Geneva, Moscow's withdrawal of
its troops from Afghanistan ``will be performed differently'' from
terms agreed to this month.
   Those terms state that the 115,000 Red Army troops would be out
of Afghanistan in a nine-month span and that half would leave in
the first three months. The troops intervened in December 1979.
   A source close to the Geneva talks, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the statement was expected to add momentum to the
U.N.-mediated negotiations.
   A Pakistani source said the Soviet statement seemed designed to
pressure Pakistan into modifying its demand that a settlement be
linked to the formation of a new government in Afghanistan to
oversee a settlement.
   Pakistan represents the guerrillas in the talks.
   In Peshawar, Pakistan, Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, the new chairman of
the Afghan resistance, said the Soviets were trying secretly to
contact the insurgents.
   ``The Russians are willing to (talk) but secretly. They are
trying for it but secretly, not openly,'' Hekmatyar said.
   Hekmatyar also said that only an agreement with the resistance
would guarantee the Red Army's safe passage out of Afghanistan.
   The guerrillas do not recognize Kabul's Soviet-backed government
and have said the U.N. talks are useless because they don't
directly involve them and the Soviets.
   ``The Russians have to realize the fact that without an
agreement with the Mujahedeen it is not possible for the Afghan
crisis to be solved,'' said Hekmatyar.
   He said the guerrillas would stop fighting if the Soviet troops
withdraw unconditionally and abandon attempts to preserve the
communists' power.
   ``We will give them safe passage to leave Afghanistan ... if
they take the government they brought by their forces along with
them,'' Hekmatyar said. ``We will open the gates of Afghanistan for
them to leave.''
   If not, he said, the guerrillas will increase attacks on Soviet
bases and concentrate on their expected withdrawal route through
northern Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
