<HEAD>Now He Has To Care For Them</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANCASTER, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who commanded a pit bull to attack
trees was ordered to perform 40 hours of community service work
planting or pruning trees.
   Gerald E. Huber Jr., 20, will also have to pay for the
replacement of any of the 13 damaged trees if they die, according
to the order Thursday in Lancaster County Court. Restitution could
be as high as $1,545.
   Huber pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor charge of criminal
mischief. Police said on July 6 and July 8, Huber ``by verbal
commands and hand signals'' caused a 14-month-old dog named Davey
to attack the trees.
   ``Why would you do something like that?'' Judge Michael J.
Perezous asked.
   ``I don't know. I guess showing off,'' the defendant replied.
   Huber also was placed on probation for two years.
   Defense counsel Roy D. Shirk said that Huber told him he had
been drinking when he ordered the dog to attack the trees.
</TEXT>
