<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Thailand-Laos     03-18 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thailand-Laos,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Stalled Between Laos And Thailand On Border Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENTIANE, Laos (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disagreement over a 1907 border treaty
stalled talks Friday between Laos and Thailand to resolve a
frontier conflict that has claimed hundreds of lives.
   Thailand's ambassador to Laos, Niran Panupong, said both sides
have different interpretations of the treaty between his country
and what was then French-ruled Laos.
   In addition, Thongsi Intapon, a Laotian official of the Prime
Minister's Office, said Laos first wanted to define the role and
duties of a joint border committee proposed by the Thais before
such a body is formed.
   ``If we commit ourselves to that committee now, we will find
ourselves arguing in the jungles,'' Thongsi told reporters
accompanying the 15-member Thai delegation to the talks.
   The Thais want an agreement defining the location of the border
in the disputed wedge of hills between Thailand's northern
Phitsanulok province and Laos' Sayaboury province.
   Top Thai army officials have said 147 Thai soldiers and 402
Laotian troops died before the two sides began a truce and pledged
to enter into peace talks Feb. 19.
   The Thais say they will take the dispute to the World Court if a
bilateral agreement is not reached. But Thongsi said such a move
would be ``a last resort and not necessary.''
   He said the prime ministers of both countries want a speedy
agreement but added the talks could take ``quite a while'' if the
atmosphere at Friday's meeting persisted.
   The 1,030-mile border is poorly defined, and a similar
territorial dispute over three border villages led to battles in
1984.
</TEXT>
