<2ND_LINE>AM-Arafat,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Chief Attends Brother's Funeral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chief Yasser Arafat led about 1,000
mourners after Friday in a funeral procession for his elder
brother, a Cairo businessman.
   Mustafa Arafat, 62, died of liver cancer Thursday at the
Palestinian Red Crescent Hospital in Cairo, which is run by Fat'hy
Arafat, another brother.
   Yasser Arafat, 57, flew to Cairo for the funeral from the
Palestine Liberation Organization headquarters in Tunisia.
Officials he met afterward with Foreign Minister Esmat Abdel-Meguid
about Palestinian unrest in the Israeli-occupied territories and
efforts for MIddle East peace.
   Hundreds of uniformed police and plainclothes security men
guarded the mosque in suburban Nasr City and the 500-yard
procession route.
   The coffin, shoulder-carried by members of the Palestinian Red
Crescent Society in white and blue uniforms, was draped in the red,
black, white and green Palestinian flag. The Red Crescent is the
Moslem equivalent of the Red Cross Society.
   Yasser Arafat, wearing his customary khaki fatigues and black
and white checkered headdress, shook shook hands with mourners who
offered condolences outside the mosque. The funeral service
coincided with the weekly Moslem midday prayers.
   President Hosni Mubarak was in Sinai with Sheik Zayed bin Sultan
al-Nahyan, the visiting president of the United Arab Emirates, and
delegated former Prime Minister Aly Lutfy to represent him at the
funeral.
   Also among the mourners were Prime Minister Atef Sedki, other
Cabinet members and senior government officials, and leaders of
opposition parties.
   Mustafa Arafat was among the first to join his brother's Fatah
guerrilla group, the largest of eight factions in the PLO, nearly
25 years ago.
   The PLO chairman is known to have two living brothers _ Fat'hy,
the hospital director, and Gamal, who represents the PLO in North
Yemen _ and a sister in Cairo who is known by the code-name Um
al-Mumeneen, ``Mother of the Faithful.''
</TEXT>
