<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BicycleDeath     03-18 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bicycle Death,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dog Owner Charged in Cyclist's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROUND ROCK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have charged the owner of two
dogs with criminally negligent homicide after the dogs chased a
bicyclist who fell and died.
   Candelario Guerrero, 45, was released from the Williamson County
Jail on Thursday after posting $1,500 bond on the misdemeanor
charge, which carries penalties of up to a year in jail and a
$2,000 fine.
   Donald Carlyle Westbrook, 41, of Austin, who rode his bicycle 30
to 40 miles each day, died from head injuries, according to police
Officer Bryan Leath.
   Westbrook was riding near Guerrero's business Tuesday when two
dogs started to chase him, according to the police report. As he
sped up to flee the dogs, Westbrook looked back, lost control of
his bicycle and flipped over the handlebars, the report said.
   He died Wednesday. His heart was transplanted into an Austin
woman Thursday morning, and one of his kidneys was transplanted
into another patient.
   The dogs, police said, were used to guard Guerrero's automotive
repair business. Guerrero was at the business when the dogs got out
through an open gate, Leath said.
   Guerrero could not be reached for comment Friday. The telephone
at his business was disconnected; there was no residential listing
for him in Round Rock.
   Police Chief Wesley Wolff said the dogs were confiscated and
will probably be destroyed. One is a 1-year-old Doberman; the
second is a 2-year-old chow mix, according to police.
</TEXT>
