<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RapeOrdeal     03-18 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rape Ordeal,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tape Reveals Policeman Ordered to Rescue Rape Victim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALUMET CITY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tape-recorded police transmissions
indicate three officers who stood outside an apartment while a
12-year-old girl was raped didn't heed a supervisor's order to kick
in a door.
   The recording was played Thursday during a disciplinary hearing
for Officer James Horka. Horka is accused of waiting for the
building's landlord to arrive with a key instead of breaking down
the door to rescue the girl.
   The tape indicates Horka arrived outside the apartment at 4:39
a.m. on Dec. 20 and said over the radio two minutes later, ``We're
going to the back door; supposedly it's a home invasion.''
   The order to kick down the door came two minutes after Horka
told his superiors the girl's mother was ``worried for the welfare
of her 12-year-old daughter,'' according to the tape.
   Horka's supervisor, Sgt. Ernest Targonski, said, ``...you've got
to get in there somehow, so long as she states that the man is in
there. We've got to push the door in; push the door in.''
   But Horka and two other police officers waited almost a
half-hour before entering the home, the tape indicates.
   The girl was rescued when Officer Peter Miller arrived at the
scene and entered the apartment through an open back door.
   Hearings for officers Kevin Beasley and Daniel Surufka, who
arrived with Horka and were under his supervision, are to begin
March 28.
   Former Police Chief James Shutoski, who retired during the
controversy, recommended firing the three officers.
   Horka expressed confusion on the tape. He said of the mother,
``This girl is freaking out.'' When asked by the dispatcher whether
the incident was a rape, he replied, ``I don't know; I don't know
what this is right now.''
   Horka's attorney Thomas Tyrell says the tape proves Horka's
contention that he decided to wait for a key because he did not
know if the intruder had a weapon and would harm the girl or her
10-year-old brother if he heard police breaking in.
   Benjamin Valentine, 19, of Chicago, has been charged in the
assault.
</TEXT>
