<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ArtCollection     03-18 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Art Collection,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Western Art Collection To Go To Autry Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new Gene Autry Western Heritage Museum in
Los Angeles has purchased an 87-piece Western art collection worth
an estimated $8.7 million.
   The collection, which had been on permanent loan to Joslyn Art
Museum since 1967, contains works by 37 artists, including Frederic
Remington, Charles M. Russell, Albert Bierstadt and George Catlin.
   The Autry museum obtained the collection by a sealed bid to the
Enron Art Foundation at Enron Corp. headquarters in Houston. An
Enron spokesman declined to disclose the price or number of
bidders. A statement by the Autry museum also did not give the
price.
   The collection, assembled from the Western art holdings of
Knoedler Galleries in New York City, was purchased for an
undisclosed sum in 1967 by the Northern Natural Gas Co., an Enron
Corp. predecessor.
   Last May, the Enron Art Foundation offered the collection, along
with a collection of 113 works by Alfred Jacob Miller for $10.8
million.
   Joslyn said it would buy the Miller collection for $4.4 million,
but decided not to buy the Western collection. The museum has
another Western collection, appraised at $14 million, that was
donated by the Enron Foundation in November 1986.
   ``Under the circumstances that the sale was inevitable, I am
pleased that the material is coming to a museum,'' Henry Flood
Robert, Joslyn's director, said Thursday. ``It means the material
will still be accessible to the public in the future.''
   The Autry museum, named after the cowboy movie actor who now
owns the California Angels baseball team, is being built by a
charitable trust set up through the estate of the late Ina Mae
Autry, Autry's wife.
   The museum is to open in October with 52,000 square feet of
exhibit space on 13 acres in Griffith Park. It has a collection of
12,000 items, including Autry's personal holdings.
</TEXT>
