<1ST_LINE>r p AM-KansasDemocrats     03-18 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kansas Democrats,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Holds Organizational Edge in Kansas Caucuses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEW FERGUSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis holds a
slight edge in Kansas Democratic presidential caucuses on Saturday
based on an organization that even his rivals concede is strong.
   Dukakis, Jesse Jackson and Albert Gore Jr. all campaigned in
Kansas this week, trying to kindle enthusiasm among registered
Democrats and spur them to turn out at 117 caucuses. Kansas, with
only 39 national convention delegates, has been ignored until now.
   ``We've been organized in Kansas for eight months,'' said state
Sen. Paul Feleciano, Dukakis' state chairman. ``I feel very good
heading into the caucuses. I think we'll get 20 to 24 of the 39
delegates still to be picked.''
   State Sen. Joe Norvell, a Gore supporter, conceded Dukakis'
organizational lead in Kansas, but said, ``I do believe that, with
Sen. Gore's extensive campaign trip through the state, his efforts
could minimize what I would consider an early lead for Gov.
Dukakis.''
   Gore, lacking a big organization here, campaigned Wednesday and
Thursday throughout the state. The Tennessee senator won
endorsements from state Treasurer Joan Finney, the highest elected
Democratic state official, and a qualified endorsement from state
Chairman Jim Parrish.
   ``Were it not for my promise to the Democratic state committee
early on ... to stay neutral until the 19th of March, I'd be making
a public announcement for you,'' Parrish told Gore. ``I'm leaning
very much in your favor.''
   Jackson has had a better organizational effort in Kansas than
has Gore, but his supporters conceded recently they are not
organized in enough counties to garner a majority of the Kansas
delegates.
   Rep. Jim Slattery, who supports Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt,
said Friday his candidate would do well in Kansas, and he said
Michigan ``is a do-or-die state'' for Gephardt. Michigan's
Democratic caucuses will be held March 26.
   ``I always hate to make predictions that can be proven wrong in
48 hours, so I'll avoid doing that. I think they'll all get
delegates. Rep. Dick Gephardt and undecided will do well,''
Slattery said.
   Gore supporter Norvell also predicted a large uncommitted vote
Saturday, saying he thinks Kansas Democrats still are making up
their minds.
   ``I really do not see a front-runner in Kansas,'' he said.
   Democrats will caucus Saturday afternoon and vote for delegates
to the district conventions April 23 and the state convention May
14.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
