<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     03-18 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Threaten Action Against Planned National Protest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Friday threatened
strict action against organizers of a national strike set for
Monday, the anniversary of the 1960 Sharpeville massacre.
   Anti-apartheid organizations have called for a ``national day of
protest'' to mark the anniversary and to protest the recent
crackdown on major black opposition groups.
   The strike also had been intended to protest the scheduled
execution Friday of six blacks from Sharpeville convicted of
complicity in the 1984 mob killing of a black town councilor during
anti-apartheid riots.
   On Thursday, 15 hours before the hangings were to take place, a
judge granted a one-month stay of execution to the ``Sharpeville
Six.'' Instead of a mass execution, one black man convicted in a
separate murder case was hanged at Pretoria Central Prison at dawn
Friday without fanfare or an overnight vigil.
   Tsepo Letsoara, 24, was convicted of killing a black woman in
October 1985. There was no campaign to save him, and neither the
government nor its opponents has contended that his crime had
political overtones.
   Police commanders announced that reinforcements would be
deployed Monday in the Johannesburg area, where the strike is
expected to be most widespread.
   Calls for strikes are illegal under emergency regulations in
effect since June 1986. But on other ``days of protests'' since
then, hundreds of thousands of black workers and students have
stayed home.
   ``We are planning all actions humanly possible to prevent
persons from intimidating and preventing workers from being able to
do a good day's work,'' said Lt. Pierre Louw, a police spokesman.
   He said labor unions and other ``elements'' organizing the
strike were under investigation.
   March 21 is observed annually by blacks as ``Sharpeville Day''
to mark the day in 1960 when 69 blacks were shot and killed by
police in the township south of Johannesburg while demonstrating
against the pass laws. The laws restricting blacks' freedom of
movement have since been repealed.
   Anti-apartheid riots broke out in Sharpeville and nearby
townships in September 1984, starting a two-year period of
nationwide unrest in which more than 2,000 blacks were killed. The
councilor whose murder led to the ``Sharpeville Six'' trial was
killed on the first day of those riots.
   The five black men and one woman gained their reprieve when
Pretoria Supreme Court Justice Willem Human granted a one-month
stay of execution after receiving evidence of perjury by a
prosecution witness.
   The government said it ignored a massive international appeal
for clemency, leaving the case in the hands of the judge.
   Attorney Prakash Diar said Friday the defense team had already
begun preparing an application to reopen the trial and re-examine
government witnesses.
   The six were convicted under the principle of ``common cause,''
which held them responsible for the September 1984 death of town
councilor Jacob Dlamini because they were part of a crowd of 100
who stoned and burned him to death in Sharpeville.
   President P.W. Botha had rejected pleas from leaders of most
Western nations and from countries and organizations around the
world to grant clemency. The government said Human's decision
``proves the wisdom of the state president and his ministers in
deciding not to intervene in the due process of law.''
   Two Johannesburg newspapers reported Friday that Botha had
granted clemency three weeks ago to a black policeman who had been
sentenced to death for 1986 murder of a youth in Mamelodi, a black
township outside Pretoria.
   A spokesman for Justice Department said Botha had commuted
Constable George John Sindane's death sentence to eight years in
prison, and he was one of five people whose death sentences were
commuted this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880318-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 1415EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Space     03-18 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Space,0629</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Shuttle To Be Launched By June in Unmanned Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet scientists are working around the clock to
prepare the first launch of their space shuttle on an unmanned test
flight expected by June, officials said Friday.
   Alexander I. Dunayev, the head of the space agency Glavkosmos,
also said that the agency plans to use the actual shuttle, not a
dummy, in the test flight and that more than one of the craft will
be built.
   Dunayev's comments at a news conference were the most detailed
to date about the Soviet shuttle. The session was called to discuss
Thursday's launch of an Indian satellite by a Soviet rocket.
   The Soviets are believed to have been developing their own
winged reusable spacecraft since at least 1982, but Soviet
officials did not confirm the project until December 1984 and have
released little information about it.
   Dunayev said the first flight of the shuttle was imminent.
   ``We are now working quite energetically on testing on land, on
the surface, of the components. We are working literally round the
clock,'' he said.
   He refused to specify when the launch will occur, saying only
that it would be ``in the nearest future.''
   ``It is very important that this flight be very thoroughly
prepared so I would not get involved in some guesswork,'' Dunayev
said.
   However, another Soviet space official, speaking privately, said
the first flight would occur in the first half of this year.
Neither he nor Dunayev would comment on when the first manned
flight would occur.
   Dunayev said Soviet scientists were encountering difficulties
daily in preparing the shuttle, but he did not provide details.
   Western specialists on the Soviet space program have said the
flight would be unmanned and computerized. Dunayev confirmed the
flight would be totally automated because the Soviet Union believes
pilotless tests are prudent.
   ``With the development of manned spacecraft, the Soviet Union
prefers at the first stage automats,'' he said. ``And we believe
that for the sake of security of human life what is required above
all is to ensure that man survives.''
   He went on to imply that U.S. space officials were not as
concerned about astronauts' safety as the Soviets were. Seven
astronauts were killed when the space shuttle Challenger exploded
in January 1986.
   ``We pursue the fundamental objective: whether man is alive or
dead after the flight. On the basis of that we regard the
fundamental differences between the Soviet direction of development
and the U.S. part of development,'' Dunayev said.
   James Oberg, an American specialist on the Soviet space program,
said in a telephone interview from his home in Texas that the
Soviet shuttle may include a separable nose section from which the
crew could escape in an emergency.
   Soviet officials have said little about the size or other
characteristics of the shuttle. But the Soviet press has reported
the shuttle will be lifted into orbit by the new Energia rocket
booster, which can carry up to 100 tons of payload, more than the
U.S. shuttle.
   In its first test May 15, Energia successfully carried aloft a
payload, but the payload's own engines failed.
   Alexei F. Bogomolov, director of the Soviet mission control
center near Moscow called Medvezhyi Ozero, said in an interview the
shuttle will have on-board engines to orient the craft in space and
maneuver it through the atmosphere toward a runway landing. The
U.S. shuttle glides powerless to landings.
   The Soviet space chief said the Soviet Union plans a fleet of
shuttles.
   ``How many, it's difficult to say. It is clear that we will have
more than one,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880318-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 1417EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Trump-Plaza     03-18 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trump-Plaza,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Trump Buying Plaza Hotel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developer Donald Trump has a handshake agreement
to buy the landmark Plaza Hotel for $450 million, The Wall Street
Journal reported Friday.
   The Plaza's owners have agreed on basic terms with Trump and are
expected to sign a binding contract next week, according to sources
quoted in newspaper.
   A spokeswoman for Trump and a spokesman at Howard Rubenstein
Associates, which represents Trump, did not return telephone calls
seeking confirmation Friday.
   Another unidentified source quoted by the Journal said Trump was
the preferred bidder because it was believed he was most likely to
restore the hotel's luster.
   The 81-year-old landmark hotel was acquired in January from the
Allegis Corp. when Robert M. Bass of Fort Worth, Texas, and the
Tokyo-based Aoki Corp. bought the Westin Hotels and Resorts chain,
an Allegis subsidiary, for $1.53 billion. Bass owns 71 percent of
the Plaza; Aoki owns the rest. The Journal said a Bass spokesman
declined comment.
   The hotel, which overlooks Central Park at Fifth Avenue, can be
seen from Trump Tower on Fifth Avenue, which combines restaurants,
shops and apartments.
   The Plaza is expected to earn $22 million this year, which
industry professionals quoted by the Journal said is a meager
return for the price Trump is offering.
   ``I think anything over $350 million is high,'' Stephen Brenner,
a New York hotel consultant, said.
   In 1907, the Plaza opened as a permanent residency hotel and
later became a commercial hotel. A few tenants from before World
War II are protected by rent control laws and pay $200 a month in
rent.
</TEXT>
