<1ST_LINE>u a PM-AirborneAntics 1stLd-Writethru a0660 03-18 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airborne Antics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0660,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police: Two Accused of Having Sex on Flight; Two Threw Food</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with couple denying charges.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple accused of having sex on a transatlantic
flight were charged with public indecency, and two men who began
throwing food when a flight attendant intervened also have been
charged, police said.
   But the couple, a doctor and his wife, a lawyer and part-time
judge, say they were sleeping on American Airlines Flight 37 from
Munich, West Germany, to San Diego, and did nothing wrong.
   The four were arrested Monday when the jet made an intermediate
stop in Chicago, according to police reports.
   But Phillip Matin, who was arrested with his wife, Sharyn Jo Van
Tassell, denied the charges. ``This was the fantasy of a young girl
that is completely uncorroborated,'' he told the Sacramento
(Calif.) Bee. ``It's ridiculous.''
   Police said most passengers apparently were asleep Monday during
the eight-hour Atlantic crossing when a 13-year-old girl told her
mother she believed the couple across the aisle was engaged in a
sex act. The mother called an attendant, who notified a supervisor,
said Sgt. Jerry Thornton.
   The supervisor, Barbara Weiderman, told the captain of the
problem, and he radioed police to be on standby at O'Hare. At that
point, two other passengers ``became abusive and belligerent'' and
began throwing food and drinks at the flight attendants, according
to the police report.
   When the plane landed, police arrested Van Tassell, 42, and
Matin, 52, of Loomis, Calif. Both were charged with public
indecency; Matin was also charged with possession of a controlled
substance after authorities found eight yellow pills in one of his
bags.
   Matin said they were Valium and he couldn't prove they were
prescription drugs because the bottle they came from was in his
luggage.
   Roger F. Cline, 42, of Placerville, Calif., and Stanley Wells,
53, of Cameron Park, Calif., were charged with disorderly conduct
in connection with the food fight.
   All four missed the continuation of their flight to San Diego,
but paid the bonds set on their misdemeanor charges and were
released pending April court appearances, police said.
</TEXT>
