<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WesternWater     03-18 0158</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Western Water,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Low Precipitation Making Western Water Outlook Even Worse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Record low precipitation in parts of the West
last month has further reduced an already low water supply, the
Agriculture Department said Friday.
   ``We were hoping that precipitation levels would increase in
February and help ease the drought in sections of California,
Nevada, Montana, Idaho, Oregon, Washington and Wyoming,'' said
Wilson Scaling, chief of the department's Soil Conservation
Service. ``Instead, the situation has worsened.''
   The western water outlook is based on surveys by SCS and the
Commerce Department's National Weather Service. Western states
depend on snowmelt for about 75 percent of their water.
   Scaling said some areas are not affected by the dry conditions,
including ``very good'' prospects in Arizona, New Mexico and the
lower part of Colorado.
   ``These areas have had three wet winters in a row,'' he said.
``The soils are wet and there has been excellent carryover from
previous years.''
