<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Cholesterol-Stroke     03-18 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cholesterol-Stroke,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Low Blood Cholesterol Increases Risk Of One Kind Of Stroke</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Heart Test Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Very low blood cholesterol increases the
risk of one form of stroke, even though it decreases the overall
risk of all forms of stroke, researchers said Friday.
   A six-year study of 350,000 men showed that those with
cholesterol levels below 160 were three times as likely as others
to have a so-called hemorrhagic stroke, in which a blood vessel
bursts and the subsequent bleeding damages parts of the brain.
   The study's principal author, Dr. Hiroyasu Iso of the University
of Minnesota and the University of Tsukuba in Tsukuba City, Japan,
said his findings do not suggest any change in public health
efforts to get Americans to lower their blood cholesterol levels.
   ``Public efforts to lower cholesterol should continue, and our
efforts to understand the etiology (cause) of stroke should
increase,'' Iso said in presenting his results at a meeting of the
American Heart Association.
   Hemorrhagic strokes are less common than strokes caused by
clots, which account for 70 percent to 80 percent of all strokes.
   The increased risk of hemorrhagic stroke was observed only in
men with high blood pressure, but there might be a smaller increase
in risk in people with normal blood pressure, Iso said. His study
couldn't determine that, he said.
   The increased risk occurred in men with blood cholesterol levels
below 160 milligrams. Only 6 percent of the men he studies had
cholesterol levels that low, he said. The mean blood cholesterol
level in the subjects was 211 milligrams.
   Cholesterol levels below 200 milligrams are associated with a
low level of coronary heart disease.
   Levels over 240 milligrams double the risk. Twenty percent to 25
percent of Americans have cholesterol levels in this range,
according to the heart association.
   In Japan, low levels of cholesterol are more common, and
hemorrhagic strokes are more common, too, Iso said.
   Dr. William Kannel of the Framingham Heart Study in
Massachusetts said that study shows a similar risk associated with
low cholesterol, as does the Honolulu Heart Study directed by Dr.
Dwayne Reed of the National Heart, Lung and Blood Institute.
   Those researchers and others said, however, that the risk
associated with very low cholesterol is outweighed by the benefits.
   ``Nothing confers immortality,'' said Kannel. ``You're always
dealing with tradeoffs.'' He emphasized that coronary heart
disease, with its strong link to elevated cholesterol, is the chief
form of heart disease. ``Given that, I'd say get your cholesterol
as low as you can,'' he said.
   ``If you look at total stroke,'' said Dr. Lewis Kuller of the
University of Pittsburgh, ``there's no question _ the lower the
cholesterol, the better.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880318-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 1454EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gorbachev     03-18 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Says Soviet Can Learn From Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUBROVNIK, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union announced Friday
it will borrow political and economic reforms from Yugoslavia and
reiterated that it won't impose its policies on other communist
nations.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev pledged as he ended a trip to
Yugoslavia that Eastern European countries are free to follow ``any
paths to socialism'' without Soviet interference.
   This echoed speeches Gorbachev made twice last year but it
marked the first time he put such a pledge into a formal document.
   The declaration, also signed by Yugoslav President Lazar Mojsov,
brings the Soviet Union one step closer to abandoning, at least on
paper, the so-called Brezhnev Doctrine that tolerates no
alternative to Moscow's brand of communism.
   Gorbachev returned to Moscow on Friday after a five-day visit to
Yugoslavia that gave him a first-hand look at the country's
decentralized economy and at its ethnic divisions similar to those
the Kremlin confronts at home.
   The trip, one of his longest to a foreign country, included
detailed talks with communist leaders, factory visits in Belgrade
and a stroll Friday through the medieval buildings and sun-drenched
narrow streets of Dubrovnik.
   ``Proceeding from the conviction that no one has a monopoly over
the truth, the two sides declare that they have no pretensions of
imposing their concept of social development on anyone,'' the
declaration said.
   For the first time, too, the Soviet Union embraced the concept
of socialist self-management that had been developed by Yugoslav
leader Josip Broz Tito after he broke with Moscow in 1948.
   ``The two sides consider the development of socialist
self-management, in keeping with the specificities of each country,
to be of the highest importance,'' the declaration said.
   ``It ensures the genuine authority of the people and the freedom
of the individual and is a dependable guarantee against any
administrative-bureaucratic distortion of socialism,'' the
declaration said.
   Friday's document replaces agreements reached by both countries
in 1955 and 1956, when then Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev
signaled that the Kremlin might tolerate alternative ways to
communism.
   But in 1956 workers unrests were crushed in Poland and Soviet
tanks quashed revolt in Budapest.
   Soviet historians have hinted in past months that Moscow may be
willing to review its assessment of Czechoslovakia's attempt in
1968 to develop an alternative brand of communism.
   However, the present Prague communist leadership took power
after the reforms were crushed by a Soviet-led Warsaw Pact invasion.
   Therefore any reassessment of ``Prague Spring'' would have to be
sensitive to those currently in power.
   Friday's declaration indicates Moscow wants to borrow some
economic and political practices from Yugoslavia, whose position
between East and West has enhanced its international standing and
standard of living over the past four decades.
   Meat, dairy and fresh produce, often in short supply for
Soviets, are readily available to Yugoslavs who also have access to
Western luxury items, like the Sony Walkman which are still a
coveted prize for most Soviets.
   But triple-digit inflation has cut Yugoslavs' standard of living
by at least a third since 1980, placing many consumer items out of
reach of workers earning an average wage of $180 a month.
   A $20 billion debt has built up, and many Yugoslavs expect times
to get even harder after the International Monetary Fund completes
negotiations this spring on how to reschedule debt payments.
   Gorbachev indicated Tuesday he also would not favor too much
decentralization of his economy, telling workers at the Belgrade
factory that ``we have to maintain a regulatory role in order not
to make mistakes.''
   Friday's document said the Soviets and Yugoslavs will work to
develop political and personal contacts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
