<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Saudi-Missiles     03-18 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Saudi-Missiles,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Calls Sales of Chinese Missiles `Disturbing Trend'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration is assured that
nuclear warheads will not be placed on Chinese intermediate-range
missiles sold to Saudi Arabia, but the sale is still a ``disturbing
regional trend,'' the State Department said Friday.
   The department confirmed that Saudi Arabia had acquired Chinese
missiles with a range of 2,200 miles _ capable of hitting all areas
of the Middle East, including Israel.
   With Iran and Iraq engaged in a so-called ``war of the cities''
_ the lobbing of missiles against major population centers _ the
introduction of more rockets into the region has raised concerns in
Washington, spokesmen said.
   ``It is another part of a disturbing regional trend in
surface-to-surface missile proliferation,'' said Rudolph Boone, a
State Department press officer. ``The sum total of the
proliferation is a degradation of the security of all states in the
region.''
   The missiles were described as Chinese CSS-2 rockets, similar to
those used in China's limited space program in the early 1970s and
capable of being outfitted with nuclear warheads.
   ``Such a system is not in the interests of peace and stability
in the region,'' Boone said.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz expressed U.S. concern about
the sales when he talked last week with Chinese Foreign Minister Wu
Xueqian, spokesman Charles E. Redman said.
   Wu and other Chinese officials since then have told the United
States ``categorically that it will not export nuclear weapons to
any government. We accept these assurances,'' Redman said.
   Saudi Arabia as well ``has assured us at the very highest level
that Saudi Arabia does not have nor does it intend to acquire any
nuclear capability,'' Redman said.
   He said the United States was in close touch with Saudi Arabia
on the issue, as well as with other governments in the region,
presumably Israel.
   The United States and six other major industrialized democracies
have agreed not to export ballistic and cruise missiles capable of
carrying payloads of 1,100 pounds more than 187 miles.
   ``We've been actively engaged in an effort to get other
countries to join that regime,'' Redman said. ``All nations were
invited to join. In the case of the Chinese we have approached them
specifically on several occasions about discussing it, but we
really haven't had any response to that invitation.''
   According to other officials, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, Saudi Arabia sought the Chinese missiles after the U.S.
Congress blocked the sale of 48 F-15 jet fighters to the Saudis.
Congress agreed late last year to permit the sale of 24 F-15s _
enough to keep Saudi air strength at current levels.
   The administration has said Saudi Arabia needs sophisticated
weapons for defense against a possible widening of the 7-year-old
Iran-Iraq war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880318-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 1437EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-HondurasProtestsRdp 8thLd-Writethru a0701 03-18 0923</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Honduras Protests Rdp, 8th Ld-Writethru, a0701,0945</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands across Nation Protest Dispatch of Troops to Honduras</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 18th graf, `In Washington,...' with detail.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 300 people demonstrating against sending U.S. troops to
Honduras were arrested today after blocking federal buildings in
Chicago, Boston and in San Francisco, where baton-wielding police
officers waded into the crowd.
   More than 200 people were arrested in San Francisco, up to 60 in
Chicago and one in Boston on the second day of protests, police
said. Twelve men and 12 women were arrested for blocking traffic in
front of the White House.
   About 50 protesters were arrested in the three cities Thursday,
the day 3,200 troops were sent to Honduras in what the White House
called a ``measured response'' to Nicaraguan troops crossing the
border into Honduras.
   Four hundred protesters marched today in Chicago, chanting,
``Reagan sent the troops today, get them out is what we say.'' Five
hundred blocked entry to the Federal Building in San Francisco and
80 stopped traffic at a military recruiting office near the John F.
Kennedy Federal Building in Boston.
   The Chicago arrests, on misdemeanor disorderly conduct charges,
came after demonstrators pasted 8{-by-11-inch orange stickers on
first-floor windows at the Loop federal building and sat in
intersections, police said.
   Many of the stickers bore skull and crossbones, and the message
``Stop U.S. intervention in Central America.''
   More than 1,000 people marched Thursday night from the Honduras
Consulate to the Federal Building in San Francisco. In Minneapolis,
protesters burned the U.S. flag. A mock ``Central America War
Memorial'' was erected in Philadelphia.
   At Fort Ord, Calif., home of the 7th Light Infantry, wives of
some of the 1,200 shipped-out soldiers joined protesters at the
gates Thursday.
   ``Bring the troops home. No Contra aid, no war,'' the Boston
protesters chanted today as they marched. One person was arrested.
   ``We want to non-violently protest President Reagan's decision
to send combat troops to Central America,'' said the Rev. Michael
Curry of Cliftondale United Methodist Church in Sagus, a protest
organizer. Curry said the marchers were affiliated with the
ecumenical Pledge of Resistance group.
   ``I believe our actions in Central America are wrong,'' said
Lenore Azaroff, 22, of Somerville. ``I believe sending troops to
Honduras is the first step to another Vietnam.''
   More than 200 people were arrested today in San Francisco as
they blocked traffic and the entrance to the Federal Building.
Helmeted police at one point blocked a street, rerouting rush-hour
traffic. Protesters stalled three cars in streets near the
building, forcing police to push them to the side.
   At least half a dozen violent confrontations erupted when
demonstrators tried to grab police equipment, including batons.
Officers lashed back, jamming the batons in the demonstrators'
stomachs and chests.
   The arrested demonstrators were handcuffed with plastic ties,
photographed and booked on the street, then taken in police vans to
the Hall of Justice.
   Police said the demonstrators arrested today would be cited and
released by federal authorities, just as 25 protesters were
Thursday.
   ``I'm outraged by the administation's sending troops to
Honduras. This is to cover-up all of Reagan's mistakes. It's also a
cover-up to divert our attention from the indictments,'' said
businessman Peter Holbrook.
   Four key figures in the Iran-Contra scandal were indicted
Wednesday, the day the White House annouced the troop movements.
   In Washington, D.C., 150 to 200 people demonstrated in front of
the White House today, said police Officer Tom Randolph. Twelve men
and 12 women were arrested after the protest spilled into
Pennsylvania Avenue. They were to have been fined $50 for blocking
traffic, but that was cut to $25 for disorderly conduct because
they didn't use a vehicle, Randolph said.
   Hundreds of sign-carrying demonstrators marched through Beverly
Hills, Calif., Thursday shouting ``Hands Off'' and ``No War in
Central America.'' No one was arrested, although police cited two
motorists for excessive honking.
   Authorities in Phoenix, Ariz., arrested 24 people for
trespassing when they blocked the entrance to the downtown federal
building with a 30-foot-long homemade sign reading ``U.S. troops
out of Honduras.''
   In Minneapolis, 400 people wearing everything from business
suits to studded leather jackets dragged newspaper racks and
benches into a busy street, bringing traffic to a halt during the
afternoon rush hour.
   The protesters burned a U.S. flag and chanted slogans as they
crowded the streets. No injuries were reported.
   In Boston, 200 people marched in a circle and chanted ``U.S.
troops out of Honduras'' outside the John F. Kennedy Federal
Building. Police said six people remained inside after closing but
were evicted without incident.
   U.S. Rep. Peter DeFazio, D-Ore., joined about 200 people who
gathered outside the federal courthouse building in Eugene to
denounce the action by the Reagan administration.
   Protesters in Philadelphia erected a 30-foot ``Central America
War Memorial'' that mimicked the Vietnam Memorial in the nation's
capital. It bore the names of Central Americans killed in the
region's civil wars. About 200 people marched in front of the
federal courthouse.
   In Fargo, N.D., on Thursday, 60 people chanted, sang and carried
signs outside the post office to protest.
   At Fort Ord, a the base 90 miles south of San Francisco, the
demonstrators included a pregnant Renee Worthing, 21, wife of
soldier James Worthing. She carried a sign that said, ``Stop The
Lies.''
   ``I think the whole thing has just been a lie,'' she said.
``Every time a presidential election comes up, a crisis comes up
and the president runs to the rescue. The community is not going to
stand for this.''
</TEXT>
