<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Cyprus     03-18 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Cyprus,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Sees Hope for Settlement of Greek-Turkish Dispute Over
Cyprus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Friday he sees a chance
for significant progress toward settlement of the long-standing
dispute over Cyprus between Greece and Turkey.
   In a bimonthly report to Congress as required by law, the
president noted that the new special representative of the United
Nations, Oscar Camilion, visited Cyrpus shortly after the election
of George Vassilou as president in February and ``expressed his
hope that there will be progress in the near future.''
   ``We also have seen the development of a new climate between
Greece and Turkey as a result of the recent meetings between Prime
Ministers (Andreas) Papandreou and (Turgut) Ozal,'' the president
said.
   Cyprus has been split between Turkish and Greek Cypriots for 14
years. In 1983, the Turkish Cypriot minority, which makes up 17
percent of the population of 650,000, proclaimed a breakaway state
in the Turkish-occupied northern third of the Mediterranean island
nation.
   Vassilou, a leader of the 500,000 Greek Cypriots, was sworn in
as president on Feb. 28 and promised to seek direct talks with
Turkey. The Turks have about 30,000 troops and 65,000 settlers in
the northern part of Cyprus.
   Altough talks between the two sides had been deadlocked for two
years, Reagan said Papandreou and Ozal ``have resolved to increase
their cooperation and to work toward lasting solutions of the
issues dividing Greece and Turkey. We welcome this development and
resultant building of confidence and lessening of tensions in the
area.''
   These recent developments, he said, ``reinforce my belief that
there is an opportunity at this time to make real progress toward a
settlement of the dispute.''
   Reagan made his remarks in a letter to House Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas, and Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee.
</TEXT>
