<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma-Riot     03-18 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma-Riot,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Riot in Burma in Cassette Tape Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-government protesters set fire to a
downtown department store Friday as demonstrations over the playing
of music in a tea shop persisted in the capital.
   Hundreds of students and other protester demonstrated in support
of students at the Rangoon Institute of Technology who rioted March
12 after a dispute in a tea shop.
   One student died in the violence, which began when students
argued with villagers over what songs to play on a tape player.
   Police occupied the campus Tuesday and detained a number of
students suspected of fighting the villagers.
   Larger groups of both students and villagers resumed fighting on
Sunday and about 200 students set fire to seven buildings,
according to the Burma Broadcasting Service.
   On Friday, witnesses said more than 300 students from government
high schools gathered at a public park.
   They shouted anti-government slogans, and joined by outsiders,
wrecked government cars in the area. The protesters then set fire
to a nearby government department store. Traffic was paralyzed.
   Several arrests were made before riot police dispersed the crowd
three hours after the protest began.
   Student disturbances are rare in this southeast Asian nation,
which has been under Ne Win's one-party rule since 1962.
</TEXT>
