<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sweden-Elderly     03-18 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sweden-Elderly,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swedish Hospital Limits Cancer Treatment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hospital is not treating cancer
patients older than 70 with radiation because of a shortage of
nurses.
   The head of the Radiumhemmet cancer clinic, Jerzy Einhorn,
called the move ``an extremely painful decision,'' but said the
hospital lacked resources to treat everyone.
   Associate Professor Ulrik Ringborg, an administrator at the
Stockholm clinic, told the Aftonbladet newspaper that no one had
been turned away because of age since the decision was adopted
March 7. Some patients, however, were offered alternative
treatments to radium.
   The hospital's decision prompted an outcry from Prime Minister
Ingvar Carlsson and government health officials. ``No one in Sweden
should be too old to receive the treatment needed,'' Carlsson said.
   Health Minister Gertrud Sigurdsen called the age limit
``unacceptable and a violation of the public health care law.''
   Long waits are common for non-urgent treatments under the
socialized medical system, but the clinic's move appeared to mark a
new level in the hospital crisis. The employee shorage has been
caused by resignations of experienced nurses, who complained of low
salaries, overtime, stress and low status.
   Funds for public medicine are distributed by the governments of
each county. Most health care is free and financed with tax money.

</TEXT>
