<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SpaceStation-Europe     03-18 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Station-Europe,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>European Space Agency Finally Agrees To Join U.S. Space Station</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Space Agency has agreed after two
years of contentious negotiations to take part in the U.S. space
station project and provide a laboratory module to be permanently
attached to the Earth-orbiting facility.
   The agreement, approved by the 13-member ESA Council, provides
for cooperation in the design, development, operation and use of
the space station. The European investment in the module to be
called ``Columbus'' is expected to exceed $2 billion.
   The United States is currently in the detailed design stage of
building the space station, which is expected to be ready for
occupancy early in 1998. The estimate of U.S. costs has risen from
a projection of $8 billion made in 1984 to more than $30 billion in
current dollars.
   Japan also is expected t contribute $2 billion and Canada about
$800,000.
   Cooperation between the United States and ESA seemed doomed to
failure late in 1986 when the Pentagon announced it wanted to
retain its options for military research on the station. The
National Aeronautics and Space Administration had to assure its
European, as well as Canadian and Japanese partners, that no major
weapons systems would be placed aboard, although the research
option remains.
   NASA said the agreement ``marks the end of more than two years
of negotiations on the technical and programmatic framework between
the two agencies in the largest cooperative civil space project
undertaken.''
   In its decision Thursday, the ESA Council authorized director
general Reimer Luest to sign a memorandum of understanding with
NASA administrator James C. Fletcher in the near future.
   The memorandum of understanding is being reviewed by the Reagan
administration, then will be submitted to Congress for review
before it is signed by the two parties.
   It also has to be approved by each of the ESA member
governments: Austria, Belgium, Denmark, France, West Germany,
Ireland, Italy, Netherlands, Norway, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland and
the United Kingdom.
   In addition to providing the Columbus module to the space
station complex, the ESA also will furnish an unmanned free-flying
polar-orbiting platform for Earth observation experiments. The
United States is developing a similar platform.
   As a third element, ESA will provide a free-flying spacecraft
designed to accommodate long-duration microgravity applications in
the fields of fluid physics, life and material sciences, NASA said.
That spacecraft will be visited periodically by astronauts.
   The free-flyer will be launched into an orbit, compatible with
that of the space station, by an Ariane 5 rocket.
   Presidernt Reagan invited European participation in the space
station program in 1984 and NASA and ESA agreed the following year
on what elements would be provided by each agency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
