<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czech-Church     03-18 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czech-Church,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Czechoslovak Catholics Demanding Religious Freedom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholics plan to demonstrate March
25 in the Slovakian capital of Bratislava to bolster calls for a
free and independent church, religious sources said Friday.
   The planned demonstration was intended to back a petition
calling for religious freedom and separation of church and state.
That petition has been signed by 400,000 Czechoslovak Catholics,
according to Slovakian church sources in Bratislava and Vienna,
Austria.
   Cardinal Frantisek Tomasek, Czechoslovakia's Catholic primate,
has urged his flock to sign the petition. It has gained support
from religious believers throughout the nation, where bishops and
priests are paid with government funds and must receive state
approval before taking their posts.
   Demonstrators also will press for quick appointment of 10 new
bishops. Government officials have been arguing with the Vatican
over the vacant posts.
   No breakthrough has been achieved so far, and the talks are
scheduled to resume in Rome on April 11, a Czechoslovak government
spokesman said this week.
   The planned demonstration was announced in a letter to local
authorities by Franitsek Miklosko, a Catholic layman, according to
the Austrian Catholic news service Kathpress. Organizers of the
rally reportedly told authorities it will be peaceful with
participants lighting candles symbolizing their support.
   There has been no comment from the government on the planned
demonstration.
</TEXT>
