<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Robertson     03-18 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robertson,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Describes His Campaign As `Rallying Point For
Conservatives'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Robertson said Friday he is
staying in the Republican presidential race despite Vice President
George Bush's overwhelming delegate lead because ``there has to be
a rallying point for conservatives.''
   Otherwise, the former television evangelist told a news
conference, conservatives would lose their political leverage to
influence Bush on specific foreign or domestic policies or
influence his selection of a vice presidential running mate.
   ``If everybody drops out, then whatever policies are being
advocated by George Bush will become the policies of the Republican
Party,'' Robertson said.
   But, he conceded, ``if the trend continues, George Bush has a
pretty close lock on it, absent some unforeseen event.''
   ``Certainly I'm a realist and I can count,'' Robertson said,
referring to Bush's accumulation so far of more than 700 of the
1,139 delegates needed to win the GOP presidential nomination in
August. The Associated Press delegate count gives Robertson just 17
delegates.
   Robertson said he is continuing his campaign to further the
conservative principles of President Reagan.
   ``I'm a supporter of Ronald Reagan. I'd like to see the Reagan
policies of 1980 and the Republican platform of 1984 carried on to
1988,'' he said.
   Questioned about farm issues, Robertson said he wants ``a world
that is free of subsidies by the year 2000'' but that he supports
``some writedown of farm debt'' for family farmers. Robertson said
he would redirect agricultural subsidy funds from agribusiness to
family farmers.
</TEXT>
