<DOCNO> AP880318-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 2149EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Gephardt     03-18 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gephardt,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gephardt Brings 18 U.S. House Supporters To Michigan Campaign</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM IRWIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighteen members of Congress flew to Michigan
Friday trying to help revive the flagging presidential campaign of
fellow Rep. Richard Gephardt, who said, ``I'm the underdog today
but that doesn't really matter.''
   Rep. John Dingell of Trenton, Mich., said Gephardt's support in
the House was significant because ``we in Congress don't like
weaklings or phonies.''
   A new poll published Friday showed Gephardt well behind
Democratic rivals Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson in Michigan.
But the Missouri congressman said, ``I think you will see that the
Gephardt message about economic revival is going to get through to
the Michigan voters.''
   Gephardt, soundly beaten on Super Tuesday and then again this
week in Illinois, has pinned much of the future of his campaign on
the March 26 Michigan caucuses, which will allocate 138 of the
state's 150 delegates to the Democratic National Convention next
July in Atlanta.
   Eighty House members support his nomination, Gephardt has said.
Among the 18 who joined him Friday was Michigan's Rep. Dingell, who
said Gephardt's support among members of Congress reflected their
greater experience with him than with Jackson and Massachusetts
Gov. Dukakis.
   He ``is obviously a known quantity,'' Dingell said. ``We also
know how he responds in a crisis. We in Congress don't like
weaklings or phonies.''
   Gephardt dismissed a new survey, conducted for the Detroit Free
Press and WXYZ-TV and published in Friday editions of the
newspaper, that showed Dukakis and Jackson each favored by 32
percent of Michigan Democrats or others leaning toward the party.
   Gephardt was preferred by 10 percent of the 328 voters surveyed
earlier this week. Sens. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee and Paul
Simon of Illinois each had 6 percent support, and 14 percent was
undecided. The poll's margin of error was plus or minus 5
percentage points, the Free Press said.
   The candidate said he had overcome poor showings in surveys
prior to the Iowa Democratic caucuses and in other states.
   ``We're going to make political history in Michigan, just as we
did in Iowa,'' he said.
   Gephardt had also flown House colleagues in to help him in Iowa.
   That time, 42 congressmen flew on a chartered plane that cost
$15,500, an expense partially defrayed by lobbyists who flew along.
The plane ride turned into a flying fund-raiser, drawing pointed
comments from critics who noted that Gephardt was running as the
anti-establishment candidate.
   Gephardt spokesman Mark Johnson said Friday there were no
lobbyists on the plane this trip. ``You all make much more of this
than we do. This is just, send them out to a couple events and come
back.''
   The congressmen flew into Detroit on two planes, he said, one
belonging to Chrysler and the other a regular charter. ``The
campaign paid for it _ first class airfare for everybody,'' he said.
</TEXT>
