<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AmnestyLending     03-18 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amnesty Lending,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>El Paso Diocese To Lend Money To Some Amnesty Applicants</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Aliens-Amnesty Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illegal immigrants who find amnesty
application fees too steep will be able to get interest-free loans
from the Catholic Diocese of El Paso, the bishop said Friday.
   ``I think it's good for our community for these individuals to
become citizens,'' Bishop Raymundo Pena said. ``They would have
better opportunities to get good-paying jobs and that would help
our economy.''
   Under the program, people who apply for immigration amnesty
through the diocese's Migrant and Refugee Services program are
eligible for one-year loans if they live below the federal poverty
level.
   Under the Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986, people who
have lived in the United States illegally since before Jan. 1,
1982, are eligible for amnesty. Immigrants who qualify for amnesty
are granted temporary residency, and are eligible later for
permanent residency and then citizenship.
   The deadline for applying is May 4. The government announced
Friday it will give people seeking amnesty 60 additional days to
submit supporting documents.
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service charges a filing fee
of $185 per person or a maximum of $420 per family, plus a $75
counseling fee and a $10 photo and fingerprint fee.
   Applicants also must go to a doctor for a medical exam. Often,
they hire lawyers to help them, and the search for documentation
can become expensive. The INS justifies the fees by saying they are
a way to ensure that applicants won't become public charges.
   ``I think the government has a valid argument that they should
be self-sufficient,'' Pena said at a news conference. ``But illegal
immigrants get caught in a Catch-22 situation where they can't get
a work permit, so they can't get a job that pays enough money.''
   INS spokesman Art Moreno said the agency approves of the program.
   About 27,000 people in New Mexico and West Texas have applied
for amnesty so far, Moreno said. An estimated 10 percent of those
qualified for amnesty can't afford the filing fees, the Rev. Rick
Matty said.
   The diocese needs about $60,000 to fund the loan program, and
has raised about $12,000 so far from businesses and individuals,
Pena said.
</TEXT>
