<2ND_LINE>AM-Airborne Antics,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police: Two Accused of Having Sex on Flight, Two of Throwing Food</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple accused by a 13-year-old girl of having
sex on a trans-Atlantic flight were arrested, and two men who began
throwing food when a flight attendant intervened also were charged,
police said.
   The passengers were arrested when American Airlines Flight 37
from Munich, West Germany, to San Diego, Calif., made an
intermediate stop in Chicago, said Sgt. Jerry Thornton of the
police O'Hare International Airport unit.
   But Phillip Matin, 52, of Loomis, Calif., said he and his wife
were sleeping.
   ``This was the fantasy of a young girl that is completely
uncorroborated,'' Matin told the Sacramento (Calif.) Bee on
Thursday. ``It's ridiculous.''
   ``It was broad daylight, and there were people walking around,''
Matin said. ``Even at home with our kids, we are careful.''
   He and his wife, Sharyn Jo Van Tassell, 42, a lawyer and
part-time judge, were arrested Monday and charged with public
indecency.
   Police said most passengers apparently were asleep during the
Atlantic crossing when the girl motioned to her mother that she
believed the couple across the aisle was engaged in a sex act.
   The girl's mother summoned a flight attendant, who notified a
supervisor, Barbara Weiderman, Thornton said.
   Ms. Weiderman told the plane's captain, and the captain radioed
police to be on standby at O'Hare.
   At that point, two other passengers ``became abusive and
belligerent'' and began throwing food and drinks at flight
attendants, according to the police report.
   Roger F. Cline, 42, of Placerville, Calif., and Stanley Wells,
53, of Cameron Park, Calif., were both charged with disorderly
conduct.
   All four missed the continuation of their flight to San Diego,
but paid the bonds set on their misdemeanor charges and were
released pending April court appearances, police said.
   Matin, a doctor, was also charged with possession of a
controlled substance after authorities found eight yellow pills in
one of his bags. Matin said the pills were Valium but he couldn't
prove they were prescription drugs because the bottle they came
from was in his luggage.
</TEXT>
