<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merv Griffin's $225 million offer for Resorts
International Inc. has put him at odds with the hotel and casino
operator's flamboyant chairman, Donald Trump.
   Griffin Co., the former talk show host's private company, made
its $35 a share offer contingent on winning Trump's backing and his
agreement to end his five-year management agreement for Resorts'
Atlantic City, N.J., properties.
   But an attorney for Trump spurned Griffin's offer Thursday as a
``blatant attempt at market manipulation.''
   The New York real estate baron controls about 90 percent of
Resorts' voting power and is offering $22 per share to take the
company private. His lawyer claimed Griffin's offer was instigated
by another major Resorts shareholder seeking to force Trump to
raise his bid.
   Resorts' board decided Thursday that Griffin's offer was
``moot'' and reiterated its support for Trump's bid.
   In response, a spokesman for Griffin, who broke into the hotel
business late last year by buying the Beverly Hilton in Beverly
Hills for $100 million, said he is considering legal action against
Resorts' outside directors.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Fried Kemper cq in 8th graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau's ex-wife,
Margaret Kemper, has been charged with marijuana possession, her
lawyer said.
   The Royal Canadian Mounted Police charged her in provincial
court Thursday after seizing a package at her home.
   ``She denies the offense and is anxious to get this matter
cleared up in court,'' said lawyer Michael Edelson.
   Canadian Press news agency reported that police seized the
package after an informer in British Columbia tipped them off that
Ms. Kemper would receive one pound of marijuana in the mail.
   Ms. Kemper, 39, is to appear in court April 11.
   The jet-setting former first lady divorced Trudeau in 1983 and
married Ottawa real estate developer Fried Kemper the following
year, with whom she has one son.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Mayor Dianne Feinstein says she's
hoping to learn about big business in her new role as board member
of Bancal Tri-State Corp. and its Bank of California subsidiary.
   ``I'm a private citizen and not looking to make any political
decisions this year,'' she said Thursday after her election to the
board. It was her first professional venture since leaving office
two months ago.
   The new job is ``an opportunity for me to learn more about a
major business in the Bay area and the state of California,''
Feinstein said. ``I'm just a beginner.''
   The corporation expanded its board from 15 to 16 members to make
room for the ex-mayor, who attended her first meeting after her
election and was assigned to the trust committee.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Audrey Hepburn said she was
overwhelmed after visiting drought-plagued northern Ethiopia, where
millions are threatened with starvation.
   ``Let us hope that the spades we provide them will be used to
dig wells, not to dig graves for children,'' she said Thursday.
   Miss Hepburn, on a three-day visit in her first assignment as a
special ambassador for the United Nation's Children's Fund, said
she would appeal around the world for long-term development aid to
help Ethiopia overcome recurrent drought, as well as massive
emergency aid to stop this year's disaster reaching famine
proportions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DURANGO, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western novelist Louis L'Amour has won a
$55,000 out-of-court settlement against La Plata County and a power
company in a battle over a power line that crosses his ranch.
   Colorado-Ute Electric Association last August completed a
345,000-volt power line supported by three poles and a lattice
tower on L'Amour's 1,000-acre ranch in southwestern Colorado.
   ``I can't sit around trying to write looking at these
monsters,'' L'Amour said earlier. ``That's what these towers look
like _ monsters from Mars.''
   L'Amour has shunned 100 acres of his ranch because he fears the
power line poses a health hazard, his attorney, Russell Yates, said
Friday.
   The county agreed to pay L'Amour $4,000 and Colorado-Ute will
pay $20,000 to settle L'Amour's claim that approval for the power
line was arbitrary, Yates said. The utility also will pay $31,000
in compensation, he added.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VICTORIA, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cheered by about 150
flag-wavers, King Carl XVI Gustaf and Queen Silvia of Sweden toured
this province's legislature Friday.
   The couple received bouquets of flowers from well-wishers as
they walked up red-carpeted steps to be welcomed by Premier Bill
Vander Zalm and other provincial officials.
   Flowers in Sweden's colors of blue and yellow adorned the
rotunda and the legislative library where the king and queen
learned a bit of British Columbia history.
   The royal couple also met 85-year-old Britta Wickham, who moved
to Canada in 1923 from Sweden. Wickham called it a
once-in-a-lifetime experience.
