<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 2152EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MapleSyrup     03-18 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Maple Syrup,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sap Running Well So Far; Producers Keep Fingers Crossed</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY MITMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After two dismal seasons, many maple syrup
producers say the sap is running well this season and hope their
good luck will last.
   ``We've got it coming out of our ears. We've got so much sap we
don't know when we're going to get it all boiled in,'' said Nancy
Clark of Clark's Sugar House in Alstead.
   Clark's Sugar House, which usually produces about 1,000 gallons
a season, only made 620 last year. This year the trees have yielded
about 500 gallons.
   ``A year ago we were at 411 gallons,'' said Roger Adams of
Stuart and John's Sugar House in Westmoreland. ``This year we're at
1,250.''
   Last year, Stuart and John's produced only 1,400 gallons; in a
good year they produce up to 3,000 gallons.
   About 60 percent of the state's maple syrup is produced in the
Connecticut River valley, where producers are pressed to keep up
with the flow, said Agriculture Commissioner Steve Taylor.
   Prices have leveled at about $35 a gallon, Taylor said, adding
that even with a good season, he does not expect prices to drop
dramatically because demand remains high after the last two years.
   Annual maple syrup production in the state averages about 77,000
gallons, Taylor said. However, the last two crops yielded about
47,000 gallons, compared to the bumper crop of 102,000 gallons in
1984.
   The poor crops were directly attributable to a cycle of warm
days and warm nights. Without cool nights and warm days, sap
doesn't run.
   ``The weather has everything to do with it,'' Adams said.
   Though some producers experienced small sap runs two weeks ago,
this week's sunny weather following cool evenings had buckets and
pipelines overflowing.
   ``This last time it started running it doesn't seem it'll ever
stop,'' Clark said. Adams added that his two wood-fired evaporators
are ``going full tilt.''
   Liz Bascom, co-owner of the state's largest syrup producer,
Bascom's Sugar House in Acworth, said she was unwilling to predict
a banner year because a quick thaw could end the season as quickly
as it began.
   Shirley Sullivan of Broken Ridge Farm said the sap was running
so heavily that it almost guaranteed she would be working until
midnight.
   ``I like that,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
