<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-Honduras 1stLd-Writethru a0719 03-18 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Honduras, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0719,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Council Holds Urgent Meeting On Central America,
Nicaraguan Request</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS lede with 1 graf to UPDATE with meeting under way.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Security Council convened an urgent
meeting today at Nicaragua's request to discuss the
Nicaraguan-Honduran conflict and the deployment of U.S. troops in
Honduras.
   The 15-member council, the highest U.N. body charged with
maintaining international peace and security, was to hear three
speakers: Nicaragua, Honduras and the United States.
   In Washington, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said today
the United States supports the meeting.
   Asked if the United States would present ``show-and-tell''
evidence of Nicaraguan forces invading neighboring Honduras,
Fitzwater said the production of evidence is up to Honduras. He
stressed that the movement of American forces into Honduras was
strictly in response to a request of Honduran President Jose Azcona.
   The United States sent 3,200 troops to Honduras after charging
that Nicaraguan troops entered Honduras in pursuit of Contra rebels.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, meanwhile, was
studying Nicaragua's request to send an observer team to its border
with Honduras on a fact-finding mission.
   The meeting was called for information purposes and there were
no immediate plans for a resolution. The 159-member world body
usually votes with Nicaragua and other Latin American and
developing countries against the United States.
   On Thursday, Nicaragua's chief delegate, Julio Icaza Gallard,
sent a letter requesting an ``urgent and immediate'' meeting on the
U.S. action. Nicaragua's speaker was expected to be Rita Dalia
Casco, director of international organizations within the foreign
ministry.
   Earlier Thursday, Gallard denounced the United States during a
Security Council debate on British military maneuvers in the
disputed Falkland Islands claimed by Argentina.
   He condemned British ``buccaneers who pillaged our coast in the
past.''
   ``Nicaragua today is the vicim of the threats and aggression of
another American state,'' he said. ``It denounces, once again, this
gunboat policy which reflects disdain for our dignity and rights.
We must oppose them with the force of right, law, justice and the
decisive strength of international solidarity to win respect for
our sovereignty.''
   The secretary-general has urged all parties to exercise
restraint and abide by the Guatemala Accord, signed by all five
Central American nations.
   The council members are the United States, Britain, China,
France and the Soviet Union _ the ``Big Five'' permanent members
with veto power _ and Yugoslavia, Algeria, Argentina, Brazil,
Italy, Japan, Nepal, Senegal, West Germany and Zambia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
