<DOCNO> AP880318-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 1601EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Brazil-Dollars     03-18 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Dollars,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Recover Almost All Of Brink's Missing Millions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE HANDLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Friday announced they
recovered nearly all of the $8 million in U.S. cash that vanished
from a February air shipment from the United States to Argentina.
   It was the largest Brink's robbery in the history of the
company, which was protecting the cash.
   The money was recovered by narcotics agents working for Rio de
Janeiro's Specialized Police Department.
   Four suspects, all Brazilian employees of a private cargo firm
that operated at Rio's International Airport, were arrested.
   ``It's obvious they planned it together. We are going to
interrogate them to find out how they pulled it off,'' said Nilo
Augusto Batista, head of the Specialized Police Department.
   The suspects and the recovered money were shown to reporters at
the narcotics squad's headquarters, a dilapidated,
turn-of-the-century building in downtown Rio.
   The suspects, all appearing to be in their late 20s, hid their
faces from reporters and clicking cameras and refused to answer any
questions.
   The money was part of a $52 million shipment from the Federal
Reserve Board in New York to the Central Bank of Argentina, said
Marven Moss, a spokesman for Brink's Inc., based in Darien, Conn.
   The money disappeared Feb. 5 when 13 canvas sacks containing $52
million were transferred in Rio's International Airport from a
flight from New York to one to the Argentine capital of Buenos
Aires. Two of the sacks never made it to Argentina.
   Batista said the cargo company which hired the four suspects
``took the money out of the first plane, put it on a cart and took
it in for inspection by government officials. Afterward the money
was placed inside vans and taken to the second plane'' for the trip
to Argentina. Somewhere along the line $8 million vanished.
   He said the first break in the case came when the narcotics
squad of his department came across certain information about the
theft apparently from tipsters with connections to Rio's drug
trafficking world.
   ``Even though this case was, technically, not in the drug area,
our people followed the tip, and the result was nearly total
success,'' Batista said. He added that the dollars were traced to
the states of Sao Paulo, Espirito Santo, Minas Gerais and Rio de
Janeiro, where the thieves tried to exchange them, apparently for
other American dollars or for foreign currency.
   Narcotics Division Detective Antonio Carlos Estevam, who
coordinated the three-man team that arrested the four suspects and
found the money, said ``it was a combination of solid police work
and luck. We have no crystal ball.''
   ``Usually, when there is a large theft of money, most of it
gravitates to the drug world. This is the theory we operated on
after the airport incident. I would say we have achieved what no
police force anywhere else has ever achieved. We captured all the
suspects, recovered practically all the money and no one was
hurt,'' Estevam said.
   Estevam said the operation started Thursday when two of the
suspects were arrested in a car in the Ilha do Governador district
located near the airport. Later that day, two more suspects were
arrested and the money was recovered.
   Batista said the four suspects were Brazilians and that there
were no signs of involvement by foreigners. He added that none of
the money wound up in the hands of drug dealers.
   The recovered money belongs to Brink's, since its insurance
repaid the Federal Reserve Board for the theft, Moss said.
</TEXT>
