<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TreasuryTangle     03-18 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Treasury Tangle,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Come And Get It' _ Sure, But How Long Does It Take?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Treasurer Ann Richards has been
loudly urging Texans to claim long-forgotten money left in state
coffers, but Joseph Phillips is finding it hard to heed her call.
   ``How long does it take?'' Phillips, 48, asked Thursday, more
than seven months after first filing to reclaim $900 from the state.
   The money belongs to Phillips and his sister, Patricia Crawford,
and was part of a trust left by their father, who died in 1985. The
money was left erroneously to languish in a bank account and found
its way into the treasury under a law stipulating that accounts
inactive for at least three years be turned over to the state.
   The treasurer's office says there is no question that Phillips
should get the money. It is part of about $60 million owned by
75,000 residents and companies but held by the state.
   ``You can be assured that if you have money coming to you, you
will get it,'' Ms. Richards said at a press conference earlier this
month to publicize efforts to return the money.
   But Phillips was not assured: ``I thought, if they are that slow
in responding to me, how in the world are they going to handle more
claims?''
   Phillips first filed his claim with the treasury last Aug. 7
after a trust official told him about the money. In January, he
filled out another form. Later, he discovered his sister also would
have to complete a form, which took him several weeks just to
obtain.
   Three weeks later, after reading about Ms. Richards' news
conference, Phillips wrote The Dallas Morning News.
   A spokesman for Ms. Richards conceded to the News that the claim
had taken too long. He said the claim was complicated and that a
series of miscues, including a change of address by the Unclaimed
Property Division, caused delays.
   ``We are expediting a check,'' he told the News. Phillips will
get his check within four weeks _ after it's cleared by the
attorney general's office, he assured.
</TEXT>
