<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Simon     03-18 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Simon,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon Says He's In Race To Stay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID MORRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illinois Sen. Paul Simon said Friday he
is having trouble raising money but took a jab at better-financed
Democratic presidential rivals, saying ``If you're talking about
buying the nomination, I can't do that.''
   Simon, in Pennsylvania for a series of fund-raising events, said
none of the five remaining candidates in the Democratic field can
win enough delegates to claim the nomination on the first ballot at
the Atlanta convention this summer.
   Even Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, who has a narrow lead
in delegates, would need to pick up 80 percent of the delegates in
remaining states to have the 2,082 needed to win the nomination,
Simon told a news conference.
   ``That just isn't going to happen, so we're going to have a
wide-open convention,'' he said. ``I think you're going to see a
wide-open process and I think it's going to be a very healthy thing
for the country.''
   He acknowledged he is still having trouble raising money, but
said he expects to remain competitive and bring in more money as he
wins more delegates. Simon won his first primary on Tuesday in his
homestate.
   ``If you're talking about buying the nomination, I can't do
that. If you're talking about winning the nomination, I can do
that,'' he said. ``I intend to be in the race through Atlanta,
through November the 8th.''
   Earlier in the day, Simon met briefly with Gov. Robert P. Casey,
who has not yet endorsed a candidate for president and might not
before the primary.
   ``I really have to make a basic decision on whether or not to
get involved and that's the process I'm going through now,'' Casey
said.
   Simon said he would not seriously contest the March 26 Michigan
caucuses but predicted he would do well in the April 5 Wisconsin
primary and the April 19 New York primary, which is one week before
Pennsylvania's vote.
   Commenting on his chances here, Simon said, ``I am candid in
saying if there were a poll taken today in Pennsylvania, I'm sure
Paul Simon would not emerge on the top. But after the headlines and
the television coverage for Wisconsin and New York, you're going to
have a very different situation in Pennsylvania.''
</TEXT>
