<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 2157EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Spy     03-18 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Spy,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High-Ranking East German Leads Police To Alleged Spy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-ranking East German transport
official defected to West Germany and led authorities Friday to
arrest a suspected communist spy, officials and news reports said.
   The mass-circulation newspaper Bild said the woman was arrested
following the interrogation of the defector and was suspected of
having spied for East Germany.
   West German officials identified her as a secretary in the
federal Ministry for Economic Cooperation.
   Earlier Friday, security sources said Ulrich Fuchs, one of the
four deputy directors of East Germany's state-run Deutrans
transport company, had defected to West Germany.
   The sources, who requested anonymity, said West German
intelligence officials hoped to learn more about how East Germany
uses its long-haul trucks to spy on the West.
   Bild said the woman had access to secret documents provided to
the ministry by West Germany's intelligence service. The documents
dealt mainly with the situation in Third World countries, such as
Nicaragua and Angola, the newspaper said.
   The national television network ARD said the documents did not
contain military information.
   Alwin Brueck, a former state secretary in the ministry in whose
office the woman worked for some time, identified the suspect as
Elke Falk, according to ARD.
   Bild said the woman returned several days ago from a vacation in
Austria, where she may have met with communist colleagues.
   Hans-Juergen Foerster, spokesman for the federal prosecutor's
office, confirmed the woman's arrest but declined to link the two
cases.
   He said the woman, whom he refused to identify, was in
investigative custody. She is suspected of having supplied
information to a communist secret service since 1975, when she met
an agent known to authorities under the false name of Gerhard
Thieme, Foerster said. He declined to identify the communist agency.
   Bild said Thieme was an East German agent who recruited the
woman after seducing her. She is in her 40s and worked in the
ministry's European section since 1987, following other positions
in the ministry, the newspaper said.
   West Germany's counterespionage agency had placed the woman
under surveillance one year ago, Bild said.
   Several government secretaries have been unmasked as communist
spies in recent years.
   Margret Hoeke, a long-time secretary in the West German
president's office, was convicted of spying for the Soviet KGB and
sentenced to eight years in prison last August. During her trial,
Ms. Hoeke described how she began spying after falling in love with
an East Bloc agent.
   Sonja Luenburg, chief secretary to Economic Minister Martin
Bangemann, vanished in August 1985 and is believed to have fled to
East Germany.
   West German sources said Fuchs was undergoing interrogation by
counterespionage officials at an undisclosed location in West
Germany.
   They said Fuchs had also unofficially worked for the East German
secret service, ``but apparently was no big fish.''
   The sources added that further questioning of Fuchs could give
more insights into his activities for the communist secret service.
   But Bild quoted unidentified security experts as saying Fuchs
was one of the most important defectors in 10 years.
   The newspaper said Friday Fuchs defected in early March during a
business trip to the West.
   Bild said Fuchs knew ``everything about the secret spying trucks
of East Germany and the Soviet Union, he knows secret meeting
points for agents and courier methods used by communist spies.''
   Quoting an unidentified counterespionage expert, Bild said the
West Germans hoped to learn about the electronic equpiment built
into Soviet bloc trucks, the routes they take while traveling
through the West and about ``safe houses'' used by communist agents.
   West German security officials long have suspected East German
truckers of using their drives through West Germany to report on
military movements and gather other information for the East German
secret service.
   Bild said about 3,000 Deutrans trucks pass through West Germany
every month. The trucks are usually equipped with sensitive cameras
and electronic listening devices, Bild said.
</TEXT>
