<1ST_LINE>r w AM-North-Conservatives     03-18 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-North-Conservatives,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conservatives Launch Campaign For North-Poindexter Pardons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservatives launched a campaign Friday to
persuade President Reagan to pardon Lt. Col. Oliver L. North, with
one saying, ``Juries don't convict heroes who stand 10 feet tall.''
   ``Indicting a true American hero _ at a tremendous cost _ is
completely unacceptable and should be rejected immediately,'' L.
Francis Bouchey, president of the Council for Inter-American
Security, said in a statement issued at a news conference.
   In a related development, Pentagon sources said Friday that
North has asked to retire from the Marine Corps. North submitted
his request Thursday, asking that he be allowed to retire effective
May 1, when he will have completed 20 years of active military
service, the sources said.
   The conservatives said they have formed an ``Ollie North Task
Force'' to lobby for a pardon for North and John M. Poindexter,
former head of the National Security Council.
   Sen. Steven Symms, R-Idaho, sent a letter to Reagan asking him
to pardon North, Symms office said.
   The two former White House aides _ along with arms dealers
Richard V. Secord and Albert Hakim _ have been charged with
conspiring to defraud the government in the Iran-Contra episode.
The case involved diverting money from the sale of weapons to Iran
to the Nicaraguan rebels.
   Bill Kling of The Foreign Policy Project said he thought the
public supported North. ``Juries don't convict heroes who stand 10
feet tall,'' he said.
   North and Poindexter are a ``package deal,'' on pardons,
according to Andrew Messing, head of the National Defense Council
Foundation.
   But he and others refused to commit themselves to seeking
pardons for Secord and Hakim.
   Messing said Secord and Hakim were in a different category
because they were businessmen who stood to gain personally from the
Iran-Contra affair, he said.
   Marlin Fitzwater, Reagan's spokesman, said there have been no
discussions at the White House about possible pardons.
</TEXT>
