<DOCNO> AP880318-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 2212EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pool-Panama     03-18 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pool-Panama,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Head of Southern Command Says Panamanian Defense Forces Ruptured</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The following dispatch was filed by Frederick
Kempe of the Wall Street Journal, a member of a Pentagon press pool
covering the arrival of U.S. troops in Honduras.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PALMEROLA AIR BASE, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander-in-chief of
the U.S. Southern Command said he was skeptical that U.S.-backed
efforts to oust Panamanian strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega
would bring any quick results.
   ``Putting a time line on Gen. Noriega is probably one of the
greatest hazards of our profession,'' said Gen. Fred Woerner, who
was on an inspection mission to observe the arrival of about 800
paratroops from the U.S. Army's 82nd Airborne Division.
   He said this week's failed coup attempt showed that the
``solidarity of the Panamanian Defense Forces has been ruptured.''
   Woerner ruled out the possibility of using U.S. troops to help
bring down Noriega, something he said was a matter for the
Panamanian people.
   He wouldn't comment on whether the United States military would
respond if Panamanian President Eric Arturo Delvalle requested its
assistance in the future.
   Delvalle has been in hiding since his aborted attempt to fire
Noriega as military leader last month. Noriega responded by forcing
the ouster of Delvalle, but the United States still regards him as
Panama's constitutional leader. Noriega has been indicted by two
federal grand juries in Florida on drug-trafficking charges.
   Woerner provided a gloomy description of Panama's internal
situation in his brief remarks during the second day of maneuvers
here.
   ``The city is locked up. The economy has come to a standstill.
The people are afraid, intimidated. The normal political processes
are non-functioning. People are desperately struggling for their
basic freedoms,'' he said.
</TEXT>
