<1ST_LINE>r a AM-82ndAirborne-Families     03-18 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-82nd Airborne-Families,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Wives Await Return Of Husbands</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Honduras, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRING LAKE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bonnie Miskanin has been the wife of an
82nd Airborne Division paratrooper for six years. Two days ago, she
found out exactly what that means.
   Her husband, Sgt. Donald Miskanin, ``left for work about 4:15
a.m. Wednesday,'' she said. ``The day went on and everything was
fine when I noticed around 6 o'clock that he wasn't home yet.''
   Mrs. Miskanin, 27, said she called a friend whose husband was in
the same unit as her husband at Fort Bragg.
   ``She told me they had been deployed to Honduras,'' she said
Friday.
   The United States deployed 3,200 U.S. troops, 2,000 of them from
the 82nd Airborne, after reported incursions into Honduras by
Nicaraguan soldiers pursuing Contra rebels. The last of the troops
left early Friday for what is described as a non-combat show of
force.
   Mrs. Miskanin said 6-year-old Donald Jr. has been taking his
father's absence ``very rough.''
   As for herself, she said she had been drawing on the support of
friends, family and other Army wives.
   ``We just stick together,'' she said. ``We act like our husbands
are right here in the field.''
   Paula Arndt, 21, said she also relied on other Army wives since
the departure of her husband, Spec. 4 Chester Arndt, whom she
hasn't seen since Wednesday morning.
   ``The more the pressure keeps building, you have to let it
out,'' she said. ``You take it day by day. I'll be taking care of
my baby, doing my household chores, and doing a lot of praying.''
   As the last of the troops from the fort prepared to leave
Thursday, soldiers said they were excited but also nervous.
   ``I'm only 18,'' said Pfc, James Bullard Jr. of Shallotte, a
soldier since July. ``Yeah, I get scared. You don't know what's
going to happen. All I know is we're going on a readiness exercise.
I'm nervous, real nervous.
   ``But I signed on the dotted line, so I have to deal with it,''
he said.
</TEXT>
