<HEAD>Dukakis Campaigns in Michigan, Kansas, Criticizes Troop Deployment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DRAYTON PLAINS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate
Michael Dukakis criticized the Reagan administration's sending of
troops to Honduras as he split his campaign day Friday between
Michigan and Kansas.
   He spoke with junior high school students in Michigan, then flew
to Kansas, where Democrats hold party caucuses on Saturday. He was
returning Friday night to Michigan for appearances at union halls
with Sen. Edward Kennedy. Michigan's Democratic primary is one week
from Saturday.
   ``The whole policy in Central America is illegal,'' Dukakis said
at a news conference after addressing a student assembly at Mason
Junior High School in Drayton Plains, just outside Pontiac.
   ``Call back the troops and end this,'' he said.
   The Massachusetts governor said the assignment of troops to
Central America runs against agreements signed by members of the
Organization of American States. He said if he were president, he
would end aid to the Contra rebels and back a Central American
peace plan drafted by Costa Rican President Oscar Arias and signed
by five Central American nations.
   ``As long as you have an administration that's obsessed with the
overthrow of that government (in Nicaragua), the peace process
cannot begin,'' Dukakis said.
   On Tuesday, Dukakis had failed to win any delegates in the
Illinois primary. But despite gains in Illinois by favorite sons
Paul Simon and Jesse Jackson, Dukakis dismissed what some have
suggested is a growing possibility of a brokered convention, one in
which no candidate enters with a clear majority.
   ``I've always felt from the beginning that somebody would emerge
... from the primary process with a good plurality, particularly if
the field begins to thin down a little bit,'' he said.
   On other matters, Dukakis:
   _Urged a reduction in military spending through scaling back the
president's Star Wars space-based missile defense program. ``If
you're going to spend $6 billion on Star Wars, you can't spend $6
billion on housing,'' he said.
   _Spoke broadly about a change in U.S. policy in the Middle East,
saying the United States must show leadership in the region. ``My
secretary of state would have been pushing ahead as a follow-up on
the Camp David accords,'' he said.
</TEXT>
