<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PuertoRicoPrimary     03-18 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Puerto Rico Primary,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore in Person, Dukakis by Videotape Pitch for Puerto Rico Votes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate
Albert Gore Jr. on Friday sought the favor of Puerto Rico voters
ahead of their Sunday primary, saying he would consider allowing
the territory to be exempt from federal minimum wage laws.
   Gore, addressing potential delegates of the Popular Democratic
Party of Gov. Rafael Hernandez Colon, also said he favored letting
Puerto Rico decide itself whether to become a U.S. state.
   Gore appeared in person while another Democratic candidate,
Michael Dukakis, made a videotaped address in Spanish to the same
delegates. Dukakis said if he is elected, he would work to increase
payments to Puerto Ricans under the Medicaid, Aid to Families with
Dependent Children, and Supplemental Security Income programs.
   ``During the past several years, unfortunately, Puerto Rico has
not received from the federal government the help it deserves in
the fight for economic opportunity for everyone,'' Dukakis said.
   A main issue in the campaign is control of the local Democratic
Party. Both the PDP, which favors the political status quo, and the
rival New Progressive Party, which favors statehood, want to use
the party to win appointments and influence legislation in
Washington.
   Democratic and Republican primaries in this Caribbean island of
3.5 million located 1,000 miles southeast of Florida are set for
Sunday. The State Election Commission projects that 1 million
voters _ more than one of every two _ will cast ballots.
   The Democrats will choose 51 delegates, all of them officially
uncommitted.
   Fourteen GOP delegates are at stake in a winner-take-all vote
that George Bush is expected to dominate.
   Only Bush, who won the 1980 primary and is strongly linked with
the pro-statehood movement, organized a real campaign.
   On Friday in a telephone interview with a local broadcast
station, Bush defended the sending of U.S. troops to Honduras.
   ``We did the proper thing,'' he said. ``We are for freedom and
democracy. There is no question that Nicaragua invaded Honduras.''
   Puerto Ricans are U.S. citizens with most every right and
obligation except they cannot vote for president and do not pay
federal taxes. Puerto Ricans may, however, vote in presidential
primaries.
</TEXT>
