<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Knight-Ridder     03-18 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Knight-Ridder,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Board Plans To Make Batten CEO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Knight-Ridder Inc. board of directors said
Friday it plans to elect James K. Batten the company's president
and chief executive officer.
   The board would take that action at a meeting following the
annual company meeting April 15, said Frank N. Hawkins Jr.,
Knight-Ridder vice president for corporate relations and planning.
   The board also announced that Alvah H. Chapman Jr., who reaches
company retirement age of 67 on March 21, has agreed to continue as
chairman of Knight-Ridder at the board's request. Chapman has been
chief executive officer since 1976 and chairman since 1982.
   The holdings of Miami-based Knight-Ridder include 31 daily
newspapers, such as The Miami Herald, The Philadelphia Inquirer,
the San Jose (Calif.) Mercury News, The Charlotte (N.C.) Observer,
and the Detroit Free Press; eight network television stations, an
international business information services company, and interests
in cable television and newsprint operations.
   Batten, 52, has been president of Knight-Ridder since 1982. He
is also a member of The Associated Press board of directors.
   He worked as a reporter for The Charlotte Observer and spent
five years as a correspondent in Knight-Ridder's Washington bureau,
specializing in Southern politics and civil rights.
   He also has worked as assistant city editor for the Detroit Free
Press, executive editor of The Charlotte Observer, Knight-Ridder's
vice president for news, and senior vice president for news. He was
elected to the board of directors in 1981.
   Chapman joined the Knight organization in 1960, became vice
president and general manager of The Miami Herald, and was The
Herald's president from 1969 to 1983.
</TEXT>
