<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PoliticalBriefs     03-18 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Briefs,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis and Jackson Lead Pack in New York Poll</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and Jesse
Jackson appear to be far ahead of their rivals among likely New
York Democratic primary voters, according to poll results released
Friday.
   With a month to go before the delegate-rich New York primary,
the Marist College Institute for Public Opinion reported that 37
percent of the 459 likely Democratic voters surveyed preferred
Dukakis while 28 percent said they would vote for Jackson. The
poll's margin of error was plus or minus 5 percent.
   The remaining Democrats trailed far behind with Tennessee Sen.
Albert Gore Jr. at 5 percent, Illinois Sen. Paul Simon at 4 percent
and Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt at 3 percent. Almost 13 percent
of those surveyed were undecided.
   The final 10 percent opted for an uncommitted line that will
appear on the primary ballot. That line is the product of an effort
by elected Democratic county clerks, many of whom said they would
like New York Gov. Mario Cuomo to run for president.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tower Says Iran-Contra Won't Hurt Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iran-Contra affair shouldn't pose a
problem for George Bush's candidacy because voters are not
interested in the issue, former Sen. John Tower said Friday.
   ``I fully expect the opposition to use it on him, but I don't
think it's going to have a major impact. I think the electorate
will tend to focus on the problems of the moment,'' said Tower, who
served as chairman of President Reagan's special panel that
investigated the Iran-Contra affair.
   The issue ``has already been used in the campaign'' by Bush's
opponents for the GOP nomination, Tower said, but it has ``fallen a
little bit flat.''
   ``Admittedly that's among Republicans, who are probably a little
tired of it anyway because of the embarrassment to the Republican
administration,'' Tower added. ``They don't like to hear it brought
up.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Robertson Forces Say They'll Elect Louisiana GOP Chairman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of presidential candidate Pat
Robertson say they have won nearly half the seats on the Louisiana
Republican State Central Committee and on Saturday intend to elect
a pro-Robertson candidate as state Republican chairman.
   ``We elected 45 Robertson supporters ... and we have 20
