<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 2255EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SavingLives     03-18 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Saving Lives,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Announces New Steering Wheel That Moves With Driver On Impact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors President Robert Stempel on Friday
introduced a new car steering wheel designed to move with the
driver on impact and reduce injury in car crashes.
   Stempel told a conference of 1,000 road safety activists that
the steering wheel remains ``a primary source of injury in the
event of a crash,'' despite the collapsible steering column
developed 20 years ago.
   The new steering wheel has an energy-absorbing hub, the point
where the wheel meets the steering column. At this juncture in the
new wheel, six metal joints are designed to fold on impact and
enable the wheel to move parallel to the driver's chest. This
allows the wheel to rest against the body and move with it.
   ``That helps spread the force of the impact and reduces chest
injuries,'' Stempel said.
   Tests showed the new steering wheel also lessened injuries to
the abdomen and the face when those were the points of impact, he
said.
   The new wheel will make its debut next year in the Chevrolet
Cavalier and will be phased in on other models not equipped with
air bags.
   Stempel used the occasion to encourage the wearing of seatbelts,
especially in Massachusetts where a seatbelt law was repealed.
Thirty-two states require motorists to wear seatbelts.
   He also urged motorists to pay better attention to pedestrians
and motorcyclists, who comprise one quarter of the annual road
death toll.
   The three-day national conference, called Lifesavers, is the
sixth annual meeting of safety experts, state and city officials,
car makers and dealers, and representatives from the insurance
industry and law enforcement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
