<DOCNO> AP880318-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 1719EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>b w AM-North-Retire 2ndLd-Writethru a0786 03-18 0684</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-North-Retire, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0786,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Top 6 grafs with North announcement; picks up pvs 4th graf,
``According to;'' adds 4 grafs at end with stastus of request,
right to pension after conviction</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Col. Oliver North, the fired national
security aide facing trial in the Iran-Contra affair, announced
Friday he has asked to retire from the Marine Corps and said he may
subpoena ``the highest-ranking officials in our government'' as
part of his defense.
   North submitted his request on Thursday, asking that he be
allowed to retire effective May 1 when he will have completed 20
years of active military service, Pentagon sources said.
   That is the minimum amount of service required to retire with a
pension. With 20 years of service, North is entitled to a pension
totaling 50 percent of his base monthly pay, or slightly over
$22,000 a year.
   In a statement read in the office of his attorney, Brendan
Sullivan, North said the lawyer ``has informed me that the defense
against these charges may require him to issue subpoenas for the
testimony and records of the highest ranking officials in our
government.''
   ``That strikes me as a course of action incompatible with my
continued service as a Marine officer,'' he continued.
``Accordingly, with great sadness, I have tendered my request to
retire from the Marine Corps.''
   North, who wopre a civilian busines suit in place of his usual
ribbon-bedecked Marine uniform, refused an answer questions after
reading the statement.
   According to one official, who agreed to discuss the matter only
if not identified, North has available a substantial amount of
accumulated leave and probably will stop working as a staff officer
at Marine Corps headquarters pending his retirement.
   North was reassigned to headquarters in November 1986 after
President Reagan fired him as an aide to the National Security
Council.
   The sources said there was nothing to block approval of North's
retirement request.
   They noted that Rear Adm. John Poindexter, North's former boss
and Reagan's former national security adviser, exercised his right
to retire from the Navy late last year.
   North, Poindexter and two others were indicted by a federal
grand jury Wednesday on charges they conspired to divert Iranian
arms sales profits to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
   The 23-count indictment, which also named retired Air Force Maj.
Gen. Richard V. Secord and his business partner, Albert Hakim, said
the defendants organized, directed and concealed ``a program to
continue funding of and logistical and other support for military
and paramilitary operations in Nicaragua by the Contras'' at a time
U.S. law barred such action.
   North vowed after the indictment was returned to fight the
charges, declaring: ``I did not commit any crime.''
   North, a much-decorated combat veteran of Vietnam and graduate
of the U.S. Naval Academy, testified last year before Congress that
he always believed he had the approval of his superiors to take the
actions he did.
   Poindexter, during his testimony before Congress, said he never
informed the president of his decision to divert arms sale profits.
   The 44-year-old North is currently drawing a base pay of
$3,693.60 per month. Under military retirement rules, he will be
entitled to half that _ or slightly more than $22,000 a year.
   According to one source, North was technically required to
provide the Marine Corps with four months' advance notice before
retiring. The service is unlikely to balk, however, at granting him
a waiver of that advance-notice requirement, the source added.
   One Pentagon official said Gen. Alfred M. Gray, the Marine Corps
commandant, had already approved North's request and that it was
now awaiting only the approval of the Navy secretary's office.
   ``And that should come on Monday,'' said the source. ``This is
all very routine.''
   According to the Defense Department, the pension rights of North
and Poindexter are unlikely to be affected by the outcome of the
legal cases against them since both men served honorably for at
least 20 years.
   ``Generally speaking, a conviction does not affect eligibility
for a military pension,'' said Col. David Shea, a Pentagon
spokesman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880318-0203 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 0244EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MortonThiokol-Fire     03-18 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Morton Thiokol-Fire,0730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Vows To Fight Citations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OGDEN, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morton Thiokol officials said Thursday that
if five employees killed in fire while loading an MX missile motor
with fuel had followed company policy, they would be alive today.
   They said the crew ignored strict company rules and entered the
building during a phase of the operation that should have been
handled by remote control from a bunker a quarter of a mile away.
   ``We don't know why the people were in the building. By
procedure, they should not have been there. We have not been able
to come up with a reason ... we just don't know,'' said Robert
Lindstrom, a former NASA executive who directed Thiokol's internal
investigation of the Dec. 29 fire.
   However, in response to a question, Lindstrom said it was
possible that the crew had complied with procedures.
   Lindstrom said the company's probe resulted in the same
conclusion reached by an Air Force investigation, namely that the
explosive fire which burned 100,000 pounds of solid propellant and
destroyed the building was ignited by either a spark of static
electricity or heat from friction.
   The Air Force conclusions were expected to be released shortly.
   On Wednesday, the Utah Division of Occupational Safety and
Health cited the defense contractor for six safety violations and
imposed a $31,700 fine. The victims' presence in the building and
failure to use remote-control equipment were among the most serious
violations alleged by the agency, which characterized three of them
as willful and serious.
   Phillip R. Dykstra, vice president of strategic operations for
Morton Thiokol, said the state's contention that management knew
that crews occasionally were present during restricted operations
was not supported by facts.
   ``It's not true,'' Dykstra said. ``Our investigation shows no
one was aware that occasionally (procedures) had been violated..''
   Lindstrom said that during interviews with numerous employees,
one or two said crews had gone into buildings in violation of
safety rules. He said investigators did not pursue that issue
because their charge was only to find the cause of the fire.
   Dykstra contested UOSH's classification of the three violations
as willful, although the facts supporting the citations were true.
He said the company ``will avail itself of every legal avenue to
challenge these citations,'' a procedure which involves appeal to
the independent Utah UOSH Review Commission.
   The workers were withdrawing the core from a casting of the
first stage of an MX missile when the solid fuel ignited. The blaze
caused $6.2 million in damage to the building at the company's
Wasatch Operations plant 25 miles west of Brigham City.
   Morton Thiokol makes the missile's four stages, and the space
shuttle's solid-fuel rocket boosters, one of which failed when the
Challenger blew up in January 1986.
   The fire has held up production of the MX missile until the
cause and corrective measures could be determined. Ed Garrison,
president of the company's aerospace group, said Morton Thiokol
hopes to reach an agreement on corrective measures with the Air
Force within two weeks.
   He said those measures include removing the Teflon-coated steel
core at a slower rate to reduce friction, verification that the
motor is properly grounded to prevent buildup of static
electricity, and installation of instruments to monitor static
electricity.
   The cores, or forms, are removed after the propellant has been
poured into the casing and allowed to harden.
   The state agency alleged that the missile motor was not properly
grounded during the operation, though Lindstrom said the previous
shift had grounded the missile correctly. Because of extensive fire
damage, it was impossible to know whether the grounding had
remained intact, he said.
   However, he said static electricity can build up even when there
is proper grounding.
   It takes up to four hours to remove the 60-inch core from the
casing. After the initial phase, in which the core is lifted about
30 inches, crews are authorized to enter the building to remove a
hydraulic lift and attach the core to a crane that completes the
procedure.
   Responding to a question, Lindstrom said it was possible the
workers had completed the first phase of their task and were in the
building to change the equipment. If so, they were following
company policy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
