<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 2254EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BlackJournalists     03-18 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Black Journalists,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Journalists' Group Says Media Still Not Hiring Enough
Minorities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty years after the Kerner Commission accused
the news media of looking at the world ``with white men's eyes,''
newspapers and broadcast stations still are not hiring or promoting
enough blacks, a group of black journalists said Friday.
   Despite some industry attempts to improve black employment
prospects, ``what has resulted in far too many instances can simply
be characterized as a lot of motion and little movement,'' the
group's report said.
   The National Association of Black Journalists formed a panel to
compare the status of blacks in journalism today with 20 years ago,
when race riots prompted President Johnson to appoint Illinois Gov.
Otto Kerner to head the National Advisory Commission on Civil
Disorders.
   The Kerner Commission conclusion that ``the journalistic
profession has been shockingly backward in seeking out, hiring,
training and promoting'' blacks ``still rings true,'' said DeWayne
Wickham of the Gannett News Service, president of the NABJ.
   The panel, which Wickham said carried out its study over several
months, acknowledged ``substantial good will'' among news media
executives.
   But, Wickham said: ``We also found there had not been a lot of
progress. ... It would be wrong to stand here and say there has
been no progress. It would be equally wrong to say it is
significant.''
   The panel's recommendations:
   _Newspaper publishers should promise to double the number of
black journalists from 3.5 percent of newsroom employees to 7
percent by 1991.
   _Newspaper and broadcast industry foundations should deny grants
to college journalism programs ``which do not employ a single
full-time black member, or which does not undertake a serious
effort to recruit and retain black students.''
   _The National Association of Broadcasters and the
Radio-Television News Directors Association should join the NABJ to
form a task force to halt the decline in blacks working in
television news. A declining number of black men employed in
broadcast news caused the ratio of minority group members in the
field to drop from 15 percent in 1979 to 13 percent in 1986, the
panel said.
   ``Believing there is a possible relationship between the
deregulation of the broadcast industry and this sharp drop ... the
NABJ will monitor the compliance of television stations with
existing (Federal Communications Commission) regulations,'' the
report said.
   ``Where we are unsuccessful in bringing compliance through
negotiations, the NABJ will move aggressively to challenge the
licenses of broadcast stations,'' it said.
   Ernie Schultz, president of the RTNDA, said his group supported
the report's recommendations ``100 percent.''
   Wickham said copies of the report also would be sent to the NAB,
the American Society of Newspaper Editors and the American
Newspaper Publishers Association for comment.
   Dwight Ellis, NAB vice president for minority services, said,
``Blacks are losing ground in broadcasting. It's been documented.''
   He said that although the reason for the decline was unclear,
the NAB and the news editors were considering two remedies: an
advertising campaign to tell blacks about some of the less obvious
jobs available in broadcasting, and creation of an institute to
train minority group members for management.
   Lee Stinnett, executive director of the ASNE, said surveys show
that the number of minority group members employed in newspaper
newsrooms has more than doubled since 1978, rising from 1,700 to
3,600, or from 4 percent of the total to 6.5 percent, he said.
Slightly more than half the minority newspaper journalists are
black, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
