<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FCA     03-18 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FCA,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Pledges To Protect All Depositors, General Creditors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators on Friday pledged to
protect all depositors and general creditors of the thrift unit of
the troubled California-based Financial Corp. of America, the
nation's second largest thrift holding company.
   The announcement by the Federal Home Loan Bank Board came after
the company's disclosure, in a report filed with the Securities and
Exchange Commission, that its thrift unit _ American Savings & Loan
Association of Stockton, Calif. _ was insolvent under generally
accepted accounting principles.
   The bank board's promise, designed to provide the ailing S&L
with stability and stem a drain of deposits, goes beyond its usual
mandate of protecting deposit accounts up to $100,000.
   In the statement, the bank board also reaffirmed its support for
the management of FCA and American.
   FCA, based in Irvine, Calif., said American's net worth _ the
difference between assets and liabilities _ had fallen to negative
$106 million at the end of the year, compared with positive $244.4
million on Sept. 30.
   Under less stringent regulatory accounting guidelines, its net
worth was plus $69 million at the end of 1987, compared with $357.8
million at the end of the third quarter.
   FCA had previously revealed that its net worth had fallen into
the red, but this is the first disclosure that net worth at
American, FCA's main subsidiary, has fallen below the zero mark.
That happened when American concluded that repayment of debts due
from its parent company was not assured.
   FCA's annual report, filed with the SEC, also disclosed that
American had a drain on deposits of $493 million during the first
two months of this year. It attributed the drain to publicity about
the bank's problems and said the drain eased during the first 10
days of March. Deposits had totaled $17.1 billion at the end of the
year.
   The drain was milder than the severe run at American in August
and September of 1984, when the bank _ amid heavy operating losses
_ lost about $6.8 billion of its $25 billion in deposits.
   The bank board's sister agency for commercial banks, the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp., issued a similar promise on Thursday
protecting all depositors and general creditors of First
RepublicBank Corp. of Dallas, a bank holding company of about the
same size as FCA.
   However, the FDIC went a step further than the bank board by
pumping $1 billion into First RepublicBank.
   FCA on Feb. 23 asked the bank board for a $1.5 billion in
assistance as soon as possible. Karl Hoyle, a bank board spokesman,
said the request is under review.
   FCA, with $33.7 billion in assets, ranks second among thrift
companies only to H.F. Ahmanson & Co., the Los Angeles-based parent
of Home Savings of America.
   The bank board has tried unsuccessfully for nearly a year to
find another institution willing to take over all or part of FCA on
terms that wouldn't be too costly to the Federal Savings and Loan
Insurance Corp., the bank board unit that insures deposits.
   On-again, off-again talks with the thrift unit of Ford Motor Co.
broke down early in January.
   Because of its size, FCA is the bank board's largest single
problem institution, although the problems collectively of Texas
S&Ls are more severe.
   On Jan. 27, FCA reported a loss of $224.6 million in the last
three months of last year, bringing its 1987 loss to $468 million.
   Two weeks later, the bank board ordered it to sell off $2.5
billion in mortgage-backed securities to reduce its vulnerablity to
interest rate fluctuations.
   On March 9, the bank board, which regulates about 3,150 S&Ls
nationally, passed a resolution reassuring nervous Wall Street
firms, which had loaned more than $12 billion to American in the
form of reverse repurchase agreements.
</TEXT>
