<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-SalvadorElections     03-18 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Salvador Elections,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Delegation To Monitor Voting In El Salvador</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 19-member U.S. delegation selected by
President Reagan is heading to El Salvador this weekend to monitor
legislative and municipal elections that leftist guerrillas have
threatened to disrupt with violence, officials said Friday.
   ``The president strongly supports the people of El Salvador and
their democratic aspirations and is demonstrating this support by
sending this delegation,'' White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
said.
   A delegation member, Rep. John G. Rowland, R-Conn., said, ``Our
presence there is mainly one to deter any fraud (by the
participating political parties) and to objectively and fairly
report what we see happening.''
   Andy Fisher, an aide to Sen. Richard G. Lugar, R-Ind., said the
delegation will visit polling places in San Salvador and the
countryside despite the pinpointing of the polls as military
targets by the leftist forces.
   The delegation, headed by Lugar and Rep. John P. Murtha, D-Pa.,
was scheduled to leave Andrews Air Force Base Saturday morning and
return late Sunday night or early Monday morning.
   The U.S.-backed Salvadoran government of President Jose Napoleon
Duarte is holding elections Sunday for mayors and councils in the
country's 262 municipalities and for all 60 seats in the
Legislative Assembly.
   Leftist groups have vowed to obstruct road transportation during
the elections to disrupt voting, and said polling places will be
``military objectives.'' The rebels maintain that peace must be
achieved before any election is held.
   The main electoral opposition to the ruling Christian Democratic
Party is Arena, a rightist group.
   ``This particular election is a test for democracy, not only
because of the hazards proposed by the rebels, but perhaps because
many citizens of El Salvador, after five elections, have lost some
of their enthusiasm for democracy,'' Lugar said in a statement.
   The delegation will be briefed by State Department officials in
San Salvador before monitoring the elections.
   Additional members of Congress in the delegation are Sen.
Christopher Bond, R-Mo.; Rep. Mickey Edwards, R-Okla.; Rep. John
Kasich, R-Ohio; Rep. Beverly Byron, D-Md.; and Rep. Alan Mollohan,
D-W. Va.
   Other members of the delegation are Howard Penniman, an
elections expert with the American Enterprise Institute; Mario
Paredes, executive director of the Northwest Regional Center for
Hispanics in New York; Merom Brachman, retired chairman of the Ohio
Ethics Commission;
   Eugenia Kemble, executive director of the Free Trade Union
Institute; Susan Kaufman-Purcell, Council on Foreign Relations, New
York; John White, former Democratic national chairman; Devier
Pierson of Pierson Semmes and Finley, a Washington law firm;
   James Dyer, deputy assistant to the president; Edwin G. Corr,
U.S. ambassador to El Salvador; Fritz Korth, International
Foundation for Electoral Systems, an advisory member; and Betsy
Warren, principal deputy assistant secretary of state for
legislation.
</TEXT>
