<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Contributions     03-18 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Contributions,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Fund-Raisers in Firm With State Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Partners in a New York banking firm that does
business with the state of Massachusetts have given money and
helped raise more for the presidential bid of Gov. Michael Dukakis,
according to a published report Friday.
   A Dukakis campaign spokesman denied there was anything improper.
   Michael Del Giudice, general partner in Lazard Freres and Co.,
organized eight fund-raisers last June that raised $250,000 for the
Dukakis campaign, said The Boston Herald.
   And Jonathan O'Herron, a partner in the same firm, was co-host
of a fund-raising dinner, also in June, that raised $25,000, the
Herald said.
   Federal Election Commission records show Del Giudice gave the
maximum contribution of $1,000 to Dukakis, and O'Herron and his
wife each gave $500, the newspaper said.
   Lazard Freres was awarded a three-year contract Jan. 7 to advise
the state on fiscal management of construction of a third Boston
Harbor tunnel and the depression of the Central Artery.
   ``I think it's ridiculous to suggest that there is any
appearance of a conflict of interest,'' said campaign spokesman
Steve Akey. ``There is absolutely no connection between
contributions and contracts.''
   Akey said other members of the banking firm support different
candidates. And he said it would be impractical for the campaign to
refuse contributions from the thousands of individuals and
companies that do business with the state or operate under state
regulation.
   The subject of campaign finance has become a debating point
between Dukakis and a Democratic rival, Rep. Richard Gephardt of
Missouri.
   Dukakis has faulted Gephardt for taking money from political
action committees, while noting that his own campaign rejects PAC
money and contributions from registered Massachusetts lobbyists.
   Gephardt has defended his nearly $300,000 in PAC donations and
persistently raised questions about Dukakis' acceptance of
contributions from anyone doing business with the state of
Massachusetts.
</TEXT>
