<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Shamir     03-18 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shamir,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Says He Still Seeks Middle East Peace</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
insisted Friday that his country remains committed to seeking peace
in the Middle East despite his rebuff of a U.S. proposal for an
international peace conference.
   Israel cannot accept the proposal offered by Secretary of State
George Shultz because such a gathering would give Arab countries
and the Soviet Union a chance to impose their will on Israel,
Shamir said.
   However, Israel remains open to direct talks with the Arabs, the
prime minister said.
   ``This approach is enshrined in the Camp David accords, to which
we remain committed,'' Shamir said, referring to the settlement his
country made with Egypt in 1978 under U.S. auspices. ``They still
provide a workable blueprint for resolving issues between us and
our Arab neighbors, including the Palestinian Arabs.''
   The Camp David agreement called for a period of limited
self-rule for Palestinians in the occupied territories.
   About 250 Palestinians and their supporters demonstrated outside
the Century Plaza Hotel as Shamir addressed 750 at a luncheon of
the World Affairs Council.
   The chanting demonstrators carried signs protesting Israeli
troops' violent suppression of Palestinian unrest in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip.
   About 20 members of the militant Jewish Defense League staged a
counter-demonstration outside the hotel, but there were no
confrontations, said police Sgt. Larry McKinley.
   In the occupied territories Friday, Israeli troops shot a
protester to death and at least 25 others were injured in violence
that erupted after Moslem noon prayers. The death was the 101st
since the unrest began 3{ months ago.
   Shamir's Likud bloc, which shares power with the more liberal
Labor Party, rejects Shultz' proposal for a conference including
the permanent members of the U.N. Security Council. Such a meeting
would lead to demands that Israel give up territory it has held
since 1967 and considers vital to its defense, Shamir said.
   ``The Soviets have been pushing the idea because they know that
within this framework they can push a settlement favorable to
themselves and their Syrian clients,'' he said.
   Shamir, who arrived in Los Angeles on Thursday after talks in
Washington with Shultz, President Reagan and congressional leaders,
has sought to blunt criticism by some American Jews of his
country's action in the occupied territories.
   He reiterated that the picture of the Palestinian riots in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip has been distorted by the news
media, and said Americans shouldn't confuse the violence with
U.S.-style civil rights activism.
   ``It is war. It is an extension of urban terrorism,'' he said,
defending his troops' use of rubber bullets, beatings and live
ammunition.
   In answer to a question from the audience, Shamir said he
believed American Jews continue to support Israel despite the
controversy.
   ``I don't see any changes,'' Shamir said. ``I think the great
majority of the Jewish community in America supports the state of
Israel.''
</TEXT>
