<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-18 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow Falls In East Just Two Days Before Spring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow fell across a wide area of the East on Friday and much of
the nation's northern half had unseasonably low temperatures just
two days before spring.
   Light snow extended from Kentucky across West Virginia and Ohio
into Pennsylvania and New York.
   Snow advisories were posted in parts of northern Kentucky,
mountainous areas of Pennsylvania, and the northern mountains of
North Carolina.
   Rain showers extended from there to the Gulf Coast, scattered in
most areas but numerous in Alabama, Georgia and Florida.
   Temperatures were in the 30s and 40s east of the Rockies, except
for the Southeast, where it was warmer, and northern and central
Minnesota across to Upper Michigan, where early afternoon readings
were in the 20s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 21
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 82 degrees at Thermal, Calif. The
morning low for the nation was 8 degrees below zero at Gunnison,
Colo.
   The forecast for Saturday called for showers and thunderstorms
in Florida; snow from New England to the Great Lakes region; rain
and snow from Indiana to New Jersey; rain from Maryland and West
Virginia to eastern South Carolina, and scattered showers across
Washington state and western Oregon.
   Temperatures will remain below 40 degrees from eastern Montana
through the Great Lakes region and northern Ohio Valley to New
England, including highs in the 20s and upper teens from eastern
North Dakota through the upper half of Michigan. Highs above 60
degrees were forecast from the coast of Oregon and northern
California through the southern Plains to northern Florida; in the
70s across southern Florida; in the 70s to low 80s from southern
and central California to southwestern New Mexico, and the 40s and
50s across most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
