<1ST_LINE>u p AM-GOPPlatform-Conservatives     03-18 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GOP Platform-Conservatives,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Seeks A Conservative GOP Platform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Republican activists said Friday they
will fight to keep this year's GOP presidential campaign platform
true to conservative principles.
   They insisted their fight is not an effort to stop Vice
President George Bush, the front-runner in the GOP presidential
race.
   The group seeking to ``save the Reagan platform'' is spearheaded
by the American Conservative Union and Donald Devine, who recently
was ousted from a top post in Sen. Bob Dole's lagging presidential
campaign.
   ``This is not a stop-Bush campaign,'' Devine told a news
conference.
   But he repeatedly criticized a speech the vice president gave in
Chicago last week in which Bush promised a Bush administration
would press for a tough new code of ethics for government officials.
   ``Our purpose is to promote an agenda the Republican Party can
win on,'' said Devine, who was President Reagan's director of the
Office of Personnel Management from 1981 to 1985.
   To win in November, Bush must galvanize the support of
Republican activists who are overwhelmingly conservative, not shift
his policies toward the center, Devine and other conservative
leaders said.
   Daniel Graham, a retired Air Force lieutenant general who heads
High Frontier, a group pressing for development of the Strategic
Defense Initiative, said the Republican Party must take a strong
stand against cuts in the Pentagon budget.
   L. Brent Bozell III, chairman of the Conservative Victory
Committee, said the Republican platform ``must reaffirm that the
party is committed to the elimination of the ruthless Marxist
regime in Nicaragua.''
   Devine said efforts will be made to raise money for a
delegate-tracking system ``to identify the conservatives'' and
represent their views at the convention in New Orleans in August.
   Bush, in a speech to the Governor's Club in Chicago, had said he
was ``personally disturbed at the breaches of ethics I have seen in
the past few years in government.'' He said he would appoint an
ethics panel in the White House to draft a new code of ethics.
   Devine said Bush shouldn't have started ``talking about
something unnecessarily critical of Ronald Reagan.''
   ``I would think that a stronger Ethics in Government Act is one
that provided less discretion to independent prosecutors or
permanent prosecutors to make up charges,'' said Devine. ``We have
an Ethics in Government Act that says the appearance of a conflict
of interest is a felony. Now that's preposterous.''
   Bozell also criticized the Reagan administration's
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty with the Soviet Union and
claimed it has weakened support for anti-communist rebels in
Afghanistan and Angola.
   ``We're affirming the 1980 Republican platform, which is
unfortunately a far cry sometimes from the 1988 adminstration,''
said Bozell.
   Asked where conservatives could turn if they don't prevail on
the GOP platform, Devine said: ``Stay home.''
   Some conservatives believe they would be better off if they
relinquished the White House this year to a liberal Democrat such
as Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and reclaimed it in 1992, he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
