<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Colombia-Plane     03-18 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Plane,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rescue Workers Remove Bodies From Colombian Plane Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CUCUTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue workers on Friday removed remains
of the 138 people who died when an Avianca jetliner slammed into an
Andean peak, burst into flames and started a landslide.
   A Bogota newspaper, quoting an Avianca executive, reported
Friday that the Boeing 727-100 hit the mountain after it swerved to
avoid a collision with with another Avianca plane.
   But another company official said the cause of the crash had not
been determined.
   No Americans were reported on the domestic flight.
   Witnesses said the plane clipped trees before slamming into the
mountainside Thursday near Zulia, 50 miles north of Cucuta, where
it had taken off.
   A police inspector in nearby Campo Alicia, Augusto Bautista,
said the impact ``opened a hole that looked like a crater in a
volcano.''
   Col. Miguel Benedetti, civil defense director for the state of
North Santander, said Thursday night that there were no survivors.
The government and Avianca said there were 131 passengers and seven
crew members aboard. Both had given different figures earlier.
   The government said it had begun an investigation but recovery
personnel had not yet located the plane's ``black box,'' which
could provide clues to the cause of the crash.
   ``This tragedy has saddened many Colombian homes,'' President
Virgilio Barco said in a Thursday night speech on television.
   The plane took off from Cucuta, 250 miles northeast of Bogota,
and was to stop at the Caribbean ports of Barranquilla and
Cartegena.
   Rain, snow and rough terrain hampered rescue efforts Thursday.
Civil Aeronautics Agency officials said that work crews, some using
helicopters, returned to the crash site Friday.
   Bautista said the remains of the victims were scattered and many
passengers had been buried by a landslide touched off by the jet.
   ``It's not possible to recognize anyone,'' he said.
   Police, civil defense workers, Red Cross members and local
residents placed bodies in plastic bags and loaded them on
helicopters headed for Cucuta.
   The Bogota daily ``El Siglo'' on Friday quoted Raul Garcia, an
Avianca vice president, as saying that the pilot had swerved ``to
avoid a collision'' with another Avianca jet flying from Bogota to
Cucuta.
   Garcia was quoted as saying the two pilots communicated by radio
before the accident and that the second plane landed safely shortly
after the crash.
   He did not return phone calls to his office Friday.
   Airport officials at Cucuta would not comment.
   But Jairo Mejia, Avianca's director of operations, told the
newspaper ``we can't give too much credibility to speculation'' and
said the cause of the crash had not been determined.
   Local residents said the plane appeared to be flying low before
it slammed into 8,000-foot La Cuchilla peak.
   However, the operator of the control tower at Cucuta's airport,
Ivan Robayo, said the plane was flying normally and had not
reported any trouble.
   ``The pilot said he was climbing to 26,000 feet and soon after
that I lost radio contact with him,'' Robayo said.
   The agency said the passenger list included Monsignor Horacio
Olave Velandia, 44, the Roman Catholic auxiliary bishop of Tibu,
and at least 31 soccer players from two teams flying to a
tournament in Cartagena.
   The soccer teams were affiliated with the state petroleum
company Ecopetrol.
   Colombia's last major air crash occurred July 27, 1985, when an
air force transport plane went down in the Amazon jungle, killing
74 people. The military plane was carrying civilian passengers
because of an airline strike.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880318-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 2255EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RobbersFooled     03-18 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robbers Fooled,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elderly Man Outwits Burglars and Shoots One</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 84-year-old jeweler, threatened
at knifepoint by two men, led them to a cache of diamonds then
pulled a gun and shot one of them.
   The wounded man was quickly arrested. The other man was arrested
the next day because the jeweler knew him and showed police where
he lived, said the jeweler, Lou Marks.
   Police said they doubt Marks would be charged in the shooting,
in which one robber was wounded in the chest and neck.
   Marks' daughter, Mrs. Marion Macri, 59, who lives with him, said
the incident began Wednesday night with a knock on the door. Her
father opened the door.
   Two men forced their way in, threw Marks to the floor and told
Mrs. Macri to get down as well. They took $68 in cash from Marks
and about $20 from Mrs. Macri's purse. Then Marks, who sells
jewelry from his home, tricked them.
   ``I've got a lot of jewelry you can have. Take it and go,''
Marks said he told them. ``When I said: `Follow me, I'll show you
my diamonds,' I knew I was halfway home.''
   Marks on Thursday said he led them into his den. While they
looked at the jewels, he grabbed a .32-caliber gun he had owned for
20 years and never fired, he said.
   ``I said, `Lord, please let the gun be loaded' and it was,'' he
said. ``When I put my finger on that gun, I said, `Dear Lord you
have saved my life,' and I shot him point-blank. I let him have it,
right in the chest.''
   Marks shot at the other man but missed. Both men fled.
   ``I don't feel a bit of remorse,'' he said. ``They weren't going
to let me live.''
   Raymond Edward Sumther, 39, was under police guard Friday at
Bayfront Medical Center. He was charged with armed burglary
assault, police spokesman George Pickney said.
   Gary Glover, 30, was arrested Thursday on the same charge and
was being held on $15,000 bail, Pinckney said.
   Marks had led police to Glover, whom he said he had once fed.
The jeweler went to a motel where Glover often stayed, and when
Marks saw him he called police.
   ``You befriend a man and then he comes back six months later and
does this,'' Marks said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
