<HEAD>Quotes From Presidential Candidates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some comments Friday by candidates
for the presidency:
   
   RICHARD GEPHARDT, on the Michigan situation: ``I'm the underdog
today, but that doesn't really matter. I think you will see that
the Gephardt message about economic revival is going to get through
to the Michigan voters.''
   
   PAUL SIMON, taking a jab at his better-financed Democratic
rivals: ``If you're talking about buying the nomination, I can't do
that. If you're talking about winning the nomination, I can do
that.''
   
   MICHAEL DUKAKIS, on the Reagan administration's actions in
Central America: ``The whole policy in Central America is illegal.
Call back the troops and end this.''
   
   PAT ROBERTSON, saying he will stay in the GOP race as a rallying
point for conservatives: ``If everybody drops out, then whatever
policies are being advocated by George Bush will become the
policies of the Republican Party.''
   
   AL GORE, setting his sights on the presidency in 1988, not
beyond: ``Anybody who thinks I'm involved in a dress rehearsal will
find out otherwise. I'm in this to win.''
