<DOCNO> AP880318-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 2239EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SwallowsReturn     03-18 0717</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Swallows Return,0741</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>San Juan Capistrano Prepares to Celebrate Return of Swallows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON L. JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN CAPISTRANO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wonder both spiritual and
touristic will be played out Saturday at Mission San Juan
Capistrano when thousands of visitors scan the skies for returning
cliff swallows.
   In other urban areas, the small, noisy birds are considered a
messy menace. Their pilgrimage from Argentina to regions as far
north as Alaska goes unappreciated. Their mud nests are destroyed
before eggs are laid.
   But here the annual migration is considered a marvel, thanks to
a 1939 song that popularized a legend about a Franciscan padre
befriending the weary birds when an inn keeper smashed their nests.
   Some 9,000 swallow-seekers are expected to flock to the
cobblestone streets around the 212-year-old mission during the
annual celebration of the cleft-tailed birds' official return on
March 19, St. Joseph's Day.
   ``When you think about it, who really cares if they come back
every year? People are cyclical. It assures us that things are not
screwed up,'' said Alan Lieberman, curator of birds for the San
Diego Zoo, some 60 miles south.
   He added: ``I think it romanticizes love among the animals.''
   As legend has it, the swallows have failed the camera- and
binocular-toters only once, in 1935, when they were reportedly
delayed by a storm.
   Accounts of the swallows were recorded nearly from 1776, the
year Father Junipero Serra founded the mission. Leon Rene's 1939
song ``When the Swallows Come Back to Capistrano'' put the town on
the map.
   In recent years, the number of birds sighted on March 19 has
dropped from thousands to a handful. Mission and tourism officials
maintain that the shy birds are scared off by the welcoming hoopla.
   The insect-eating birds also are a victim of urbanization that
has turned the small farming town 60 miles south of Los Angeles
into a community of 22,500. Lush orange groves and mudflats have
become parking lots and condominiums.
   Instead of nesting in the shade of the renovated mission, many
of the white-bellied, brown birds set up house under the eaves of
buildings and freeway overpasses in outlying areas.
   ``The swallows, they don't come like they used to. There are too
many people here now and they scare them away,'' laments Paul
Arbiso, 92, the mission's gardener and bell ringer since 1910.
   Arbiso will ring four antique bells when he first sees a swallow
Saturday, kicking off an all-day party.
   The festivities should begin fairly early since the first birds
to complete the 6,000-mile journey from Goya, Argentina, arrived
several weeks ago, said Brian McInerney, director of tourism for
the mission.
   ``We've got about 1,500 swallows at the mission already,''
McInerney said earlier this week.
   The mission also has 50 workers answering inquiries from around
the world, said McInerney. Last year's event put about $50,000 in
the mission's coffers, he said.
   The local Chamber of Commerce said it does not keep a tally on
the birds' economic impact, but spokeswoman Jan Hessell said hotels
in the area are booked and merchants ready for the onslaught.
   ``People will buy anything with a swallow on it, and the mobs
have to have somewhere to eat,'' she said.
   The event has its detractors. Some bird experts argue that
migrating animals don't make or keep appointments.
   ``March 19 is a day people chose and I'm not sure the swallows
are aware of it,'' said Gerald Collier, a San Diego State
University orinthologist. ``They do come around the beginning of
spring.''
   He also points out that there are between 50 million and 100
million cliff swallows in the wild. ``So 1,500 come to San Juan
Capistrano,'' he said. ``Where are all the rest?''
   Some swallows will go to a shopping mall in nearby Mission
Viejo, where nests from last year await them under the eaves of a
department store.
   Hershey Gehris, the mall's general manager, recalls a different
attitude towards cliff swallows in Campbell, Calif.
   ``They used to fight them more than here,'' Gehris said. ``They
do things to your clothes that make you a little upset, and they do
marvelous things to the paint job on your car.''
   ``I think they're neat around here,'' he adds. ``But I don't
think I'd want them around all the time.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
