<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Armenia     03-18 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Soviet Officials Meet with Armenians, Azerbaijanis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven Soviet leaders, including the Kremlin's No.
2 man, met Friday with leading Armenians and Azerbaijanis to
express the ruling Politburo's concern about ethnic rioting that
killed at least 32 people.
   The news agency Tass said Yegor K. Ligachev, second to Mikhail
S. Gorbachev in the hierarchy, also met separately with a group of
workers from Nagorno-Karabakh, the predominantly Armenian region of
Azerbaijan that Armenians want to annex.
   Armenian protests last month to support the annexation touched
off a wave of unrest in the two southern Soviet republics. On Feb.
28, rioting broke out in Sumgait, a city of Azerbaijan, and
officials say 32 people were killed.
   Tass said that Moscow-based science and cultural figures of
Armenian and Azerbaijani descent were at Friday's meeting in the
Communist Party Central Committee.
   It said that at the session, ``serious concern was expressed in
connection with the developments in the Nagorno-Karabakh autonomous
region and the situation in Soviet Armenia and Azerbaijan.''
   Besides Ligachev, officials attending included full Politburo
members Lev Zaikov and Mikhail Solomentsev; candidate members Pyotr
Demichev, Vladimir Dolgikh and Georgy Razumovsky, and Central
Committee Secretary Anatoly Lukyanov.
   Among the Armenians and Azerbaijanis at the meeting were M.P.
Mchedlov, deputy director of the Central Committee's Institute of
Marxism-Leninism; F.K. Salmanov, first deputy geology minister;
S.A. Sitaryan, first deputy director of the State Planning
Committee; and K.N. Brutens, editor of a historical journal, Tass
reported.
   It said the meeting was ``at the recommendation of the
Politburo,'' a sign of official concern about the ethnic unrest.
   Tass said those attending came up with ``constructive
suggestions that were taken into account and would help handle in a
better way problems of economic, social and intellectual life in
the region.'' It did not go into detail.
   The agency provided no further information on the meeting
between Ligachev and the workers from Nagorno-Karabakh.
   On Feb. 26, Gorbachev appealed for ``civic maturity and
restraint'' in Armenia and Azerbaijan and pledged that the
policy-making Central Committee would review relations among this
vast nation's more than 100 nationalities.
   Armenian activists reported in telephone calls to The Associated
Press on Thursday that Armenians conducted a general strike in
Stepanakert, the main city of Nagorno-Karabakh, to demand
annexation to Armenia.
   The Armenian republic's official Yerevan Radio reported Friday
that 1,661 Armenians had arrived in Armenia from Azerbaijan since
the rioting in Sumgait. The radio report was monitored by the
British Broadcasting Corp. in London.
   It said a government commission under First Deputy Premier
Vladimir Movsisyan was in charge of helping the refugees
   Armenians are predominantly Christians, while Azeries, the
dominant group in Azerbaijan, are mostly Shiite Moslems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880318-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 2240EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     03-18 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some homes these days go begging for a buyer.
   But the reason has nothing to do with high prices or rising
interest rates.
   A new sales gimmick allows prospective home buyers to drive up
to a house, tune their car radio to an AM frequency and hear the
low-down on closets, bedrooms and that unseen swimming pool out
back without getting out of the car.
   The device has a range of about 150 feet and a tape that plays
for a couple minutes.
   Robin Stella, a vice president at Robert Stone Inc. real estate
agency, said Friday her company began using the talking house
device three months ago and sales this year are up 43 percent.
   Ms. Stella said the device deserves at least some credit for the
boost.
   The devices are used primarily to sell houses, but its
manufacturer, Realty Electronics in Fond du Lac, Wis., said other
applications are being discovered.
   ``We certainly envision a time when they are very common _ that
you pull up to a bank and hear about their interest rates; that you
go to a drive-in restaurant and hear about the specials,'' said
Scott Matthew, vice president.
   Already, some of the 10,000 devices sold have gone to car washes
with long lines that use it to peddle their waxes.
   Car dealers closed on Sunday employ it to entice buyers who go
window shopping. A shopping mall in Ohio is using it to advertise
mark-downs.
   The inspiration came from Disney amusement parks, where visitors
tune their radios to a certain frequency to find out more about the
attractions, Matthew said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
