<2ND_LINE>AM-School Rumble,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High School Calm After Two Days of Fights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUSTIN BURKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANTON, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police stood guard at a high school Friday
after two days of fights between ``jocks'' and ``burnouts'' that
began over control of a hallway hangout.
   Louise Gates, a spokeswoman at Plymouth-Canton High School in
suburban Detroit, said there was one minor scuffle Friday that
lasted about 10 minutes.
   Fights between student-athletes and burnouts, who students said
are distinguished by their leather jackets and rock concert
T-shirts, erupted Wednesday and Thursday.
   Administrators said the fighting began over use of a gathering
place known as ``the pit.''
   There were no injuries, but at least 12 students were suspended
for fighting, and school officials sealed off the pit, officials
said.
   About 20 officers from Canton and nearby Plymouth Township were
called in to restore order Thursday. Police declined to say how
many officers were at the school Friday.
   ``The amount of police that they brought in was outrageous. It
gave the kids a reason to keep going,'' said Reeder Singler, a
student at nearby Plymouth-Salem High School who also takes classes
at Plymouth-Canton.
   Singler, who doesn't align himself with either group, added:
``With the police here, it's just making things worse. Things would
have died down naturally, but now something might happen sometime
in the future.''
   He said the battle is ``not really over turf.''
   ``It's over discrimination of one group over another,'' he said.
The burnouts feel the jocks receive preferential treatment from
some administrators and faculty members, he said.
   On Thursday, the burnouts sent Principal Thomas Tattan a note
saying, ``We feel we should be treated with the same courtesy as
other peer and social groups. We believe you're taking the jocks'
side over the pit issue.''
   The two groups met Friday to try to resolve the issue, but the
meeting broke up when administrators tried to join the discussions,
Singler said. The groups will continue to talk, he said.
   Gates said administrators talked to both sides, but declined to
reveal what was discussed.
</TEXT>
