<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Customs-AIDAgreement     03-18 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Customs-AID Agreement,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seized Clothing To Be Donated To Needy African Nations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Customs Service has donated about $20
million in clothing to three African nations through an agreement
with the Agency for International Development, officials said
Thursday.
   The agreement, signed by Customs Commissioner William von Raab
and AID Administrator Alan Woods, establishes a permanent program
allowing the transfer of seized textile merchandise for
humanitarian distribution.
   ``This is a true case of government triumphing over its own
bureaucracy,'' said von Raab, noting that ``it benefits more than
the egos of government officials. Someone will actually benefit
from this.''
   Previously, Customs had no recourse but to spend ``hundreds of
thousands of taxpayers' dollars to destroy this clothing,'' von
Raab said.
   A major shipment of clothing was seized after the People's
Republic of China alerted Customs that counterfeit documents were
being used to bring the items into the country.
   The clothing includes cotton jeans, shirts, dresses, denim
jackets and infants' cotton shirts manufactured in China.
   AID will turn the clothing over to World Vision Relief
Organization and the Adventist Development and Relief Agency for
distribution in Mozambique, Malawi and Zimbabwe, where it is
expected to clothe 20,000 children.
</TEXT>
