<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OrdDivision     03-18 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ord Division,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The 7th Infantry Light is Designed to Move Fast</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Nicaragua Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT ORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The soldiers who left Fort Ord for
Honduras are members of the 7th Light Infantry Division, designed
for quick airlifts to any part of the world on short notice.
   Some members of the so-called Bayonet Division have been trained
in warfare in Saudi Arabia, the Sinai Desert, Korea, Panama and
Honduras.
   In October 1985, the 7th was incorporated into the military's
Rapid Deployment Force and became the Army's first modern light
division. It is one of four light infantry divisions in the Army;
the others are based in Hawaii, Alaska and New York.
   ``A light infantry division is designed for low- to
mid-intensity combat,'' said Capt. Guy Shields, Fort Ord spokesman.
   Shields said the entire Fort Ord division of 11,400 soldiers can
be moved in less than six days. A description of the 7th Light
issued by Fort Ord says ``initial combat elements can be in a
potential crisis area in less than 18 hours.''
   The description also calls the 7th Light ``an offensively
oriented, highly responsive combat division deployable three times
faster than existing infantry divisions.''
   The units at Fort Ord consist of nine infantry battalions. They
have fewer vehicles, less equipment and fewer soldiers than
standard infantry divisions, and thus are able to move faster, in
500 airlifts instead of about 1,200.
   In March 1986, 200 Fort Ord soldiers were sent to Honduras for
U.S. and Honduran military exercises known as Big Pine. They were
stationed near the Nicaraguan border about 100 miles from the site
of skirmishes between the Nicaraguan army and the Contras, and
practiced troop deployment.
   The Fort Ord troops brought some vehicles and personal weapons
such as M-16A1 rifles and sidearms, but were cautioned to avoid any
real combat.
   In March 1987, 750 soldiers from the division were sent to
Honduras for several weeks of field exercises with Honduran troops.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
