<DOCNO> AP880318-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 2013EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Washington-Democrats     03-18 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Washington-Democrats,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Still Leading In Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
continued to hold a lead Friday as Washington state Democrats were
wrapping up their tally of results from precinct caucuses.
   With nearly complete results from five congressional districts,
Dukakis had won support from 3,784, or 44.6 percent, of the
delegates elected to county conventions, which will be held in
April. Jesse Jackson was supported by 3,083, or 36.3 percent, of
the county delegates and 1,074, or 12.7 percent, were uncommitted.
   Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois won support from 300 county
convention delegates, while 166 supported Tennessee Sen. Albert
Gore Jr. and 78 supported Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt.
   If these figures hold up through the congressional district
conventions next month, Dukakis will receive 14 delegates to the
Democratic National Convention this summer, Jackson will get nine
delegates and another five will be uncommitted.
   Washington Democrats met in party caucuses on March 8, but
results have not been available until now.
   The state party refused to release partial results from the
remaining three congressional districts. Those results are expected
next week.
   The precinct caucuses elected delegates to the county
conventions, where delegates to the conventions in each of the
state's eight congressional districts will be chosen. Those
conventions will pick a total of 43 national convention delegates,
and those delegates will meet later to choose another 22 delegates.
   In all, Washington state will send 73 delegates to the
Democratic National Convention, including 65 chosen through the
caucus process. In addition, Gov. Booth Gardner and seven
Democratic National Committee members from the state automatically
hold seats as delegates to the convention.
</TEXT>
