<1ST_LINE>u i AM-US-UN-PLO     03-18 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-UN-PLO,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Says UN Should Sue to Keep Mission Open</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PLO envoy told an emergency General
Assembly session Friday the United Nations should file suit to keep
his mission open if the United States tries to close it.
   Some diplomats said the world body should consider fighting the
U.S. government in American courts and provide alternative
accommodations for the Palestine Liberation Organization on U.N.
international territory. The PLO has observer status at the United
Nations.
   PLO observer Zehdi Labib Terzi and other speakers denounced the
U.S. Justice Department decision to close the mission under a new
anti-terrorism act, saying the move conflicts with U.S. treaty
obligations to the United Nations. The U.S. State Department has
opposed the closure.
   The Justice Department says it will take legal action if the
mission is not closed by March 21, the effective date of the law.
It is not expected to be closed by Monday and litigation is
expected.
   Terzi said Israel also should be denied its place at the United
Nations if the mission is closed. The United Nations regards the
PLO as the sole legitimate representative of the Palestinian
people, but Israel and the United States consider it a terrorist
organization.
   ``We deem it proper the General Assembly should ask the
secretary-general ... to take all steps, including legal steps if
necessary, to ensure the PLO observer mission be able to discharge
its official functions without hindrance,'' Terzi said.
   It was the second emergency session on the PLO issue this month
and the 159-member assembly is to consider draft resolutions
condemning the U.S. action. General Assembly resolutions carry the
moral weight of world opinion but are not binding on the
membership, as are those of the Security Council.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
