<1ST_LINE>b w AM-US-Panama 3rdAdd a0869 03-18 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama, 3rd Add, a0869,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>WASHN: Panama Canal.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ABC News reported Friday night that unidentified U.S. and
Central American sources say Noriega has signed off on most parts
of a package that will allow some face-saving for him, but will get
him out of office and out of Panama.
   The United States has applied economic pressure, including
blocking the transfer of currency to Panama and withholding Panama
Canal fees, in an attempt to encourage the ouster of Noriega. The
political opposition has sought to get rid of the de facto leader
of Panama for months.
   The United States stepped up its actions against Noriega after
Noriega deposed President Eric Arturo Delvalle on Feb. 25. Delvalle
had tried to fire Noriega. The United States still recognizes
Delvalle, although Solis Palma was officially installed Feb. 26.
   ABC reported that as a condition of Noriega's departure, he will
never go to jail and will be allowed to retain most of his wealth.
   According to ABC, the deal included that Noriega will step down
with full honors; several days or weeks later, he will leave
Panama, going either to Spain or France. In addition, ABC said,
opposition leaders in Panama have agreed not to seek criminal
charges against Noriega there and not to try to get any of his
money held in overseas accounts.
</TEXT>
