<DOCNO> AP880318-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 2112EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Baker-Nicaragua 2ndLd-Writethru a0849 03-18 0905</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baker-Nicaragua, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0849,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Would Consider Honduran Request For Military Help</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts one graf after 19th graf bgng: ``There have ... to
show that Baker's remarks about Noriega came before officials
revealed US envoy in Panama. Picks up 20th graf pvs bgng: On
possible ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan would give ``most careful''
consideration to any request from Honduras for U.S. troops to
assist in repelling Nicaraguan forces, White House Chief of Staff
Howard H. Baker Jr. said Friday.
   Interviewed on the television program, ``John McLaughlin's One
on One,'' Baker said, however, that he does not expect U.S. troops
to be used in any military engagements in the region.
   The presidential aide defended Reagan's decision to send U.S.
troops into the area and denied that the United States had put
pressure on the Honduran government to request them.
   He said the president made the decision ``in the second floor of
the residence portion of the White House a minute after 8:00'' on
Wednesday evening, after receiving a request from Honduran
President Jose Azcona.
   ``I do not believe there was any effort, any arm-twisting, to
try to contrive a situation where he would make this request,''
Baker said. ``I think it was made for the reason stated in this
letter: His country was invaded and that he wanted help.''
   Interviewer John McLaughlin asked Baker what the president would
do if Azcona asked him to have U.S. troops join Honduran troops
``in combat, to repel the invaders.''
   ``No such request has been received. I do not believe such a
request will be received,'' Baker said. ``But were it received, to
answer your hypothetical question, were it to be received, it would
be most carefully considered and most deliberately considered. But
I cannot tell you what decision the president would make under
those circumstances.''
   When asked at what point U.S. troops would enter action, Baker
said, ``I don't anticipate that will occur at all. I think that the
Honduran forces can handle that on their own, and I fully
anticipate that either the Nicaraguans will retire on their own or
Honduras will, as they say, encourage them to do that. But I do not
expect American troops to be involved in any military operation
there.''
   Baker rejected suggestions that the administration had raised
the alarm about the Nicaraguan border crossing in order to
strengthen its hand in seeking renewed assistance from Congress for
rebels fighting Nicaragua's Marxist-led government.
   ``It was not our design,'' he said. ``It did not work that way.
And we did not want it that way.''
   In fact, Baker said, he thinks prospects for an agreement on aid
to the rebels were better on Tuesday, before the crisis arose, than
they are now.
   ``I think we were on the brink of that until this incursion
occurred, and until we received this request from Azcona,'' he
said. ``After that, there's dust in the air and fur flying, and
clearly we are not better off now than we were before.''
   He also said, however, that he believes the prospects will
improve again after ``the dust settles and people think about it
and understand what's happened, and stop imputing bad motives to
this administration and this president.''
   ``But if that was our design, it was the dumbest legislative
strategy ever devised, because it hasn't worked that way,'' he said.
   The program was taped for weekend broadcast, and a transcript
was distributed for release on Friday.
   On other subjects, Baker said:
   _That when he went to Panama as Senate Republican leader during
the debate on the Panama Canal Treaties, Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, who was then the Panamanian intelligence chief, threatened
in a conversation to blow up the canal if the treaties were not
ratified. He said Omar Torrijos, then the Panamanian strongman,
told him, ``Look, Noriega's sort of a hot-head, don't pay any
attention to him.''
   But Baker said the administration, which is putting pressure on
Noriega to step down, has not had direct contact with the
Panamanian leader. He was asked about reports that Noriega wants
direct contacts with the United States but that the United States
will not agree to those talks until he agrees to leave Panama.
   ``There have been some contacts that would appear to be from
Gen. Noriega or on his behalf, but that's all I can tell you ...
They purport to be ... queries by _ on Gen. Noriega's part _ but we
have not (had) direct contact with Gen. Noriega,'' Baker said.
   Baker made his remarks before other administration officials
revealed late Friday that a U.S. envoy has gone to Panama at
Noriega's request to discuss terms of his possible departure.
   _On possible pardons for individuals indicted in the Iran-Contra
affair, ``The president's simply not going to address that
question. The president has the constitutional pardoning authority,
but he's said over and over, this is not the time and it's not the
circumstance in which to consider that.''
   _He does not expect Vice President George Bush, assuming Bush is
the Republican presidential nominee, to ask him to be his running
mate. ``I think he needs to go to a governor, perhaps, someone who
can bring about a balance to the ticket.'' He said possibilities
would include Govs. George Deukmejian of California, Tom Kean of
New Jersey, and former Govs. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee and
Richard Thornburgh of Pennsylvania.
</TEXT>
