<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 2114EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Taxes     03-18 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Taxes,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Law Outlines Taxes for Cooperative Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviets who earn $3,200 or more a month working in
a cooperative operating outside state control will have to pay more
than half the money back in taxes, and even as much as 90 percent,
Izvestia said Friday.
   The government newspaper outlined progressive income taxes for
members of cooperatives that it said will go into effect April 1.
   Taxes will remain low for the cooperatives themselves, but
income taxes for those who earn more than 500 rubles ($800) a month
from working in the cooperatives will climb steeply, according to
an interview Izvestia conducted with Finance Ministry official Y.
Zemskov.
   Zemskov said taxes will be increased on high salaries because
cooperatives in those cases are paying out in salaries what the
government would like them to spend improving and expanding their
services.
   Under Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms, Soviets can get permission
to form cooperatives to produce goods and provide services outside
the state-run economy. The cooperatives must be approved by local
governments, but otherwise operate outside state control.
   The tax rate now is between 2 percent and 3 percent for
cooperatives in their first year and up to 10 percent after their
third year.
   Taxes of cooperative members will start going up sharply after
an income of 500 rubles a month, Zemskov said. The tax on an income
of 1,000 rubles, ($1,600) will be 270.20 rubles and on an income of
2,000 rubles ($3,200) will be 53.5 percent.
   He said the tax eventually reaches 90 percent, but did not say
what the income threshold was for that tax.
   Zemskov said local governments will be allowed to keep the money
levied in income taxes on cooperatives to provide them with an
incentive to help cooperatives develop.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880318-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 2130EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AntarcticRow     03-18 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Antarctic Row,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Adventurers Recount Unprecedented Rowing Journey To Antarctica</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crew members of a high-tech, 28-foot rowboat that
crossed the treacherous strait between South America and Antarctica
said Friday they encountered squalls that tossed three of them into
the turbulent sea.
   ``Why did we do it?'' said Jay Morrison, 34. ``Because nobody
had ever done it before. That's a pretty good reason.''
   Rowing most of the way, Morrison and three colleagues crossed
the stormy Drake Passage between Tierra del Fuego, the southern tip
of South America, and Antactica in a 600-mile voyage that ended
March 7.
   ``You should see what it's like to try to walk on land after
being thrown around at sea for 12 days,'' said Ned Gillette, who
organized the voyage and led an similar expedition last year that
was scuttled by ice.
   ``Until we made it, we weren't really sure it could be done,''
said Gillette, of Stowe, Vt. ``I didn't think we'd expire on the
trip, but I didn't know where we'd end up.''
   The expedition in the $17,000 red boat jokingly dubbed the Sea
Tomato mixed raw adventure with high-technology precision. The
expedition was financed by corporate sponsors.
   While crew members bailed flooded cabins and rowed the boat
through 100-foot swells, a Massachusetts weather station each day
fed the expedition forecasts, and the boat's location was tracked
by satellite.
   After waiting nearly a month for proper weather, the expedition
almost ended in disaster off the Chilean coast Feb. 22, just hours
after leaving under sail.
   A heavy squall erupted and swamped the craft, sending Gillette
overboard. Gillette, an experienced moutaineer, was saved by a line
fastened to the boat, as were two other crew members who were
washed overboard later in the trip.
   Three days out, the crew took down the sails and began rowing in
shifts, sometimes all night. They went about 2.6 mph on average, or
about as fast as a person walks.
   ``Sometimes an albatross would land alongside,'' said Gillette.
``It would paddle along and watch us. We would outdistance it _
sometimes.''
   The team brought provisions for 25 days. ``We didn't know how
long we'd be out,'' said Gillette. ``There was a lot of
uncertainty.''
   The Sea Tomato, stripped of some expensive equipment, now rests
on King George Island in Antarctica as a gift to the Chilean
government.
   ``I kind of hope they leave it there,'' said Gillette. ``It did
its job to get us there. It would be fitting it keep it there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
