<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest 1stLd-Writethru a0752 03-18 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0752,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sumgait Officials Fired; Police Raid Glasnost Office</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with raid on magazine; no pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor and the Communist Party chief of a city
in Azerbaijan where at least 32 people died in ethnic rioting were
fired Thursday, reports from Soviet Armenia said.
   Those dismissed were said to be the mayor and Communist Party
chief of Sumgait, Azerbaijan, where riots broke out Feb. 28 between
Azerbaijanis and ethnic Armenians.
   In another development, the editor of Glasnost magazine reported
a police raid Thursday he said was linked to the publication's
coverage of ethnic violence in Armenia and neighboring Azerbaijan.
   Sergei Grigoryants, a former political prisoner and editor of
Glasnost, said six carloads of police descended on the office in
Kratovo, a town about 15 miles southeast of Moscow.
   He said by telephone that uniformed and plainclothes officers
spent more than two hours checking editors' papers and taking
photographs.
   Grigoryants said they wanted to search the office but did not
have a warrant. The five editors present would not let police into
the back half of the office where editorial work is done, he said.
   ``The house was completely surrounded by police cars,''
Grigoryants said, adding that many police were involved. He said
they did not detain anyone or take anything from the office.
   Grigoryants founded Glasnost, named for Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's policy of more openness, last June and has
unsuccessfully sought official approval for it.
   Gamlet Kocharyan, a member of the governing council of the
Kafar, Armenia, said by telephone the dismissals at Sumgait were
announced in a television broadcast from Yerevan, capital of the
Armenian republic.
   Armenian activists say the victims in Sumgait were Armenians
killed by Azeris, the dominant group in neighboring Azerbaijan.
Most Azeris are Shiite Moslems and Armenians are predominantly
Christian.
   Unrest in the southern republics began with Armenian
demonstrations pressing for Nagorno-Karabakh, an area of Azerbaijan
that has an Armenian majority, to be annexed by Armenia.
   Kocharyan identified the men fired as Muslim Zade, Communist
Party chief in Sumgait, and Mayor Tavakkula Yagub Ogly Mamedov.
   The report said they would be replaced by the premier of the
Nakhichevansky autonomous republic in Azerbaijan and a factory
manager from Sumgait, according to Kocharyan.
   Baku radio reported earlier that Mamedov was fired for ``serious
shortcomings in the work of maintaining appropriate law and order
and discipline in the city, and for the lack of political foresight
he has shown which has resulted in tragic consequences.''
   The television report also said a commission had been formed to
search for witnesses to the rioting in Sumgait, Kocharyan said.
   Grigoryants is Armenian and has reported regularly to Western
correspondents in Moscow about the ethnic unrest in Armenia and
Azerbaijan.
   He traveled to Yerevan to witness a memorial procession March 8
for those killed in Sumgait. He and fellow editor Andrei Shelkov,
who went to Sumgait, held a news conference last Friday for foreign
journalists who have not been permitted to visit the area.
   According to Grigoryants, the police visit to the Glasnost
offices was ``undoubtedly'' part of a campaign of reprisals against
him.
   On Saturday, Shelkov was attacked on a Moscow trolley bus by a
person who could not be identified, Grigoryants said.
   Official Soviet media have criticized Grigoryants. Police made
two raids in August on the editorial office, but did not take
anything or arrest anyone.
   In October, police confiscated about 70 copies they said were
printed illegally on state-owned equipment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
