<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Biaggi-Wedtech     03-18 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness: Meese Interceded with Pentagon for Wedtech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Wedtech Corp. executive testified
Friday that he was told Attorney General Edwin Meese III interceded
with the Pentagon on the defense contractor's behalf over a $24
million Navy contract.
   The allegation came at the racketeering trial of Rep. Mario
Biaggi and six others charged in a series of bribery and influence
peddling schemes involving Wedtech.
   The government's first witness, ex-Wedtech official Mario
Moreno, said he met with a close friend of Meese, San Francisco
lawyer E. Robert Wallach, in December 1983. Meese at the time was
presidential counselor.
   Moreno said Wedtech had been notified it would be awarded the
less lucrative part of a Navy contract to build bridge pontoons,
and he asked Wallach to get Meese ``to change the Navy's mind.''
   Moreno said Wallach told him, ``Mr. Meese said he would talk to
Mr. Weinberger,'' referring to then-Defense Secretary Caspar
Weinberger. Moreno testified that he understood Weinberger would
call then-Navy Secretary John Lehman.
   Moreno said that in January 1984, Wedtech received approval
making it eligible for the entire pontoon contract, which it signed
in April 1984.
   Moreno first described Meese's alleged intervention in an
affidavit disclosed in October at a Senate hearing. At the time,
Meese and Weinberger said through spokesmen they had no
recollection of the action described by Moreno.
   Moreno previously testified at the Wedtech trial that Wallach
told him that Meese had also interceded on Wedtech's behalf with
the Commerce Department over a federal financing package.
   Wedtech, a $100 million-a-year defense contractor before
declaring bankruptcy in 1986, grew from a small New York machine
shop through a series of no-bid defense contracts. Prosecutors
claim Wedtech falsely portrtayed itself as a minority company to
get contracts.
   Wallach, Meese's former personal lawyer, is under indictment on
charges of taking bribes from Wedtech officials for trying to
influence Meese and others.
   In December, a special prosecutor in Washington said there was
insufficient evidence to charge Meese in the Wedtech case.
   Moreno is one of four ex-Wedtech officials who have pleaded
guilty to bribing public officials and to other crimes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
