<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BabyCases     03-18 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baby Cases,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Child Was Stillborn; No Murder Charges To Be Filed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A father told police he stuffed his
newborn baby into a toilet and later threw him into a lake, but
authorities concluded the child had died in the womb and said no
murder charges will be filed.
   However, the case has prompted several tips about pregnant women
whose newborns have vanished, and detectives are opening
investigations into three cases as a result, said Tarrant County
sheriff's Detective Wayne Boggus.
   The so-called Benbrook Lake case was solved by a tip from an
acquaintance of the mother, authorities said. The acquaintance
never saw the baby after the mother's pregnancy ended.
   Sheriff's investigators confronted the 22-year-old mother and
24-year-old husband and they gave detailed statements. The couple's
names were withheld.
   The woman gave birth Feb. 16 in her bathroom. The frightened
husband, apparently unaware the child was stillborn, stuffed the
body into the toilet and took a nap next to his bloodied wife, the
father told police Wednesday.
   ``He said when he woke up, he hoped it was all just a
nightmare,'' said Boggus. The father said he found the baby dead,
and he put the body in a bag with heavy rocks and tossed it into
lake, Boggus said.
   The man's wife, still weak, did not knew what was in the bag,
the man said. It was two weeks before he told her what he did with
the baby, authorities said.
   ``The only explanation we got from him was that he `freaked
out,''' Boggus said. ``He said he almost fainted himself. I assume
he was pretty scared and confused.''
   A fisherman hooked the bag March 7 in a nearby creek. On March
8, the county Medical Examiner's Office ruled that the baby was
choked by his umbilical cord in the womb.
   With the natural-death ruling, murder charges cannot be brought
against the couple, Robert Hester, assistant Tarrant County
prosecutor, said Thursday.
   Hester said authorities may charge the man with abuse of a
corpse, a misdemeanor punishable by a maximum of a year in jail and
a $2,000 fine.
   Because of a plea through the news media for information on the
Benbrook Lake case, detectives are looking into other cases. Police
declined to give details of those cases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
