<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Trade-Frenzel     03-18 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade-Frenzel,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Ride To The Rescue As Trade Debate Bogs Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese officials were sitting in their
embassy studying a major Senate trade document while House members
were forced to wait hours to get their copies, an influential
lawmaker complained Thursday.
   An irate Rep. William Frenzel, R-Minn., told a closed-door
caucus of House trade lawmakers he finally obtained a copy of the
paper by messenger from the Japanese as a courtesy three hours
before it arrived from the Senate.
   Frenzel's remarks to House members of a House-Senate conference
committee drafting a sweeping trade bill were confirmed by his
administrative assistant, Pat Eveland, who also handles trade
legislation for him.
   ``We think it would be nice if the Senate would decide to give
us the trade offer first before the private sector and the press,''
she said when asked what Frenzel told the caucus. His aides said
the congressman himself was not available to discuss the matter.
   The document was a compromise offer from Senate members of the
conference committee. It was designed to resolve conflicts between
House and Senate versions of the 1,000-page trade bill, primarily
sections dealing with unfair practices by the Japanese and other
trading partners.
   Among other things, it contained the Senate's proposal to erase
the from the bill the controversial trade plan sponsored by
Democratic presidential hopeful Richard A. Gephardt, D-Mo. His
proposal, calling for 10 percent yearly rollbacks in Japanese trade
surpluses, is contained only in the House bill.
   In place of Gephardt's plan, the Senate is proposing its own,
so-called Super 301 proposal, which would require the U.S. trade
representative to draw up a list of Japanese barriers to American
products and then either negotiate an end to them or retaliate.
   Eveland said that she was on the telephone with a Japanese
Embassy official early Wednesday morning, discussing the Senate's
offer, when to her surprise ``it became evident that they had a
copy of it.''
   She said that she asked the Japanese for a copy and that they
immediately duplicated theirs and sent it by messenger to Frenzel's
office on Capitol Hill. She said a version was not available from
the Senate Finance Committee until 12:30 p.m. Wednesday.
   Just how the Japanese managed to obtain the offer remained
unclear, Eveland said. Several copies were distributed to reporters
who worked late in the Senate Press Gallery on Tuesday night.
   Meanwhile, Rep. Tom Downey, D-N.Y., said he also was among those
who were forced to wait and finally had to go out of channels to
get his copy.
</TEXT>
