<HEAD>Contras Monitor Border Clash While Readying For Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spokeswoman for Nicaragua's Contra rebels said
Thursday that peace talks scheduled to begin Monday with the
Sandinista government are still on despite a reported clash at the
Nicaraguan-Honduran border.
   The government of Daniel Ortega and Contra representatives are
scheduled to begin three days of talks in the southern Nicaraguan
town of Sapoa near the border with Costa Rica.
   Intense fighting continued Thursday between the rebels and 2,000
Sandinista soldiers in Honduras, said Marta Sacasa, spokeswoman for
the Nicaraguan Resistance, a Contra umbrella group.
   Unless there is an official decision otherwise, the peace talks
will go on despite the Contras' weakened military position, she
said. Some resistance leaders already have left the U.S. for the
scheduled talks.
   ``The intention of the Sandinistas was to weaken our position at
the negotiating table,'' Ms. Sacasa said. ``It's also timed to
coincide with the end of United States aid.''
   Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government said its troops were
not in Honduras.
   But the Reagan administration said Sandinista forces were in
Honduras and were threatening to overrun Contra bases, and it
dispatched 3,200 U.S. combat troops.
   ``The United States troops did not go to Honduras to involve
themselves with the fighting in any way, so we have no comment,''
Ms. Sacasa said.
   Preliminary reports indicated 10 Contra rebels were killed and
56 wounded in the Sandinista offensive, she said. ``They knew we
would not be resupplied, ... but our determination and morale are
unwavering and high,'' Ms. Sacasa said.
