<HEAD>PRECEDE Madrid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet Actor Requests Political Asylum in France</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with France saying it granted
Soviet temporary residence, details.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet actor has asked for political asylum in
France and will be allowed to stay in the country while his request
is considered, a Foreign Ministry spokeswoman said Thursday.
   In Madrid, the independent daily El Pais cited police sources as
saying Alexi Maslov, a member of the Taganka theater company, flew
to Paris Wednesday shortly after being granted asylum in France.
   But the French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said the actor ``is expected within the
next few days.'' She said his asylum request was under review.
   She said Maslov would be treated as a political refugee and
would be granted a temporary resident alien permit while his case
is reviewed by French courts.
   El Pais said Maslov had been in the care of Madrid police since
shortly after he arrived in Madrid on March 14 with the rest of the
Taganka troupe to take part in the International Theater Festival
of Madrid.
   He had been scheduled to perform Thursday in the play ``The
Mother'' by Maxim Gorki.
   Taganka director Nikolai L. Dupak and a Soviet Embassy official
had reported Maslov missing Tuesday after he failed to return to
the hotel where the troupe was staying, the newspaper said.
   The Soviet Embassy had no comment on the report.
