<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WritersStrike     03-18 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Strike-Bound Show To Go Forward; Picketing Resumes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite a scriptwriters' strike, producers of
the new ``The Smothers Brothers Comedy Hour'' decided Thursday to
make six of the TV shows even though they have only three
union-written scripts.
   CBS announced the hour-long show starring Tom and Dick Smothers
would debut March 30 at 8 p.m. Production plans had been postponed
by the strike by 9,000 TV and film scriptwriters belonging to the
Writers Guild of America.
   The writers went on strike March 7 against the Alliance of
Motion Picture and Television Producers over creative control and
residuals from syndication and distribution abroad.
   No new talks are scheduled. A session was held with a federal
mediator over the weekend.
   Producers say their final offer is a $50 million increase; the
union says the package would represent a $37 million loss to its
members.
   A CBS spokesman who talked on condition he not be identified
said six ``Smothers Brothers'' shows were planned, and three
scripts were in hand.
   He would not say what would happen if the strike were still in
progress when it came time for the fourth show.
   Script contain not only dialogue and monologue but lighting and
stage directions. Under the guild contract, not even cue cards can
be drawn up without violating the strike.
   The ``Smothers Brothers Comedy Hour'' is a follow-up to a
well-received reunion of the old Smothers Brothers cast earlier
this season.
   The Smothers Brothers first comedy-variety show for CBS was
canceled in 1969 after running into a long stream of censorship
problems.
   Union spokeswoman Cheryl Rhoden said the guild had no immediate
comment on the decision to go ahead with the program.
   One of the show's producers, Ken Kragen, did not immediately
return a message seeking comment.
   WGA members resumed picketing Thursday, with about 800
sign-carrying members showing up at the CBS-MTM complex in the
Studio City section of Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
