body.
   Washington has said the 3,000 U.S. troops it was sending to
Honduras were to engage in joint military exercises with the
Hondurans.
   Honduras complained that Sandinista troops from neighboring
Nicaragua entered Honduras in pursuit of Contra rebels. President
Reagan has called it an invasion by Nicaraguan forces.
   Nicaragua and Panama used a council debate on British military
maneuvers in the Falkland Islands Thursday to condemn U.S. military
activities in Central America.
   ``Nicaragua, having suffered pillage and spoilage by English
buccaneers who pillaged our coast, is victim today of the threats
and aggression of another American state,'' Nicaragua's acting
ambassador, Julio Icaza Gallardo, told the council.
   ``Nicaragua denounces once again this gunboat policy which
reflects disdain for our dignity and rights.''
   Britain and Argentina fought a 74-day war over the Falklands in
1982, lost by Argentina.
   Panama's ambassador, George Eduardo Ritter, drew a parallel
between the British claim on the Falklands and U.S. control over
the Panama Canal Zone.
