<2ND_LINE>AM-Shamir Visit,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Prime Minister Calls On American Jews To Stand With Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir warned
American Jews on Thursday not to compare Palestinian protests in
the occupied territories to a civil rights struggle.
   ``These are another expression of the Arab refusal to accept
Israel, to coexist with us, and to recognize that Israel is a
permanent feature in the region,'' Shamir said.
   The protesters ``cry, `Palestine is Arab,' and openly declare
that all of Palestine is theirs,'' Shamir told about 1,500 members
of the Jewish community at a dedication of a cornerstone for a
museum commemorating the Holocaust.
   ``These are not passive civil rights marches,'' he said.
   Shamir, fresh from his meeting with President Reagan, Secretary
of State George P. Shultz and congressional leaders, reiterated his
opposition to an American plan for peace in the Middle East that
calls for an international conference.
   Shamir, his address punctuated by enthusiastic applause, said
the proposal would play into the hands of the Soviets and Arabs,
who he said are trying to bypass direct talks with Israel.
   ``We are for direct negotiations, without preconditions, for
open talks at which each side will present its views and claims on
an equal footing, without outside intervention,'' Shamir said.
   He called on his audience to close ranks behind Israel as it
tries to quell rioting by Palestinians on the West Bank and the
Gaza Strip, which Israel has occupied since the 1967 Mideast war.
   ``When unity breaks down, then our enemies exploit every
critical statement to their own end,'' he said, referring
apparently to criticism by some American Jews of the Israeli Army's
use of beatings and live ammunition to quell the riots.
   At least 100 Palestinians have been killed in more than three
months of violence, and hundreds wounded.
   Shamir flew Thursday from Washington to Los Angeles, where he
helped dedicate the cornerstone of the Simon Wiesenthal Center's
Beit Hashoah-Museum of Tolerance. The museum focuses on the
extermination of Jews by Nazi Germany.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
