<HEAD>Carlucci, Yazov Discuss Nicaragua, End Talks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One graf SUBS for 3rd graf pvs, ``I would ... UPDATING with
Carlucci back in Washington. Picks up 4th graf pvs, U.S. troops ..
.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Honduras, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secrtary Frank C. Carlucci said
Thursday he protested to his Soviet counterpart Nicaragua's alleged
intrusion into Honduras.
   Carlucci said he and Dmitri Yazov briefly discussed the
Nicaragua-Honduras dispute and that Yazov ``made some attempt to
defend the Sandinista action.''
   ``I would not characterize it as a vigorous defense,'' he added
at a news conference in Bern. Carlucci arrived back in Washington
later Thursday.
   U.S. troops arrived in Honduras on Thursday after the United
States and Honduras accused Nicaraguan troops of entering the
country in pursuit of U.S.-backed Contra rebels. Carlucci said he
had endorsed the decision.
   Carlucci described the three days of closed-door talks with
Yazov as ``cordial and businesslike,'' and said Yazov invited him
to Moscow to continue their discussions at a later date.
   At a separate news conference, Yazov termed the discussions, the
first ever business session between U.S. and Soviet defense chiefs,
as ``quite candid and very useful.''
   Carlucci said that ``of course, there were a number of areas of
disagreement.'' Yazov said the Kremlin ``does not harbor any
illusions'' about a breakthrough in superpower relations.
   The two sides announced agreement that the chairman of the U.S.
joint chiefs of staff, Adm. William Crowe, and the Soviet Chief of
Staff, Marshal Sergei Akhromeyev, will meet soon to work out
guidelines to prevent friction between U.S. and Soviet forces.
   Carlucci said he had not obtained the apology he sought for the
fatal shooting by a Soviet soldier of U.S. Army Maj. Arthur
Nicholson in East Germany three years ago.
   Yazov said the incident occurred before he became defense
minister last May and was being handled by the foreign ministry,
according to Carlucci.
   The two sides also discussed the U.S. proposed space-based
defense plan and regional conflicts, including Angola, Cambodia and
Korea, Carlucci said.
   Yazov said in a statement that both sides agreed to hold further
talks on each other's military doctrine and to consider an exchange
of data.
   He called for launching all-European negotiations on
conventional arms this year.
</TEXT>
