<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv21   03-18 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 21 ,0621</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Monday March 21</NOTE>
<HEAD>New York Doesn't Mirror the Nation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although there are few signs of a looming
recession, the probability of one remains a subject of intense
discussion in certain areas of the country, such as New York.
   Why is this so? asks Albert Sindlinger, who was testing public
opinion as long ago as the Great Depression _ and as recently as
this very day _ and who declares again that recession isn't an
immediate threat.
   Sindlinger, whose company conducts scores of telephone
interviews each day, says he finds a contradiction between what he
reads and hears in the media and what ordinary folks around the
country are telling him and his staff.
   The people he and his staff talk to, he states, are confident
about their own economic future. He says their household money
supply, a measure of existing conditions, is healthy. And so are
their expectations, he says.
   He points out that these opinions can't be taken lightly because
the consumer factor _ the ability and willingness to buy _ is the
vital ingredient of our total economy, bigger even that business
and government.
   But, he continues, many of the economic reports he reads include
phrases such as ``when the recession begins'' rather than ``if
there is a recession.''
   He was especially indignant about the profiferation of these
references following the Oct. 19 stock market crash which, he
contends, bore no resemblance to 1929, which he vividly recalls.
So, he sought the reason why.
   Sindlinger now says the fault lies with the financial press,
which he says is headquartered in New York City, close to the
financial community.
   New York, he says, is a special situation that doesn't reflect
the country's mood.
   Ever since Black Monday, he says, ``we have been watching a
strong, steady decline in consumer confidence in one _ and only one
_ area: eastern New York state.''
   He declares that the economy in much of the country has improved
in the past year, and is continuing to do so. He couldn't have said
that in late 1986, when his readings showed 31 states in recession.
Now, he says, there are but four in recession: Oklahoma, Louisiana,
West Virginia and Mississippi.
   In short, by his estimates the nation's economy has been growing
stronger, but the economy of eastern New York has not. He measures
that area at barely above recession level.
   ``The weakness there is rooted around the New York City
financial community,'' he states. ``Large numbers have been laid
off, and many others say they are extremely concerned about their
lack of job security.
   ``These layoffs have spilled into the BMW automobile
dealerships, fur salons and fern restaurants. McDonald's also is
feeling the pinch on Manhattan Island, since lower-paid clerks are
being laid off, too.''
   He concludes:
   ``So, the financial press, stuck on the same island with the
financial houses and their current and former employees can't help
but get the idea that something's wrong with the economy.
   ``They see these people on the streets, and interview them for
their stories. Being observant people, they immediately sense that
people in the Big Apple are in trouble.''
   He asks: ``Do these causal observations affect their
interviewing and reporting?'' Seldom without an answer or an
explanation, the crusty Sindlinger responds:
   ``Are they human? Of course they're affected.''
   While conditions could improve around the country, he says, they
are a lot better than some New Yorkers believe they are.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Monday March 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
