<DOCNO> AP880318-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 0852EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:ChineseDirector Adv23   03-18 0914</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Chinese Director, Adv 23,0938</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, March 23 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Director Works to Stretch Limits of the Permissible</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>XIAN, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blunt criticisms of art censors have come to
be expected from China's most famous movie director, Wu Tianming,
even more than the evocative and provocative films produced by his
studio.
   It takes no prompting to set him off.
   ``Those people (censors) were used to making hypocritical
propaganda,'' Wu grumbled in a recent interview. ``People who have
feudal and ultra-left ideas and bureaucrats ... get in the way of
our work.''
   Even the censors, however, have been unable to stop the cascade
of domestic and international honors awarded in the past four years
to Wu's movies and those of young directors who work under him at
the Xian Film Studio in China's ancient capital.
   Since Wu became its director in 1983, the debt-ridden studio in
arid northwestern China has become a prolific producer of
hauntingly beautiful, technically innovative movies that have
raised China's standing in the international film community. Many
in one way or another also have been seen as affronts to socialism.
   For example, Wu's own ``Old Well,'' about a poor village's
efforts to dig a well, won top honors last year at the Tokyo
International Film Festival and a special prize at the Hawaii
International Film festival and received critical acclaim in New
York.
   But its release to prudish Chinese audiences was delayed for
months because of the movie's depiction of a love triangle,
including several kissing scenes of unusual passion.
   ``The Black Cannon,'' directed by Huang Jianxing, one of Wu's
stable of young directors, aroused heated debate because it
attacked mindless bureaucracy. It eventually was named best movie
of 1985 by China's Ministry of Broadcast, Film and Television.
   Another Xian studio release, ``The Horse Thief,'' directed by
Tian Zhuangzhuang, never was shown to general Chinese audiences
because of its depiction of poverty among Tibetan horsemen.
   From his brick office compound with peeling paint and leaking
pipes, the 48-year-old Wu said he wants to expand the limits of
what is acceptable in Chinese filmmaking, largely restricted since
1949 to socialist morality tales.
   Wu said the studio does not seek to create controversy, but it
often results because he and his fellow directors are trying to
depict the often harsh realities of life in China.
   This frightens conservative bureaucrats accustomed to propaganda
movies, he said: ``They lived illusions. They cannot accept any
movie that reflects the dark side of life.''
   It's a side of life Wu knows well. He was born in the mountains
of Shaanxi province, north of Xian, where perpetual drought keeps
many peasants in poverty. During the 1966-76 far-leftist Cultural
Revolution, he was denounced as a rightist and paraded through
Xian's streets wearing a signboard proclaiming his political sins.
   Afterward, he said, he went home and ``shut my door and
studied'' for the rest of the tumultuous decade, during which China
made almost no movies.
   Wu is willing to take risks not only for his own movies but
those of other directors at the Xian studio _ one reason it has
attracted talented young directors and cinematographers.
   On his movie, ``The Black Cannon,'' Huang said: ``The moment we
saw the film for the first time we knew it would be controversial.
   ``But we had a common idea,'' he said pointing to Wu, ``that
this film should reflect life. We felt some pressure when the film
was not (immediately) approved. But Mr. Wu said at one meeting if
problems occurred he would be held responsible.''
   Another attraction is Wu's readiness to give young directors
free rein.
   Asked if he gives advice to the less experienced, 34-year-old
Huang, Wu laughed and said, ``He does fine on his own. If I were to
help him ... I might stifle him.
   ``There would be great prosperity in China's literature and arts
if all artistic leaders followed my example: to let artists do what
they like.''
   Wu is harsh in his criticism of standard Chinese movie fare.
``Sixty percent of Chinese movies are seriously lacking,'' he said.
But he is no kinder to foreign movies.
   He disliked Steven Spielberg's ``Empire of the Sun,'' partly
filmed in Shanghai, about the Japanese invasion of China in World
War II. Wu also said he does not seek to copy Western movies.
   He says his studio's movies are the best being made in China
now, and was confident his own ``Old Well'' will sweep the Chinese
critics' and government awards for best movie of 1987.
   Several upcoming Xian movies appear ripe to arouse debate: one
is about army chief Peng Dehuai, purged in 1958 for daring to
criticize Mao Tse-tung; another concerns three youths whose lives
are failures despite their efforts to get ahead.
   ``Maybe some people will think it's too gray,'' Huang said of
the latter movie, which he is directing, to be called ``Floating
Out of the Sea.''
   His own output is relatively slim. In addition to co-directing
two movies, he has directed just three: ``Old Well,'' ``Life''
(1984) and ``River Without a Buoy'' (1983). All three have received
prizes at home or abroad.
   The demands of running a studio that employs 1,450 and is
perpetually in debt will keep him from starting his next movie
before next year, he said.
   Will it be controversial?
   ``Yes,'' Wu said emphatically, using one of his few English
words. ``Definitely.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed, March 23</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880318-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 0853EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Indonesia-Discord Adv21   03-18 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Indonesia-Discord, Adv 21,0762</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, March 21 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Indonesia's Suharto Starts New Term Amid Discord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The People's Consultative Assembly has
closed shop for another five years after an 11-day session marked
by unprecedented discord.
   A public outburst by an army general, a dispute over the vice
presidency and previously unheard of votes on policy matters upset
the script at what is usually a pre-arranged ceremonial occasion.
   The assembly is supposed to ``elect'' the president and vice
president and approve state policy guidelines. It consists of the
500 members of Parliament chosen through a general election last
April and another 500 people appointed by President Suharto.
   The constitution describes the assembly as the nation's supreme
lawmaking body. In fact, Suharto rules the world's fifth most
populous country with the support of the armed forces and
participatory democracy is limited.
   Five factions in the assembly acclaimed Suharto as president for
a fifth five-year term. The factions include three political
parties, the military and appointees from different regions.
   State Secretary Sudharmono was sworn in unopposed as vice
president only after Jailani Naro of the Moslem-based United
Development Party withdrew at the last minute.
   ``I didn't withdraw. I was pulled out by my party,'' Naro told a
news conference.
   Earlier in the session, Naro's party caused the assembly to
depart from tradition by voting for the first time ever to break a
deadlock.
   Political custom calls for ``musjawarah,'' or negotiating for as
long as it takes to reach consensus. Some authorities dislike
voting as a practice they associate with Western-style democracy.
   The Moslem faction was outvoted 280-28 in committee on its
request to add a clause to election rules stating that ``general
elections should be held in a fair and honest manner.'' Opponents
maintained this was already embodied in the regulations.
   The Moslem group lost by equally lopsided margins on proposals
to reject Javanese mysticism as part of religion and subsidize
Islamic boarding schools.
   The vice presidency is a largely ceremonial position. But with
the 66-year-old Suharto starting what is assumed will be his last
term, his running mate would be well-placed to stake a claim as
heir to the presidency.
   Stepping out as vice president is Umar Wirahadikusumah, 64, a
retired general and Suharto's former comrade-in-arms. Umar kept a
low profile during his one term and was never regarded as having
presidential ambitions.
   Constitutional procedures for succession exist, but do not take
into account the widespread mystical belief that the national
leader must be blessed with a divine ``mandate'' before one has a
right to rule.
   About 90 percent of Indonesia's 170 million people are
considered at least nominally Moslem. But ``dukuns,'' or
soothsayers, have a wide following and Suharto rules with the help
of Javanese spiritual advisers, informed sources say.
   Suharto and the late President Sukarno are the only presidents
Indonesia has had since independence from the Dutch after World War
II. Economic chaos, an attempted coup and bloodshed in the last
months of Sukarno's rule were supposed to be signs that he had lost
the divine mandate. Sukarno died in 1970.
   Sudharmono, who is 61, the is leader of Golkar, the government
political party. As minister in charge of the state secretariat
since 1966, he has been boss of the country's 2.6 million civil
servants.
   Once known as ``Suharto's doorman'' because he wielded power for
years by controlling access to the president, Sudharmono is a
retired army general. His background is in military law not field
command, however, and not all in the officer corps welcomed his
nomination by Golkar.
   Military sources who insisted on anonymity said some generals
supported instead the newly appointed armed forces commander, Gen.
Try Sutrisno, 52, a popular figure and a former Suharto aide.
   One military figure, Gen. Ibrahim Saleh, startled the assembly
session when he took the microphone and said: ``We Indonesian
soldiers who believe in God and defend honesty and justice have
heard rumors that the nomination of the vice president is not being
fairly and correctly carried out.''
   ``There are certain things that we feel are against our
conscience,'' he added but then was escorted out by other generals
of the military faction before he could finish his statement.
   Former armed forces commander Gen. L.B. Murdani told reporters
later that Saleh did not reflect the views of the armed forces.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, March 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
