<2ND_LINE>BC-AZT-Year Later, Adv 20-1st Add,0328</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 20 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: for AIDS.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Instead, they expect it will be, at most, part of a growing
armamentarium against AIDS. The FDA said there are now more than
100 drugs being tested against AIDS or against the opportunistic
diseases that attack bodies weakened by AIDS.
   Broder at NCI is conducting tests that team AZT with other
drugs, principally one called ddC, for dideoxycytidine. He is
conducting tests in which the drugs are alternated.
   ``I believe we eventually be using a combination of several
drugs,'' said Dr. Glen Mathisen, chief of infectious diseases at
Olive View Medical Center in Los Angeles.
   Mathisen and others note that drug combinations have been used
successfully against major killers such as leukemia and
tuberculosis. Most cancer chemotherapy includes a combination
skillfully administered in cycles.
   AZT's full range of uses are still being explored because the
drug now is limited only to patients at a late stage of AIDS or of
AIDS-related complex, or ARC.
   Barry said studies are under way using AZT to protect medical
workers who have been exposed to the blood or other body fluids of
AIDS patients during treatment. There have been more than 1,000
such reported incidents and its hoped that AZT given within hours
of the exposure will prevent development of AIDS.
   Other studies are exploring the use of AZT for infants born with
the disease, or for people who test positive for the HIV virus, but
who do not have the AIDS sympthoms.
   But no matter what else is learned about AZT, the important
thing is that the drug has bought time, said Broder.
   ``It's not the magic bullet,'' he said. ``But it's keeping
people alive. We can now worry about things like longterm toxicity
of the drug. Before AZT, they didn't live long enough for that to
be a concern.''
</TEXT>
