<1ST_LINE>s w AM-DeafPresident Adv20   03-18 1003</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaf President, Adv 20,1033</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 20 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Gallaudet's New President: `We Can Do Anything _ Except Hear'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Before I. King Jordan Jr. lost his hearing, he
knew nothing about Gallaudet University. Like many District of
Columbia residents, he drove by it frequently without so much as a
curious thought.
   Now, Jordan has taken over the 124-year-old liberal arts
university for the hearing impaired. As its first deaf president,
he has become an important symbol to the non-hearing, even those
who have nothing to do with Gallaudet.
   ``It's overwhelming,'' Jordan said. ``I came here after I
accepted the appointment; the students were crying, hugging me. The
emotion is still very high. It's a wonderful feeling.''
   ``When I go off campus, I ride in the Gallaudet University
station wagon and people blow their horns and wave at me. I can see
people recognize me.
   During the last week, the campus has been empty while its 2,200
students, who pushed Jordan into power, took spring break.
   On Monday, they'll return, and Jordan will hold a celebration
assembly to reinforce what has become his motto: ``Deaf people can
do anything except hear.''
   Jordan rose to the presidency March 13 on a wave of student
protest that followed the decision by Gallaudet's trustees to
appoint a hearing woman, Elisabeth Zinser, as president.
   The outcry led to Zinser's resignation and the hiring of Jordan,
who had been among two deaf people also considered for the job.
   ``What you saw was something really unique,'' Jordan said of the
seven days of protest.
   ``It was not dissatisfaction with the university administration
at all. What you saw was the deaf community, the entire national
and international deaf community finally reach a point where they
knew it was time to speak out about their frustrations at not being
in the top leadership positions in the field.
   ``The conditions were just perfect. The leadership in the
student body was tremendous.
   ``I can't tell you how proud I am of the students, how well
organized they were. How they guaranteed that there would be no
violence, no damage and they carried that out. There was never
anyone hurt or any damage done.''
   Virtually all the students were in on the demonstrations. They
marched, they rallied, they blocked entrances to the campus and
they convinced older deaf people that the time was now to take
charge.
   Jordan originally threw his support behind Zinser, saying he had
hoped to persuade the students to compromise for the good of the
university.
   ``Overnight, literally overnight, it became clear to me that it
was getting bigger and bigger by the minute and that I had misread
it, that I had made a mistake,'' he said.
   ``I don't think anyone realized the support there was on the
outside. I've never seen a movement that was universal support
before.
   ``When the group marched from here to the Capitol, people came
out of their houses and applauded. People who were tied up in
traffic, instead of blowing their horns impatiently and wanting the
march to be over, blew their horns in support, got out of their
cars and waved.
   ``People lining the way between here and the Capitol were
signing `I love you.' It was probably a once-in-a-lifetime
movement.''
   Jordan's deafness has not impaired his speech, but he uses a
sign language interpreter to understand hearing people. Though he
can read lips, he says a lengthy conversation is exhausting without
the help of signing.
   He lost his hearing in 1965 when he was 21 and stationed in
Washington with the Navy. A motorcycle accident caused multiple
skull fractures, severed his auditory nerve and put him in the
hospital for a year.
   When he recovered, someone suggested he enroll at Gallaudet.
Until then, he knew nothing about the school.
   ``Before I became deaf, I drove by here regularly, a few times a
week, and I had no idea what it was,'' he said.
   Though his family was very supportive, deafness had never been a
part of their lives. Growing up in Glen Riddle, Pa., Jordan never
even knew a deaf person.
   His father was a shipping clerk, his mother an office clerk, and
his life with two older sisters and one younger brother had been
typical small town America.
   ``When I first came to Gallaudet I was going through a period of
adjustment to deafness. One of the things that was easy for me to
do was to lose myself in my studies. I found that I was very good
at it. While I couldn't hear, I could read and I'd write, and
became a very strong student. I made a conscious decision to become
as good a student as I could.''
   After getting his bachelor's degree in psychology, Jordan went
on to receive a masters' degree and PhD from the University of
Tennessee. There were no interpreters to translate lectures, so
Jordan read the professors' lips and got help from his hearing
classmates.
   Along the way he married ``a hearing, but very supportive
woman'' and now has a 17-year-old son and 15-year-old daughter.
   He returned to Gallaudet in 1973 as a professor of psychology
and became dean of the College of Arts and Sciences in 1986.
   As it's president, he said he will encourage deaf people to seek
teaching positions at Gallaudet, but he will not put any quotas on
the number of deaf people who should hold either staff or
administrative positions.
   About 30 percent of the professors are deaf. Fewer
administrators are.
   Academica is becoming a better career program for deaf people,
Jordan said. In the past the only opportunity for deaf people would
have been Gallaudet.
   He said he knows of deaf people in other schools using
interpreters to teach hearing students.
   ``I really believe that the events of last week show that even
when someone needs an interpeter, still there can be clear,
meaningful communication,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 20</NOTE>
</DOC>
