<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   03-18 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0557</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. merchandise trade deficit widened to
$12.44 billion in January, but economists say the 1.9 percent
increase reported by the government was too small to cause alarm.
   Exports fell by 10 percent to $22.33 billion and imports by 6
percent to $34.77 billion, the Commerce Department said Thursday.
   Analysts said the export drop was expected and happens every
January. But the decline in imports was greeted as good news and a
further indication that the trade balance is slowly improving.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. factories, mines and utilities operated
at 82.4 percent of capacity in February, the third consecutive
month the operating rate has been at that level, the Federal
Reserve reports.
   Even though the February rate was the same as December and
January, those two months were revised up slightly in the newest
report published Thursday, a change that private economists said
was encouraging.
   Before the revision, the operating rate in December and January
was reported as 82.2 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government moved to calm
depositors' fears and protect the nation's banking system by
advancing $1 billion to banks owned by an ailing Texas bank holding
company.
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. said Thursday it was lending
the money for six months to subsidiaries of First RepublicBank
Corp. as an interim step toward restoring the Dallas-based
company's health.
   The $1 billion lifeline thrown to First RepublicBank worked
quickly to calm fears of depositors, who in recent days of drained
funds from the institution, analysts and bank officials said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firestone Tire & Rubber Co. has agreed to be
acquired by Japan's Bridgestone Corp. in an $80 a share all-cash
buyout totaling nearly $2.6 billion.
   Firestone also said late Thursday that its board recommended
shareholders reject the rival, unsolicited $58 a share buyout offer
from Italian tiremaker Pirelli SpA that had spurred the Bridgestone
proposal.
   In connection with the merger agreement, Firestone stated it had
granted Bridgestone the option effective through the end of this
year to buy an 18 percent stake in the company.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Standard Inc. has accepted a nearly
$2.5 billion cash tender offer from an investment banking firm
specializing in employee-led leveraged buyouts, spurning Black &
Decker Corp.'s hostile advances.
   Industry analysts said Thursday that the $78-a-share tender
offer from Kelso & Co. represented a market premium and that the
bidding war was unlikely to continue.
   The offer topped a cash bid of $73 a share, or $2.1 billion,
from Black & Decker, a tool and appliance maker that had tried to
gain control of American Standard for nearly two months.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Individuals and businesses voluntarily paid
only 83.2 percent of the federal income taxes they owed last year,
leaving the government with a tax gap of $84.9 billion, the
Internal Revenue Service said.
   More than half the shortage reported Thursday was attributed to
individuals who file tax returns but fail to report income from
moonlighting, a small business or other legal non-wage sources.
   IRS Commissioner Lawrence B. Gibbs said closing the gap may
require a basic change of attitude among taxpayers.
</TEXT>
