the industry if rates continue to rise and programming is withheld
from competitors.
   ``Some of us feel we were had'' by the congressional decision
that freed most cable operators of municipal rate control in
January 1987 and let them set their own prices, Metzenbaum said
Thursday.
   Metzenbaum said Congress is concerned that operators of cable
TV, an $11 billion-a-year industry serving 51 percent of U.S.
households, enjoy a monopoly that can freeze out competing TV
distribution systems and raise prices.
