<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     03-18 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Spurred by Better-Than-Expected Trade Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A better-than-expected January trade deficit helped drive the
Dow Jones average of 30 industrials to a post-crash high, while a
report showing sustained factory usage underscored signs of
economic strength.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 21.72 points in a
late buying spree Thursday to close at 2,086.04, the market
barometer's best showing since October's stock market crash.
Analysts credited the better-than-expected trade deficit and
takeover-related buying for the strong performance.
   Separately, the Federal Reserve reported the nation's factories,
mines and utilities operated at 82.4 percent of capacity in
February, sustaining that rate for the third consecutive month.
   The Commerce Department reported a slight widening of the U.S.
merchandise trade deficit to $12.44 billion, but economists said
the 1.9 percent increase was too small to cause alarm.
   Exports fell in a seasonally-expected trend, this time by 10
percent to $22.33 billion.
   But economists were more enthusiastic over a 6 percent dip in
imports, to $34.77 billion, which they say is a firmer indication
the trade balance slowly is improving.
   January's deficit was up from $12.20 billion in December, but
down from the gaps of $13.21 billion in November and $17.63 billion
in October.
   If the January level continued for 12 consecutive months, it
would yield an annual trade deficit of about $149 billion. In 1987,
the merchandise trade deficit was $171.22 billion.
   The January report represented a slight setback after two
consecutive monthly improvements, but there were some bright spots.
   The deficit with Japan _ still the largest single-country
imbalance _ fell by 17.6 percent in January to $3.95 billion, its
lowest level since December 1986.
   The United States showed its first surplus in nearly three years
with Britain, with exports topping imports by $75 million. For all
Western Europe, the deficit declined 51 percent, to $1.33 billion.
   The trade news helped support the dollar and pushed interest
rates lower in the credit markets, where the yield on the
Treasury's bellwether 30-year issue fell to 8.53 percent from
Wednesday's 8.60 percent.
   The Federal Reserve's report showing sustained high factory use
helped underscore economists' contentions that the industrial
sector remained strong.
   Before the year began, some experts had expressed fears that the
economy could weaken significantly due to widespread cutbacks in
production as businesses tried to work off a huge supply of unsold
goods built up in late 1987.
   While high inventories have led to cuts in auto production, many
other industries, such as textiles, chemicals, and paper, have
continued to have high operating rates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
