<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FederatedHearing     03-18 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federated Hearing,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FTC Chairman Refuses to Testify Before House Panel</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Federated Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Federal Trade Commission has
been asked to justify his refusal to give Congress documents on the
agency's review of Campeau Corp.'s proposed takeover of Federated
Department Stores Inc.
   The request was made Thursday by Rep. Thomas Luken, D-Ohio,
after FTC Chairman Daniel Oliver and FTC Commissioner Terry Calvani
refused to appear before the House Energy and Commerce
transportation subcommittee.
   ``I'm a little outraged at this conduct,'' Luken said following
the hearing. ``They're setting up roadblocks.''
   Luken, chairman of the subcommittee, said if the officials
continue to refuse to comply, ``I will obviously be thinking about
proceeding with subpoenas'' and possibly contempt citations.
   Campeau and R.H. Macy & Co. Inc. are locked in a takeover battle
for Cincinnati-based Federated. The congressman has accused the FTC
of failing to thoroughly investigate the hostile takeover bid by
Campeau, which preceded the friendly takeover agreement between
Federated by Macy's.
   Robert Paul, the FTC general counsel, said the commissioners
decided not to give the documents to the subcommittee because
several weeks ago the panel released to the press an FTC staff memo
on the Campeau bid the agency considered confidential.
   ``There's tremendous concern on their part that this was very,
very bad precedent,'' said Paul. ``Chairman Oliver and Commissioner
Calvani are not going to be party to producing documents
further...until there is assurance by the subcommittee that this
type of thing will not happen again.''
   Paul said that if there was an FTC investigation of the Macy's
bid and the commissioners rendered a decision, they might be
subject to allegations by private parties that the agency acted
because of congressional pressure.
   ``The more the Congress acts on this, puts pressure on us, the
greater the possibility of arguing that we have been influenced by
Congress, that we've been tainted,'' said Paul.
   Luken said 80 percent to 90 percent of the information marked
confidential in the FTC memo released by the subcommittee was
contained in public filings and that the rest is just
``chit-chat.'' He said Federated and Campeau were told the memo was
being given to the subcommittee and neither objected.
   Luken asked that Oliver and Calvani submit a legal memo giving
their reason for not providing the documents and for not appearing
before the panel.
   FTC Commissioners Mary Azcuenaga and Andrew Strenio, who
appeared before the subcommittee Thursday, said they had voted to
turn over the requested documents but had failed to obtain the
necessary majority vote to do so.
   Federated operates about 650 stores in 36 states and had sales
exceeding $11 billion in 1987.
   Campeau is a retailing and real estate development company based
in Toronto.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
