<DOCNO> AP880318-0291 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 0703EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CheapCandy     03-18 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cheap Candy,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cheaper Cocoa Prices May Sweeten The Pot For Chocolate-Lovers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Life has gotten sweeter for chocolate
lovers, thanks to a drop in cocoa prices that has translated into
bigger candy bars and could mean future price-cutting promotions.
   The price of raw cocoa _ which typically constitutes up to 20
percent of a typical chocolate bar _ has fallen to five-year lows.
   While that hasn't meant direct reductions in the cost of a
Snickers or Hershey bar at the corner newsstand or vending machine,
it has helped candy makers offer a bigger bar at the same price.
   The near-month cocoa future traded on the Coffee, Sugar and
Cocoa Exchange in New York traded at $1,552 per ton on Thursday,
down from the mid-July price of $2,175. Analysts say abundant
supplies and rising production have depressed prices.
   But cheaper cocoa doesn't directly translate into cheaper bars
because cocoa and chocolate don't have the direct price
relationship of, for example, oil and gasoline or beans and coffee,
industry analysts say.
   While cocoa and its by-products constitute up to 20 percent of a
chocolate bar, about 50 percent of the candy is sugar and the rest
milk, nuts, vanilla or other ingredients, said Susan Smith, a
spokeswoman for the Chocolate Manufacturers Association.
   Hackettstown-based M&M-Mars, a privately-held company considered
to be the nation's argest candy bar maker, has increased the size
of two popular products by about 8 percent in recent years.
   Last fall, M&M-Mars enlarged its Milky Way bar as it had done
with its Snickers bar _ the nation's biggest seller, according to
industry estimates _ the previous year.
   Hans Fiuczynski, a spokesman for M&M-Mars, said the lower cocoa
price ``augmented and abetted'' the decision to increase the bar
size, although he said similar moves by other candy makers also
played a major role.
   ``We did what other people did, not necessarily because of the
price of raw materials,'' Fiuczynski said.
   A spokesman for Hershey Chocolate U.S.A., in Hershey, Pa., said
a drop in cocoa prices and stabilization in the cost of other
ingredients contributed to its decision to boost the size of its
various chocolate bars by 10 percent to 14 percent in July 1986.
   But the price of cocoa ``doesn't have that direct an effect on
us'' in terms of the cost of its products, said spokesman Carl
Anderson.
   Kim Badenhop, an analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets
Inc., said recent cocoa prices could be considered the lowest in
decades if inflation was taken into account.
   Badenhop predicted the increased cash flow resulting from
cheaper commodity costs could show up in still-bigger bars and more
promotions such as coupons or discounted brands.
   Retailers probably won't pass on their savings to consumers by
cutting the price of an individual chocolate bar, but are likely to
do it by offering a bigger product for the same price, discount
coupons or through other promotions, Badenhop said.
   ``We've been told through the grapevine that has happened with
some of the companies,'' said Ms. Smith.
   Consumers may see direct savings in products such as packages of
candy bars sold in supermarkets or bags of small chocolates, said
Ms. Smith.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880318-0292 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 0703EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MediaGeneral     03-18 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Media General,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sugarman Goes On The Attack In Bid For Media General</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television producer Burt Sugarman has
launched a two-pronged attack against Media General Inc., filing a
countersuit against the company and launching a proxy fight to win
three seats on the board of directors.
   Sugarman filed suit Thursday in U.S. District Court against
Media General and each of its directors, asking a judge to order
that his $61.50 per share buyout offer, worth about $1.6 billion be
considered solely by the three directors elected by holders of the
company's publicly-held stock.
   The suit also sought a ruling that shareholders, voting as a
single class, could approve Sugarman's offer by simple majority
vote.
   Separately, Sugarman disclosed in a filing with the Securities
and Exchange Commission that he was undertaking a proxy battle to
place himself and two others in the three seats on Media General's
board for holders of the Class A publicly traded shares.
   The disclosures mark the latest skirmish in the weeks-long
struggle between Sugarman and the family of Media General's
chairman, D. Tennant Bryan, which controls a majority of the
company's voting power.
   The family _ which has rejected Sugarman's overtures repeatedly
_ owns 71 percent of the company's Class B common stock, which is
not publicly traded. The 559,168 Class B shares have the voting
power to elect seven of the company's 10 directors.
   Media General has 28 million publicly-traded Class A shares,
which have one vote each and elect three directors.
   Sugarman, who controls 10 percent of the company's Class A stock
and none of the Class B, has argued that the disproportionate
voting rule doesn't apply if a holder of more than 10 percent of
the company's stock proposes a merger. Media General says its
counsel disagrees.
   Sugarman's suit said the Bryans are thwarting a vote by
stockholders, even though their Class B shares constitute only 1.4
percent of the company's total equity.
   David L. Jordan, a Media General vice president, said the
company's lawyers had reviewed the suit and ``think it is without
merit.''
   Media General sued Sugarman and his companies in federal court
Monday, asking the court to block the takeover attempt and force
Sugarman to sell his 10 percent holding.
   The suit alleges Sugarman submitted incomplete and inaccurate
information to federal regulators about his proposed takeover.
   Sugarman's group includes Barris Industries Inc. of Beverly
Hills, Calif., which produces game shows, and Giant Group Ltd. of
Harleyville, S.C., which makes cement products.
   Media General owns several communications interests, including
Richmond Newspapers Inc., which publishes The Richmond News Leader
and the Richmond Times-Dispatch.
