<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     03-18 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose in Tokyo trading today and the
stock market continued to rally as dealers reacted favorably to
better-than-expected U.S. trade data.
   After opening the day at 128.65 yen, the dollar slid under
midday selling pressure but finished at 128.35 yen, up 0.92 yen
from Thursday's close. The dollar ranged between a high of 128.72
yen and a low of 128.30 yen during the trading.
   ``The dollar came under selling pressure from exporters and
insurance companies, bringing it down from the morning opening,'' a
foreign exchange dealer said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues finished the day's trading at 25,966.26 points, up
93.97 points, or 0.36 percent, from Thursday's closing figure.
Volume in the first section was 1.2 billion shares.
   Large-capital industrials, steels and electricals fared well
during the day, but construction issues were weak, possibly due to
friction with the United States, according to a dealer who asked
that he not be further identified.
   The Nikkei index has been gaining for the past four days, and
today's closing figure was the highest recorded since stock prices
plunged last October.
   ``The trade figures were better than we had expected, and we're
seeing a strengthening of bullish sentiment'' said a broker with a
major firm who also spoke on condition of anonymity.
   According to figures released by the U.S. Department of Commerce
Thursday, the U.S. trade deficit with Japan for January was $3.95
billion, down from $4.79 billion in December. The total trade
deficit for January was $12.44 billion, up from $12.20 billion the
month before.
</TEXT>
