<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Griffin-ResortsInternational     03-18 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Griffin-Resorts International,0637</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Merv Griffin Makes Offer for Resorts International Inc.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER GILLOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wealthy entertainer Merv Griffin, who late
last year entered the hotel business by paying $100 million for the
Beverly Hilton in Beverly Hills, has offered $35 per share, or $225
million, for Resorts International Inc.
   But an attorney for New York real estate investor Donald Trump,
who controls about 90 percent of Resorts' voting power and is
offering $22 per share to take the company private, spurned the
Thursday offer as ``illusory'' and a ``blatant attempt at market
manipulation.''
   Trump is chairman of Resorts International, which operates
hotel-casinos in New Jersey and the Bahamas.
   Griffin's offer, made by his privately owned Griffin Co.
investment concern, is contingent on several conditions, including
a provision that Trump agree to vote his shres in favor of the
merger and agree to terminate his five-year management agreement
for Resorts' Atlantic City properties.
   Trump has ``no intention of agreeing'' to those conditions, said
his attorney, Jack Nusbaum.
   In light of the stance by Trump, Resorts' board decided at a
Thursday meeting that Griffin's offer was ``moot.'' Therefore, the
board decided not to withdraw its recommendation in favor of
Trump's $22-per-share offer.
   In response, Griffin spokesman Mark Gill said Griffin is
considering legal action against Resorts' outside directors for
breach of fiduciary duty to shareholders other than Trump. Three of
Resorts' six directors are Trump nominees.
   Despite insistence by Trump that he would not raise his offer,
Resorts stock closed Thursday at $25.25 per share, up $3.37{.
   Griffin said it decided to make the offer after talks with F.V.
Scutti, a major holder of Resorts' Class A common stock who is
dissatisfied with Trump's offer. Scutti owns about 5 percent of the
htel-casino company.
   Resorts has 5.7 million Class A shares outstanding, each of
which is entitled to one vote. It also has 752,000 Class B shares,
nearly all of which are owned by Trump and each of which has 100
votes.
   In Atlantic City, N.J., Resorts, which maintains corporate
offices in both Atlantic City and North Miami, Fla., owns the
700-room Resorts Casino Hotel and undeveloped real estate facing
the Boardwalk and is building the 42-floor, 1,250-room Taj Mahal.
   It also operates a casino and owns and operates hotel facilities
with 1,370 rooms on Paradise Island in the Bahamas.
   Work on the luxurious and expensive Taj Mahal, which will be the
largest hotel-casino in New Jersey when it is completed, has been
at the root of financial problems for Resorts.
   Trump bought control of Resorts when its stock was depressed by
those difficulties, and he was granted the five-year operating
agreement of Resorts' Atlantic City properties in exchange for
agreeing to help raise financing to complete the Taj Mahal.
   That financing hasn't yet been arranged, and Trump has offered
$22 per share to buy out other shareholders and take the company
private. Initially, Trump had offered $15 per share, but a number
of Class A shareholders sued and Trump raised his offer to settle
those suits. A court hearing to approve those settlements is
scheduled for Friday in Delaware, where Resorts is based.
   Nusbaum contended the offer by Griffin was arranged by Scutti in
an effort to force Trump to raise his bid again.
   Besides the Beverly Hilton, the Griffin Co. owns several radio
stations and the nation's largest supplier of closed-circuit TV
systems, which are widely used at facilities such as racetracks. It
also has extensive real estate holdings in Beverly Hills and
Northern California.
   Merv Griffin is a 10-time Emmy Award winner who served for 23
years as host of ``The Merv Griffin Show,'' one of TV's
longest-running programs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
