a.m. on Wall Street.
   Activity was swollen by the quarterly ``triple witching hour''
involving a group of expiring options and futures on stock indexes.
   Settlement of one key futures contract was done as of the
opening today. Reports from the NYSE of preopening order imbalances
were on the buy side.
   The rest of the settlement process was slated to be conducted at
the close.
   Beyond that, analysts said traders were encouraged by Thursday's
news of a smaller-than-expected trade deficit in January, with
imports exceeding exports by $12.44 billion.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Ford Motor, up [ at 44};
Coca-Cola, up [ at 40[, and Exxon, up ] at 44]. But International
Business Machines dropped | to 114\ and American Express lost | to
26].
