<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Pillsbury     03-18 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pillsbury Stock Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co.'s stock headed lower today
after a two-day run-up, apparently dampened by a report of a
larger-than-expected quarterly loss and word that the company was
negotiating to sell its Godfather's Pizza chain.
   Rumors that the food and restaurant giant is a takeover target
pushed Pillsbury's stock up more than $7 a share over the course of
two days. On Thursday, Pillsbury closed at $45.37{ in heavy New
York Stock Exchange trading.
   But that trend reversed today, when the stock fell 25 cents a
share to $45.12{.
   Pillsbury said Thursday it lost $107.8 million during the third
fiscal quarter, $50 million more than anticipated and a sharp
downturn from the $48.5 million, or 56-cents-a-share profit posted
in the year-ago period.
   Sales during the quarter fell to $1.5 billion from $1.53 billion
a year earlier.
   William Spoor, Pillsbury chairman and chief executive,
acknowledged in a letter to shareholders, ``given our many recent
disappointments, it is not surprising that we have raised investor
skepticism and questions about our future.''
   But he said he remained committed to keeping the company
independent. ``Now we must demonstrate, through action and not
words, that we can perform at levels commensurate with our
potential,'' he said.
   Spoor said the quarterly loss, which stemmed from $140.9 million
in restructuring charges to close businesses, restaurant properties
and plants, would contribute to an earnings decline in fiscal 1988,
which ends May 31.
   Two-thirds of the charges occurred in the company's restaurant
division.
   The 580-unit Godfather's chain, which Pillsbury acquired in
1985, was put on the block because it did not have near-term
potential to be ``a major strategic component of Pillsbury's
portfolio,'' Spoor stated.
   Company spokesman Johnny Thompson said negotiations were under
way with the management team of Omaha, Neb.-based Godfather's, but
he declined to comment on whether Pillsbury had received any offers.
   Pillsbury earlier announced plans to sell its Bay Street, Key
West Grill and Quik Wok restaurant chains. Spoor said the company
had received a letter of intent from an unidentified party to buy
Bay Street.
   However, Spoor reiterated that Burger King, the company's
biggest restaurant operation, is not for sale.
   Analysts had been expecting Pillsbury to announce a
restructuring _ including the sale of its Steak & Ale, Bennigan's
and Godfather's restaurant operations _ ever since chairman John
Stafford resigned last month and Spoor took over as interim
chairman.
   Pillsbury's announcement in February of lower-than-expected
earnings for the fiscal year ended in May preceded Stafford's Feb.
29 departure.
   Analysts have speculated that potential buyers for Pillsbury
could include Swiss-based Nestle SA, Beatrice Co. of Chicago and
New York investor Saul Steinberg.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880318-0299 </DOCNO>
