<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 1135EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-FrequentFliers Adv21   03-18 0910</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Frequent Fliers, Adv 21,0939</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday March 21 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Airlines Cutting Back on Frequent-Flier Programs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Frequent is full name of publication in 11th graf.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The great U.S. airline giveaway seems to be
grinding to a halt.
   Worried about the potential financial impact of burgeoning
frequent-flier programs and triple-mileage travel awards, many
major air carriers have imposed restrictions on the plans or are
thinking of doing so.
   The frequent-flier plans, which reward passengers with free
tickets or upgrades to first class after they have flown a set
number of miles, were launched in 1981 to stimulate ``brand
loyalty'' to airlines in a fiercely competitive climate.
   The giveaway escalated to fever pitch at the beginning of this
year, when Delta Air Lines introduced a new program to
automatically triple the mileage accumulated by frequent fliers.
Most big airlines quickly followed suit.
   But the U.S. airline industry is facing a staggering revenue
loss if the estimated 8 million people enrolled in those programs
start redeeming their bonuses and bumping paying passengers. The
accumulated value of those bonuses is around $1.24 billion, reckons
Julius Maldutis, senior airline analyst for the investment firm
Salomon Brothers Inc.
   That compares with total industry revenue of around $46.7
billion in 1985, $50.5 billion in 1986 and just over $60 billion
last year.
   ``The frequent-flier programs have really gotten out of
control,'' said Dan Sheehy, a spokesman for United Airlines.
``We're concerned with the direction that the programs are taking.''
   John Zeeman, United's executive vice president for marketing and
planning, said in a speech early this month that the airline is
considering imposing restrictions on its frequent-flier programs.
He said the options under review include requiring that travel
awards be redeemed by a certain deadline, and even eliminating free
trips and providing only first-class upgrades instead.
   If United decides to limit its program, the changes would be
announced in early May, Zeeman said.
   Many other airlines have recently slapped restrictions on their
programs _ most notably by limiting the number of free tickets for
any one flight. But the limits being mulled by United, a subsidiary
of Allegis Corp. and the nation's largest airline, are more
far-reaching and could be matched by the other carriers.
   ``The last thing these airlines need is more damage on their
balance sheets,'' said Peter Tanous, an editor of Frequent, a
monthly newsletter on frequent-flier programs published in Colorado
Springs, Colo. ``The airlines are scared stiff that they may be
forced to take a hit against their earnings.''
   Observers warn that the Internal Revenue Service could decide to
tax the programs, sparking a ``mad rush'' by passengers to redeem
their travel bonuses. The IRS indicated recently that it considers
travel awards a form of reportable income when transportation costs
for a frequent business flier are paid by an employer.
   And the Financial Accounting Standards Board is expected to
require airlines to provide for the liability of unredeemed awards
in their 1988 financial statements.
   The looming crisis has taken hold during an already turbulent
period for the nation's airline industry. The business is coming
off one of its worst safety performances in 1987, struggling with
unions and threatened strikes against some big carriers, and
worrying about the possibility of a recession later in the year.
   For now, though, many airlines are enjoying robust passenger
traffic and earnings _ prompting them to raise fares recently and
to eliminate some discount fares.
   Analysts say nearly all the major airlines except Delta have
started to limit their frequent-flier largesse by instituting
``capacity control,'' or reducing the number of freebies on a
flight.
   ``Everyone else is doing it; you have to control and manage your
inventory,'' said Bob Gibbons, a spokesman for Northwest Airlines _
which will start capacity control on April 1 for bonuses issued
after Feb. 15.
   Even holdout Delta has ``blackout'' dates, or certain peak
travel periods when free tickets cannot be used. Delta, the third
largest airline, also has the unique requirement that frequent
fliers must charge their tickets on an American Express card.
   ``We want to remain competitive with the industry,'' Delta
spokesman Jim Lundy said when asked what might happen if United
instituted major restrictions.
   Some airlines also are looking at other approaches, such as
replacing free travel with merchandise awards or hotel and car
rental premiums.
   While they could significantly restrict their frequent-flier
programs, the airlines are not about to eliminate them or
triple-mileage awards altogether, observers say. When the
triple-mileage plans were launched at the start of the year, the
carriers assured passengers that the popular gimmicks would be
retained through 1988.
   ``We recognize that there certainly is an economic impact
associated with the triple-mileage program,'' said Frank DiNuzzo,
managing director of sales promotion for American Airlines. But, he
added, American has no intention of canceling its program.
   Indeed, some observers suggest the airlines may be caught in a
sort of ``Catch-22'' by their frequent-flier programs, forced to
keep them because there is no way to end them.
   ``I suspect that if the airlines had their druthers, they would
throw frequent-flier programs into a bonfire because they've just
become so expensive,'' said Michael J. Friedman, a vice president
of SH&E Inc., an aviation consulting firm.
   However, he noted, it would be extremely difficult for a carrier
to end its frequent-flier program without all its competitors doing
the same.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday March 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
