<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 1223EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Panama-Pipeline     03-18 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Panama-Pipeline,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Pumping Across Isthmus Resumes, Pipeline Operator Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Trans-Panama pipeline that
carries Alaska oil across the isthmus en route to markets on the
U.S. Gulf Coast resumed operations Friday, the pipeline said.
   Pumping had stopped because a strike by electrical workers cut
off power Wednesday and Thursday, prompting the Panamanian
government to announce it was taking over all public utilities.
   ``Service was restored at 6 a.m. (EST) this morning,'' a
spokesman for the pipeline operator said. ``We actually never
stopped loading and unloading at both ends. We stopped the actual
pumping from one end to the other because for that we depend on
public energy. But we have our own plant at each end for loading
and unloading.''
   The pipeline carries 650,000 barrels a day of Alaska oil,
roughly 10 percent of U.S. domestic production. A barrel is
equivalent to 42 gallons.
   BP America Inc. owns two-thirds to three-quarters of the oil
flowing through the pipeline. The rest is owned by Exxon Co. USA.
   The flow was first halted at 2 p.m. EST Wednesday when
electrical workers joined a widespread strike against Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega, said Tim Reynolds, a BP America spokesman in
Washington, D.C. The strike cut off power to a pump station at the
foot of a mountain, he said.
   The company was taking steps to set up a ship-to-ship transfer
operation in order to put at least some of its oil through the
canal, but service was restored, making thaat action unnecessary.
   Alaska officials were worried about a Panama pipeline shutdown
because it could slow sales of Alaska crude, which account for the
bulk of state revenues.
   West Coast oil markets are glutted with Alaska oil, and the
federal export ban prevents its sale overseas.
   Chuck Logsdon, chief oil revenue analyst for the state, said the
Gulf Coast markets have been handling more than 600,000 barrels of
the total daily Alaska production of 1.8 million to 1.9 million
barrels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
