<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     03-18 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0310</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices churned ahead today, extending the
advance that has carried the market to its highest levels since
Black Monday last fall.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 7.13 to 2,093.17 by
noontime on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 7 to 5 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 770 up, 563 down and
485 unchanged.
   Activity was swollen by the quarterly ``triple witching hour''
involving a group of expiring options and futures on stock indexes
that are used in large-scale computer program trading.
   Settlement of one key futures contract was done based on stock
prices as of the opening today. Reports from the NYSE of preopening
order imbalances were on the buy side.
   The rest of the settlement process was slated to be conducted at
the close.
   Beyond that, analysts said the market was still benefiting from
Thursday's news of a smaller-than-expected trade deficit in
January, with imports exceeding exports by $12.44 billion.
   Firestone Tire & Rubber jumped 15| to 78[. The company agreed
Thursday to be acquired by Bridgestone of Japan for $80 a share, in
a deal that topped a previous $58-a-share bid by Pirelli Group of
Italy.
   Gainers among the blue chips included Ford Motor, up ] at 45;
Exxon, up ] at 44], and Merck, up 1} at 160{. However, General
Electric dropped | to 44 and International Business Machines was
down | at 114\.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.36 to 153.04. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .63 at 299.62.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 140.41 million shares at
noontime, against 110.51 million at the same point Thursday.
