<2ND_LINE>BC-Retail Takeovers, Adv 21,0906</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Editions Monday March 21</NOTE>
<HEAD>Getting the Wagons in a Circle To Fend Off Takeovers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Running a retailing company has become a
defensive business these days.
   Time was, all management had to worry about was getting people
in the front door. Now, they have to fend off corporate raiders at
the back door.
   With takeover activity threatening their independence, some
companies have taken steps to protect themselves. But others still
cling to the myth that it can't happen here.
   Two weeks ago, Dart Group Corp. dropped its bid for Stop & Shop
Cos. after Stop & Shop agreed to a leveraged buyout by Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts Inc. Analysts expect Dart, with a string of
unsuccessful takeover attempts behind it, to try for another
retailer.
   And if Campeau Corp. loses to R.H. Macy & Co. Inc. in their
battle over Federated Department Stores Inc., the Toronto-based
developer will probably pursue another major department store
operator such as May Department Stores Co. or Dayton Hudson Corp.
   Which retailers are the most likely targets?
   The most vulnerable are companies whose stock is widely held,
rather than concentrated in the hands of a few insiders, said
Monroe H. Greenstein, a retail industry analyst with the investment
firm Bear Stearns & Co. Inc.
