<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 1335EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Britain-Ford     03-18 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Ford,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford Scraps Planned Factory After Unions Squabble</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A squabble among British unions over single-union
representation at factories led Ford Motor Co. to cancel plans
Friday for an electronics plant in Scotland.
   Ford said the proposed $73 million plant could not compete if
its workers were represented by more than one union.
   Conservative Party politicians reacted quickly, accusing the
unions of causing job losses in an economically depressed area.
   ``The Dundee fiasco is a tragic return to the socialist anarchy
of the 1970s,'' said Michael Heseltine, a Conservative lawmaker in
Parliament.
   Malcolm Rifkind, the government's Scottish secretary, criticized
the unions for holding ``neanderthal attitudes.''
   Ford said that it had reached agreement with the Amalgamated
Engineering Union to represent the initial work force of 450
employees, but that the 11 other unions also representing workers
at Ford's current British plants balked. Plans called for the
Scottish factory to employ about 1,000 workers at peak production.
   Britain's unions are deeply divided about whether to accept
single-union deals and no-strike agreements, which have become more
common in this country, particularly at Japanese-owned plants.
   Union leaders have also been struggling to find a way to regain
the power they lost under the legislation enacted by Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher's Conservative government.
   Years of relative labor calm have been disrupted by recent
strikes at Ford and other auto plants, as well as walkouts by
miners and nurses.
   Ford said there was ``no prospect'' of reaching an agreement for
a single union to represent the plant's hourly workers.
   ``After very careful consideration, we have decided not to
proceed with development of a new electronics plant in Scotland,''
Frank Macher, general manager of Ford's electrical and electronics
division in Detroit, said in a statement.
   A single trade union agreement was necessary to make the plant
``competitive in its industry in cost and quality,'' Macher said.
``We had not expected that this requirement ... would prove so
difficult to achieve.''
   Norman Willis, general secretary of the Trades Union Congress,
said he was calling two urgent meetings on Monday to discuss the
Ford decision and to try to reverse it.
   The 12 Ford unions would meet the same day, he said.
   Gavin Laird, leader of the Amalgamated Engineering Union which
represents about two-thirds of Ford's more than 32,000 hourly
workers, said he was pressing Ford's senior management for a
top-level meeting at its Detroit headquarters early next week to
try to save the plant.
   However, a Ford spokesman in Detroit, John Emmert, said later in
a telephone interview with Independent Television News: ``There is
no chance that the decision will be changed.''
   The deal's opponents feared workers at the Dundee plant would
earn lower wages than workers at Ford's 21 other British plants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880318-0308 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 1402EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Telephone-Tax     03-18 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Telephone-Tax,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Connecticut Challenges AT&T Surcharge on Telephone Bills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT LAYMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State officials moved Friday to recover
$40 million they say American Telephone & Telegraph Co. has added
unfairly to the telephone bills of Connecticut customers during the
last two years.
   In a complaint filed with the Federal Communications Commission,
the officials challenged the telephone company's right to add a 7.3
percent surcharge on long-distance charges to recoup the
gross-receipts tax it pays in Connecticut.
   They argued that the surcharge imposed in Connecticut and nine
other states violates the longstanding practice of having uniform
telephone rates across the country.
   The other states where the surcharge is imposed are: Florida,
Maine, Maryland, New York, Rhode Island, Vermont, Virginia, West
Virginia and Wisconsin, according to the complaint filed with the
FCC.
   ``Since the early days of the telephone company, this country
was built upon having an average rate throughout the country,''
Consumer Counsel James F. Meehan said in announcing the action.
   ``The thought was that people in Montana should be able to call
people in Hartford at the same rate that people in Hartford ...
call people in Montana,'' he said.
   Meehan and Attorney General Joseph I. Lieberman have formed an
alliance with the state Department of Public Utility Control in
challenging federal regulators for allowing AT&T to impose the
surcharge.
   The complaint seeks to recover the $40 million collected by AT&T
so far and to eliminate the surcharge.
   The FCC allowed AT&T to add the surcharge in states with a
gross-receipts tax on long-distance companies starting in April
1986. The surcharge in Connectict was initially 3.6 percent, but
rose to 7.3 percent in January.
   AT&T is the only long-distance carrier regulated by the FCC,
although other long-distance companies such as Sprint and MCI also
add the surcharge to their bills, Meehan said.
   AT&T officials responded that figuring the gross receipts tax
into its national rates would be unfair to customers elsewhere in
the country.
   ``Only Connecticut residents benefit from the state gross
receipts tax on telecommunications companies, and therefore
Connecticut customers should pay those extra costs of doing
business,'' said Paul Karoff, an AT&T spokesman in Connecticut.
   Meehan said AT&T came up with the idea of imposing the surcharge
in the 10 states with a gross receipts tax in order to generate
millions of dollars that would allow it to reduce rates.
   Connecticut officials contend it is unfair given that the actual
cost providing telephone service is lower in here than in many
other parts of the country because of the high volume of business.
Connecticut is the 10th-largest telecommunications market in the
United States and generates about $550 million in annual revenues
for AT&T, Meehan said.
   Also, AT&T doesn't add surcharges to recover other types of
taxes it pays, they said.
   The officials acknowledged it may be difficult to convince the
FCC to hold a hearing on the complaint, particularly since the FCC
previously approved the surcharge. They vowed to take the case to
court if the FCC refuses to hear it.
   ``There are fundamental issues of how rates are set in the
country,'' Meehan said. ``If we are successful, I think create some
new case law that will have major impact on rate setting practices
throughout the federal system.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
