<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Nestle-Buitoni     03-18 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Nestle-Buitoni,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nestle Acquires Buitoni Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nestle S.A., the giant Swiss multinational
food group, Friday said it agreed to acquire the commercial and
industrial holdings of Italy's Buitoni food group for 1.6 trillion
lire, or $1.2 billion.
   Nestle said it was buying Buitoni's operations from Cie.
Industriali Riunite SpA (CIR), a key holding of Italian financier
Carlo De Benedetti.
   Under the specifics of the transaction, CIR will sell all the
operating units of Buitoni SpA, its chocolate and confectionary
company Perugina SpA, and Buitoni S.A., the French holding which
controls Buitoni's foreign operations.
   The acquisition represents the end of De Benedetti's dream of
creating a major European food conglomerate, which was frustrated
by his failure to gain control of Societe Meridionale Finanzaria
SpA (SME), Italy's major state-run food group.
   The sale also raises a considerable sum of cash to help De
Benedetti in his fight to gain control of Societe Generale de
Belgique, Belgium's biggest company.
   CIR acquired control of Buitoni in 1985 with an initial
investment of 25 billion lire, $20 million at today's exchange
rates, which was subsequently increased to 160 billion lire.
   Given the size of the initial investment, analysts said De
Benedetti had achieved a remarkable return on his original
investment.
   ``It looks as if the engineer (De Benedetti) has pulled out of
the food industry in style. The problem was that Buitoni didn't
reach sufficient critical mass,'' said Giovanni Raimondi, an
analyst with Milan brokerage Studio Aletti.
   In 1987, the Buitoni group earned consolidated net income before
payments to minority interests of $40.8 million, up from a loss of
$37.6 million in 1984.
   Buitoni produces pasta, crackers and sauces in Italy, France and
Britain. The Perugia-based Buitoni group also includes Perugina,
one of Italy's leading chocolate producers as well as Davigel S.A.
of France, which produces frozen food and food services, Olio Sasso
SpA, an edible oils group and Vismara SpA, a meat producer.
   The Buitoni group, which employs some 8,000 people, earned 39
percent of its revenue in Italy in 1987, 36 percent in France, 16
percent in Britain, 4 percent in the rest of Europe and 5 percent
in the rest of the world.
   Nestle said it was particularly interested in the acquisiton of
Buitoni because it would give it a niche in the market for
typically Italian foods, such as pasta. It also will mesh Perugina
with its own chocolate sector.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
