<DOCNO> AP880318-0313 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 1436EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Firestone 1stLd-Writethru   03-18 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Firestone, 1st Ld-Writethru,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bridgestone To Buy Firestone for $2.6 Billion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Grafs 1-10 new with Pirelli saying it will wait before making
final decision on dropping its bid, today's stock action. Picks up
10th graf: Yeiri said ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's Bridgestone Corp. agreed to buy Firestone
Tire & Rubber Co. for nearly $2.6 billion in cash, an offer that
leaped far beyond a rival bid for Firestone from the Italian
tiremaker Pirelli SpA.
   Pirelli, which offered $1.93 billion for Firestone, said today
from its headquarters in Milan, Italy, that it would not increase
its offer. Later, in a statement issued in New York, the company
said it would wait before making a final decision on dropping its
current offer.
   Firestone directors announced the agreement to Bridgestone's
$80-a-share offer late Thursday, and recommended that shareholders
reject the Pirelli bid.
   Firestone stock, which had closed at $62.50 a share on Thursday,
shot up to $78 by midafternoon on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Bridgestone and Firestone had announced an agreement in
mid-February that called for the Japanese company to buy 75 percent
of Firestone's worldwide tire manufacturing business for $1.5
billion.
   But after Pirelli launched its bid last week, Bridgestone, faced
with losing the world's fourth largest tire manufacturer, decided
to bid for the entire company.
   ``We never considered backing away from our agreement with
Firestone to become its partner in operating its worldwide tire
businesses,'' Bridgestone President Akira Yeiri said. ``The merger
agreement merely represents an expansion and extension of our
original agreement.''
   In its statement in Milan, Pirelli said it would not raise its
bid.
   ``Pirelli has always said that its offer would be limited by its
evaluation of industrial logic,'' the statement said. ``The figure
offered by Bridgestone does not fit into such logic.''
   But Pirelli added in the later statement that it would wait
until Bridgestone formally began its tender offer for Firestone
before deciding whether to terminate its own offer.
   Yeiri said his company planned to keep Firestone's worldwide
tire operations headquarters in Akron, Ohio, under existing
management. All of Firestone's North American plants will stay in
operation.
   Firestone Chairman John J. Nevin said a Bridgestone subsidiary
would begin a cash tender offer within the next few days for all of
Firestone's 32 million outstanding shares. The offer is subject to
at least two-thirds of the shares being tendered and approval of
the deal by Firestone shareholders.
   Bridgestone also has an option to acquire up to 5.8 million
shares held by Firestone's treasury, a ``lock-up'' option typically
granted to discourage hostile suitors.
   Firestone ranks fourth in tire sales worldwide, behind industry
leader Goodyear, Michelin and Bridgestone, according to industry
estimates.
   In the fiscal year ending October 1987, Firestone had net income
of $1.45 million, or $3.96 a share, on sales of $3.87 billion.
   Firestone's agreement with Bridgestone was a major blow to
Pirelli, which wants a foothold in the U.S. tire market, the
world's largest. Pirelli has a nominal 1.5 percent share of the
U.S. market.
   Sources close to Pirelli said Pirelli will continue to seek new
markets.
   ``There are always new opportunities in the U.S.,'' said one
source, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   With the failure of its bid, Pirelli is canceling an agreement
with France's Michelin group. Pirelli had agreed to sell
Firestone's retails stores division, its Brazilian operations and
some other assets to Michelin for as much as $800 million if its
bid succeeded.
   ``That agreement (with Michelin) was contingent on us acquiring
Firestone, so that goes up in the air,'' a Pirelli spokesman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
