<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     03-18 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0297</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices turned downward today, running into
some resistance at their highest levels since Black Monday last
fall.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up more than 10 points
in early trading, was down 5.64 at 2,080.40 by 3 p.m. on Wall
Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 5 to 4 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 661 up, 806 down and
479 unchanged.
   Activity was swollen by the quarterly ``triple witching hour''
involving a group of expiring options and futures on stock indexes
that are used in large-scale computer program trading.
   Settlement of one key futures contract was done based on stock
prices as of the opening today. Reports from the NYSE of preopening
order imbalances were on the buy side.
   The rest of the settlement process was slated to be conducted at
the close.
   Beyond that, analysts said the market drew some added benefit
from Thursday's news of a smaller-than-expected trade deficit in
January, with imports exceeding exports by $12.44 billion.
   But as the session passed prices fell back as traders moved to
cash in on the market's recent gains.
   Firestone Tire & Rubber led the active list and jumped 15[ to
77|. The company agreed Thursday to be acquired by Bridgestone of
Japan for $80 a share, in a deal that topped a previous $58-a-share
bid by Pirelli Group of Italy.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
.35 to 152.33. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .50 at 299.49.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 205.94 million shares with an
hour to go.
</TEXT>
