<2ND_LINE>AM-Lotus Resignation,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lotus Senior Vice President Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top officer at Lotus Development Corp.
has resigned from the computer software company over management
disagreements with the firm's chairman and other senior executives,
the company said Friday.
   Charles J. Digate, 34, a senior vice president in charge of the
company's Analytic Software Group, resigned Thursday ``under mutual
agreement,'' a company statement said.
   But company sources quoted in several published reports said
Digate's resignation was urged by Lotus Chairman Jim P. Manzi, 36,
because his brusk style upset other top executives.
   Digate, who joined Lotus in 1983 from the European Products
Division at Texas Instruments, played a key role in development of
new software products, including the best-selling Lotus 1-2-3
programs. He also helped expand the company's growth in European
and Japanese markets.
   He was assigned nine months ago to the the Analytical Software
Group, which includes the 1-2-3 programs.
   Digate's abrupt resignation raised questions that problems may
exist with the scheduled June introduction of Lotus 1-2-3 Release
3, an upgraded version of the company's spreadsheet package, but a
company statement said there are no changes in the schedule for the
program.
   Lotus is expected to replace Digate with someone from outside
the company.
</TEXT>
