<1ST_LINE>u f AM-FirestoneBjt     03-18 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Firestone Bjt,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bridgestone Plans No Immediate Changes At Firestone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bridgestone Corp. of Japan plans to create
the most-technologically advanced tire company in the world when it
purchases Firestone Tire & Rubber Co., Bridgestone President Akira
Yeiri said Friday.
   Firestone's board of directors recommended Thursday that
shareholders accept Bridgestone's offer to purchase Firestone's 32
million outstanding shares for $80 a share. Bridgestone was spurred
to make the $2.6 billion offer Thursday because of an unsolicited
offer from Italian tiremaker Pirelli SpA.
   Pirelli did not make a counter offer Friday. The Italian firm
said in a news release that it will await the merger of Bridgestone
and Firestone before making a final decision on terminating its
$58-a-share offer.
   Firestone shareholders meet in Akron on Tuesday.
   Yeiri said Bridgestone, which employs 32,500 people worldwide,
wants to become a global tiremaker with the most efficient
production facilities and the most effective marketing organization
in the world.
   ``The Bridgestone-Firestone alliance brings together many
complimentary strengths,'' Yeiri told a news conference at
Firestone's North American tire headquarters in Akron. ``Together
we have the design and manufacturing capability necessary to build
high-quality tires and to improve our global competitive position.''
   Bridgestone plans to keep Firestone's corporate offices in
Chicago and its North American tire headquarters in Akron, he said.
All of Firestone's North American plants will remain in operation,
he said.
   In the meantime, Bridgestone still plans to move its North
American sales operation from Los Angeles to Nashville, Tenn.
Bridgestone purchased a plant outside Nashville from Firestone in
1983.
   Firestone employs 55,000 people worldwide, including 1,650 in
the Akron area. The company has streamlined itself to the number of
employees needed to operate effectively, Yeiri said. No changes are
planned in Firestone management, he said.
   The two operations complement one another, Yeiri said. Firestone
has production plants in the United States, Canada, Europe and
Latin America, he said, while Bridgestone has a strong sales
network in Asia and Australia.
   Yeiri also noted that Firestone provides original equipment to
Ford and General Motors and has made considerable progress in the
international market with Porche, Volvo, Audi and Volkswagon.
Original equipment is Bridgestone's weakest area, he said.
   Although financing for the purchase hasn't been worked out,
Yeiri said he thinks 50 percent of the purchase price will come
from Bridgestone assets, and Bridgestone will borrow the rest. The
Japanese tire maker decided $80 a share would be a fair offer after
consulting with investment bankers, he said.
   In mid-February, Firestone announced an agreement to sell 75
percent of its worldwide tire manufacturing business to Bridgestone
for $1.5 billion. But that agreement was in jeopardy after Pirelli
launched its tender offer for the entire company last week.
   Akron officials were pleased about Bridgestone's plans to keep
Firestone's Akron operations intact.
   ``The commitment to say we're going to do everything we can to
keep the operations in place with everyone working where they are _
it's good news for Akron,'' said Mayor Don Plusquellic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880318-0321 </DOCNO>
