<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SteelImports     03-18 0122</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Steel Imports,0127</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Imports Rise In January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel imports rose from December to January
and were sharply higher than in January 1987, the American Iron and
Steel Institute said Thursday.
   The additional tonnage came almost entirely from developing
nations not covered by the Reagan administration's voluntary import
quotas, the Washington-based producers' group said.
   The January imports, as reported to AISI by the Commerce
Department, were 1.81 million tons, up 7 percent from 1.69 million
tons in December and up 24 percent from 1.46 million tons in
January 1987.
   Preliminary figures suggest foreign metal captured 22 percent of
the domestic market, up from 20 percent in January and higher than
the 20 percent target set for the quota plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
