<DOCNO> AP880318-0324 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 1636EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Pillsbury 1stLd-Writehtru f0180 03-18 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pillsbury, 1st Ld-Writehtru, f0180,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pillsbury Stock Slips After Report Of Loss</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, In active ..., to UPDATE with closing
stock price</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co.'s report of a
larger-than-expected quarterly loss ended a two-day run-up in its
stock price that was spurred by takeover speculation, but analysts
said Friday that the company remained vulnerable.
   ``I don't think anything has really changed,'' said Craig Carver
of Dain Bosworth Inc. in Minneapolis. ``I think this company is
still a very strong takeover possibility even though the stock has
traded down somewhat today.''
   In active trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Pillsbury
closed down $2.50 to $42.87{.
   Speculation that the Minneapolis food and restaurant giant was a
takeover target had pushed the company's stock up more than $7 a
share from Wednesday to Thursday.
   But that trend reversed Friday. Pillsbury announced Thursday it
lost $107.8 million during its third fiscal quarter, $50 million
more than anticipated and a sharp downturn from the $48.5 million,
or 56-cents-a-share profit posted in the year-ago period.
   Sales during the quarter fell to $1.5 billion from $1.53 billion
a year earlier.
   William Spoor, Pillsbury chairman and chief executive, said the
quarterly loss stemmed from $140.9 million in restructuring charges
to close businesses, restaurant properties and plants. He said he
expected earnings to decline in fiscal 1988, which ends May 31.
   Pillsbury said it would continue streamlining its troubled
restaurant and food groups and was negotiating to sell its
Godfather's Pizza chain. The company said it would rally around its
core businesses, such as Burger King and Haagen-Dazs ice cream.
   The moves, however, failed to impress analysts.
   ``Godfather's is a drop in the bucket in this whole company,''
Carver said. ``I would think regardless of what they do short of
going out and making a major acquisition in an attempt to make
themselves unattractive is not going to deter a possible raider or
for that matter a friendly buyout attempt.''
   ``The sale of Godfather's is unlikely to generate cash proceeds
exceeding $50 million. To me, investors want more,'' added John M.
McMillin of Prudential-Bache Securities in New York. ``I think
people want more restructuring.''
   The 580-unit Godfather's chain, acquired by Pillsbury in 1985,
is being sold because it does not have ``near-term'' potential to
be a ``major strategic component of Pillsbury's portfolio,'' Spoor
said.
   Pillsbury, which employs about 104,000 worldwide with 97,200
workers in the United States, had no comment Friday on whether it
had received any takeover offers.
   Analysts have speculated that potential buyers for Pillsbury
included Swiss-based Nestle S.A., Beatrice Co. of Chicago and New
York investor Saul Steinberg.
   In a letter to shareholders Thursday, Spoor said he was
committed to keeping Pillsbury independent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
