<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   03-18 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0505</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices bounced around in a narrow range
Friday, meeting with some resistance from sellers at their highest
levels since Black Monday last fall.
   A quarterly ``triple witching hour'' passed without any dramatic
swings in the market.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials edged up 1.33 to
2,087.37, stretching its gain for the week to 52.39 points.
   But declining issues outnumbered advances by about 8 to 7 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 716 up, 807 down and 461 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 245.75 million shares, against 211.92
million in the previous session. The NYSE's composite index slipped
.03 to 152.65.
   Activity was swollen by the quarterly witching hour involving a
group of expiring options and futures on stock indexes that are
used in large-scale computer program trading.
   Settlement of one key futures contract was done based on stock
prices as of the opening. Reports from the NYSE of preopening order
imbalances were on the buy side.
   The rest of the settlement process was conducted at the close,
with a few preclosing order imbalances leaning to the sell side.
   Beyond that, analysts said the market drew some added benefit
from Thursday's news of a smaller-than-expected trade deficit in
January, with imports exceeding exports by $12.44 billion.
   But prices fell back from their midsession peaks as traders
moved to cash in on the market's recent gains.
   Takeover news and rumors continued at their recent frenetic pace.
   Firestone Tire & Rubber jumped 15\ to 77} in active trading. The
company agreed Thursday to be acquired by Bridgestone of Japan for
$80 a share, in a deal that topped a previous $58-a-share bid by
Pirelli Group of Italy.
   Roper Corp. climbed 5} to 53. Whirlpool Corp. raised its offer
for Roper to $50 a share, surpassing a $45-a-share bid by General
Electric.
   Grumman, which has been moving up lately on unconfirmed takeover
rumors, rose 1~ to 25.
   Sabine Corp. gained 1} to 20{. The company, opposing a
$20-a-share offer from Presidio Oil, said it was holding
preliminary talks with another party.
   Pillsbury dropped 2] to 43. The company reported a $107.8
million loss for the quarter ended Feb. 28 and said its Godfather's
Pizza restaurant chain might be sold.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $0.29 billion, or 0.01
percent, in value.
   Nationwide turnover in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 274.91 million shares.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials dropped .14 to
314.64, and S&P's 500-stock composite index was down .10 at 271.12.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market rose
.88 to 381.58. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 299.11, up .12.
</TEXT>
