<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HousingStudy     03-18 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Housing Study,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Young Families Facing Bigger Hurdles To Homeownership, Study Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young families trying to purchase their first
home and low-income families struggling to meet escalating rental
payments are two groups which have suffered the most from flawed
housing policies in the 1980s, according to a new study released
Thursday.
   ``America is increasingly becoming a nation of housing haves and
have-nots,'' said H. James Brown, one of the authors of the report
and the director of the Joint Center for Housing Studies at Harvard
University. ``While a majority of Americans are well-housed, too
many Americans have not been able to share in this prosperity.''
   The report, titled ``The State of the Nation's Housing,''
contended that the number of Americans unable to secure decent and
affordable housing was growing at an alarming rate. Among its
findings:
   _Since 1981, rental costs including utilities, have risen 14
percent faster than prices generally. After adjusting for
inflation, rental costs are now at their highest level in two
decades.
   _The steep increase in rental costs means that single-parent
households must devote 58.4 percent of their incomes to rent,
compared to 34.9 percent in 1974.
   _Homeownership rates have fallen steadily during this decade,
particularly among young people. In 1980, 43.3 percent of
households in the 24-29 age group owned their own home, a figure
that has now declined to 35.9 percent.
   _The after-tax cost of buying a typical first home in 1987 was
$7,449, or 32.4 percent of the average annual income of potential
first-time buyers, about 50 percent higher than the share of income
required in the early 1970s.
   The study, which was financed by a grant from the Ford
Foundation and several housing trade groups, did not make any
recommendations for needed changes in government policy.
   The Reagan administration has been criticized in the past for
its efforts to scale back federal housing assistance programs, but
Brown said it was important to realize that the country's housing
problems were a result of a number of forces which have been at
work well before the current administration took office.
   In reacting to the report, Carl D. Covitz, undersecretary of the
Department of Housing and Urban Development, said that the
administration was proud of its efforts in the past seven years to
boost housing subsidies to low-income families but realized ``much
more needs to be done.''
   ``It's never been easy for the typical family to buy their first
home or for very low-income people to afford decent housing and the
Harvard study performs a valuable service by pointing up some of
the very real problems still faced by many American families,''
Covitz said in a statement.
   William Apgar, another author of the report, said that one
particular problem was that even minimal federal housing assistance
was reaching only one in four families in need.
   ``Only one in four rentor households with incomes at or below
the poverty level live in public housing or receive some other form
of federal housing assistance,'' Apgar said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880318-0332 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 0305EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FarmOutlook     03-18 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Outlook,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farm Economy Recovering Nicely, USDA Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's farm sector is continuing a
strong recovery that began in 1987 with record-high net cash
income, the Agriculture Department said Thursday.
   Cash income is still expected to recede from last year's $57
billion to between $50 billion and $55 billion in 1988, the
department's Economic Research Service said in a new outlook report.
   The projected decline will result from lower livestock receipts,
rising expenses and lower government payments, the report said.
Those will more than offset a rise in 1988 crop receipts.
   Net cash income is the difference between gross cash income and
cash expenses in the calendar year.
   ``The income and debt-service problems that plagued agriculture
during the 1980s have largely been weathered, although financial
problems persist for some producers who acquired long-term debt at
high interest rates,'' the report said.
   ``A major contributor to increased cash flow is a marked
reduction in interest expenses since the difficult 1980-83 years.''
   Economists said receipts from crop sales are improving as a
result of increased domestic and export demand for major
commodities, including wheat and corn.
   ``Receipts from livestock sales should be off slightly, as red
meat and poultry production expands almost 2 percent and prices
falter,'' the report said. ``Fruit prices this spring will be below
a year ago as larger supplies come to market.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880318-0333 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 0023EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Pillsbury     03-18 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pillsbury,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pillsbury Stock Jumps Following Rumors of Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Speculation that Pillsbury Co. had been
targeted for a takeover bid sent the food and restaurant company's
stock soaring for a second straight day Thursday.
   Pillsbury jumped $3.50 a share to close at $45.50 a share in
heavy New York Stock Exchange composite trading. About 3.48 million
shares changed hands compared with average trading volume in the
stock of 1.1 million shares a day.
   Analysts speculated that potential buyers included Swiss-based
Nestle S.A., Beatrice Co. of Chicago and New York investor Saul
Steinberg.
   Pillsbury spokesman Johnny Thompson declined to comment Thursday
on whether the company has received any offers. The company's
rumored suitors earlier had also declined to comment.
   ``Anything could be true here,'' said Robert Cummins, food
industry analyst at Wertheim Schroder & Co. in New York. ``The main
story is that Nestle wants to acquire them for $55 per share.''
   Piper Jaffray & Hopwood analyst Stephen Carnes said he suspects
the rumors have Pillbury's executives ``scrambling for an
acquisition'' to increase their company's debt and make it a less
desirable takeover target.
   The management at Beatrice, which went private in 1986, has
nearly finished retiring the debt incurred in its leveraged buyout
of the company. Under chairman Donald Kelly, Beatrice has profited
from divesting itself of some units and is said to be looking to
acquire a whole food company.
   Carnes said Wednesday he doubts that Kelly is interested in
Pillsbury for its ``breakup'' value. Instead, Carnes, a former
Pillsbury executive, said rumblings of a $55-a-share offer by
Nestle ``make more sense.''
   Analysts have been expecting Pillsbury to announce a
restructuring _ including the sale of its Steak & Ale, Bennigan's
and Godfather's restaurant operations _ since chairman John
Stafford resigned last month. Interim chairman William Spoor has
insisted Pillsbury's largest restaurant operation, the Burger King
fast-food chain, is not for sale.
   Pillsbury's announcement in February of lower-than-expected
earnings for the fiscal year ended in May preceded Stafford's Feb.
29 departure.
