<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Whirlpool-Roper     03-18 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Whirlpool-Roper,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Whirlpool Ups Offer, Sues GE in Bid for Roper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BENTON HARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roper Corp. said Friday it accepted
a sweetened $470 million buyout offer from Whirlpool Corp., which
filed suit charging that General Electric Corp. tried to
``sabotage'' the deal with a competing bid.
   Roper said its board reviewed both offers before recommending
Whirlpool's $50-a-share cash tender offer to shareholders.
   On the New York Stock Exchange Friday, Roper's stock jumped
$5.75 a share to close at $53.
   The bid tops the $37.50-a-share Whirlpool offer made last month,
which prompted a bidding war for the Augusta, Ga.-based maker of
garden equipment and cooking ranges. On March 6, GE said it would
pay $45 a share, or about $423 million, for Roper's outstanding
shares.
   Whirlpool Chairman David R. Whitwam said the higher bid
``underscores Whirlpool's determination to complete our agreed-upon
merger with Roper, despite the deliberate and heavy-handed
interference of General Electric.''
   In a suit filed Friday in U.S. District Court in Grand Rapids,
Whirlpool charged that GE knew Whirlpool and Roper had signed an
acquisition agreement and intentionally sought to block that merger.
   The suit seeks a court order barring GE from acquiring any
interest in Roper or interfering in a Whirlpool-Roper merger.
   Whirlpool alleged that the head of GE's appliance business
personally tried to persuade Roper to break its contract with
Whirlpool. The suit said GE ``intentionally, maliciously and
unjustifiedly engaged in a continuing course of conduct to
sabotage'' the deal.
   Bruce Bunch, a spokesman at GE headquarters in Fairfield, Conn.,
said the lawsuit ``grossly misstates the facts and is utterly
without merit.''
   ``We clearly have not'' interfered, he said. ``Our offer is
directly to the Roper shareowners.''
   Analysts say the merger will move Whirlpool ahead of GE as the
nation's leading appliance maker. Whirlpool has said it would
expand Roper from a maker of ranges into a producer and marketer of
a full line of appliances.
   ``Roper has a strong desire to see this combination successfully
completed,'' said Roper Chief Executive Officer Robert Cook.
Whirlpool's Whitwam also noted that the merger is of strategic
importance.
   On Thursday, Whirlpool and GE disclosed that the Federal Trade
Commission was investigating the outstanding tender offers for
Roper. Both companies indicated they would respond promptly.
   Whirlpool said in a statement that a thorough FTC review would
``conclude that a GE takeover would have serious anti-competitive
effects.''
   Whirlpool extended its offer through midnight EST March 31.
</TEXT>
