<1ST_LINE>u f AM-InternationalPaper 1stLd-Writethru   03-18 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-International Paper, 1st Ld-Writethru,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>International Paper Proposes Meeting To Resolve Labor Disputes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1 new graf for 2nd pvs ``Officials ...'' to CORRECT name
of union. Picks up 3rd graf ``The meeting ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Paper Co. said Friday it planned
to begin discussions with union representatives aimed at resolving
bitter labor disputes at several plants around the country.
   Officials for the company and the United Paperworkers
International Union said they had agreed to meet with
intermediaries within the next several weeks.
   The meetings are intended to defuse the hostility between
management and labor and set up a framework for pursuing the
company's labor problems on a local level, the company said.
   The company and the union have been at odds for more than a year
over contracts that have come up for renewal. At the heart of the
disagreements is the issue of whether local contracts should
restore premium pay for Sundays and holidays.
   Premium pay had been eliminated with labor's approval from past
contracts, but since the industry's fortunes have improved in the
last year, the union has campaigned to revive the benefit.
   ``The parties recognize that continuation of the adversarial
relationship is not in the best interests of either party and have
committed themselves not only to resolution of the current disputes
but to building a proper relationship for the future,'' said a
statement released from the company's headquarters in Purchase, N.Y.
   Bob Frase, assistant to the president of the union, which is
based in Nashville, Tenn., said the union was encouraged by the
prospect of the talks.
   ``Anytime we can sit down and talk, that's positive,'' said
Frase.
   But he cautioned, as did the company, that the talks would not
involve formal contract negotiations. A final resolution of the
disputes, affecting at least seven plants, might be hammered out
later at the local level, the company suggested.
   About 3,500 workers in four locations are embroiled in contract
fights. In Mobile, Ala., 1,200 workers have been locked out of
their jobs by the company; while an additional 2,300 have struck
plants in Jay, Maine; Lock Haven, Pa.; and DePere, Wis., Frase said.
   Contracts also are open Pine Bluff and Camden, Ark., and
Natchez, Miss., said Holly Kinser, a spokeswoman for the company.
   Analysts who follow International Paper said the talks were a
step in the right direction.
   ``It can be significant, if out of it comes a settlement,'' said
Lawrence Ross of the investment firm PaineWebber Group Inc.
   Although the company's plants have continued to operate through
the disturbances, the analysts said the bitter struggle with the
union has hindered the company's performance at a time when the
industry has turned profitable.
   ``The mills are all running (with replacement workers), but
efficiency has been affected,'' said Mark Rogers of
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   The company said it earned $305 million in 1986 and expects to
post earnings of $407 million for 1987 when final figures are
released next week. However, the company said its profitability was
below the industry average in both 1986 and 1987, when measured in
terms of its net worth.
   The announcement said the company and the union had asked
Malcolm R. Lovell Jr., a professor of government and business at
George Washington University, and Gayle Wineriter, special
assistant to the director of the Federal Mediation and Conciliation
Service, to assist in the talks.
   The stock market greeted the news indifferently, sending
International Paper shares down 25 cents to $44.37{ per share in
New York Stock Exchange trading.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
