<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Polaroid-Kodak     03-18 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polaroid-Kodak,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>January Court Date Set in Polaroid Patent Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Friday set a January court date in
Polaroid Corp.'s $5.7 billion patent infringement claim against
Eastman Kodak Co.
   Judge Rya Zobel set a Jan. 9, 1989, trial date in the
12-year-old case and ordered pre-trial evidence be presented to the
court on July 27.
   In 1985, Zobel ruled that Kodak had infringed on seven of about
150 Polaroid patents on instant cameras and film.
   In January 1986, Zobel barred the Rochester, N.Y.-based Kodak
from the instant photography business, pioneered by Polaroid.
   The damage award amount, filed last month in federal court in
Boston, has increased Polaroid stock value and also triggered
speculation that a corporate raider may seek control of the
Cambridge-based company in anticipation of a big settlement.
   Kodak, however, has labeled the claim as ``ludicrous'' and
excessively high. Several analysts predict a settlement between $1
billion to $2 billion.
   A $1 billion award would translate to about $10 per share for
Polaroid.
   Polaroid, which was trading in the low $20 a share before the
damage claim was announced, closed Friday down { at $34\ on the New
York Stock Exchange. Kodak closed down } at $42.
   Polaroid claims $3.2 billion in lost camera and film sales and
seeks an additional $2.5 billion for lost opportunities to develop
and market new products.
   Polaroid, which introduced instant photography in 1948, held a
monopoly in the field until Kodak entered the market in the late
1970s.
   Polaroid camera sales peaked at 7.5 million in 1978 before
sinking to 3.4 million in 1984. Sales rebounded to 4.4 million in
1986 after the introduction of the Spectra camera, which offered
better quality prints, but fell 16 percent last year.
   Polaroid next month plans to introduce two new cameras, the
Spectra 600 and Image.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
