<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneyLaundering     03-18 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Laundering,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vast, Worldwide Money-Laundering Scheme Charged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirteen people were charged Friday in a
worldwide, $400,000-a-week money-laundering operation run by
Israelis in the United States on behalf of two men in Colombia.
   The network laundered $25 million since at least late 1986,
mainly through nearly 40 banks in the New York metropolitan area,
Seattle, and Los Angeles for ultimate deposit in Panama,
prosecutors said.
   At least ten suspects were arrested Friday in Washington, New
Jersey and California. They included a rabbi and two former flight
attendants nearly nine months pregnant.
   According to documents filed in federal court here, Adi Tal, a
27-year-old Israeli and former El Al Airlines employee, supervised
the U.S. operations, coordinating operations in the three states.
   He reported the activities to his superiors in Cali, Colombia,
identified as Enrique Korc and Kimaro, last name unknown, according
to U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito Jr. in Newark.
   The defendants were charged with conspiring to violate federal
laws requiring that transactions of more than $10,000 be reported.
The charge carries a five-year prison term.
   The defendants allegedly deposited smaller amounts of cash in
banks in the United States and transferred the funds in the form of
checks, money orders and cashier's checks shipped in parcels for
deposit mainly in the Banco Cafetero in Panama City, Panama, Alito
said.
   Authorities refused to say what the source of the money was, or
where it went after reaching the Panamanian bank. The case was
investigated by the Internal Revenue Service, U.S. Customs Service
and Drug Enforcement Administration.
   Attorney Clifford N. Kuhn Jr., representing Tal, his 26-year-old
wife Jacqueline and another married couple at their initial
appearance Friday, said he could not comment on the case because he
had not discussed it with his clients in detail.
   Asked if the cash resulted from drug sales, he commented: ``I
think that's what they're alleging, but I'm not quite sure.''
   Prosecutors also charged that some defendants illegally
transported hundreds of thousands of dollars in cash by plane to
England and West Germany.
   Tal, who authorities said moved to Edison this month from
Woodland Hills, Calif., allegedly supervised Nir Goldeshstein, 27,
of Edison and the two men's wives in operations in the New York
area.
   Each family had access to hundreds of thousands of dollars, had
ties to Israel and had established ``nest eggs'' there in case they
had to flee, Assistant U.S. Attorney Stuart Rabner said in court
arguments.
   Tal and Goldeshstein were ordered held without bail until a
hearing Monday by U.S. Magistrate Stanley R. Chesler.
   Hedges set bail at $50,000 for Mrs. Tal and Goldeshtein's wife,
Zoe Lawton, 23, both pregnant and close to term.
   Arrested in Seattle were Baruch Zeltzer, 32; Sergio Dias, 26;
Avi Hazan, 24; and Rabbi Shalom Levitan, said U.S. Attorney Gene S.
Anderson.
   Charged in California were Moshe Begim, 25; Guy Marom, 26, both
of West Hollywood; and Alon Redko, 32, from the Los Angeles area,
said Alito. All were arrested by Friday afternoon except Redko,
Rabner said.
   Tal, Goldeshtein, Zeltzer, Hazan, Begim, Marom and Redko are
Israeli citizens, Rabner said.
   Levitan holds a ``supervisory position'' at Chabad House, a
community center for the Lubavitch Hasidic community, Anderson said.
   The suspects referred to quantities of money as diamond karats
in intercepted telephone calls, according to a Custom Service
agent's affidavit filed with the court.
   Ms. Lawton was a flight attendant for Trans World Airlines, and
Mrs. Tal was an attendant for Northwest Airlines, said the 55-page
document.
   Both have family members in Seattle and Mrs. Tal grew up in
Panama, Rabner told the judge.
   Tal and Goldeshtein were not employed but were planning to open
a private mail drop business in Edison where customers could ship
packages, rent beepers and purchase money orders, among other
things, the affidavit said.
</TEXT>
